<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Helicopter 1stLd-Writethru a0742 07-13 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Helicopter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter With Engine Afire Ditches In North Sea; All 21 Aboard
Rescued</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with helicopter forced down by engine fire;
details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter carrying oil workers from
an offshore platform ditched in the North Sea in rough weather
Wednesday after an engine caught fire, but all 21 aboard were
rescued, the coast guard said.
   No injuries were reported among the two crewmembers and 19
passengers who were on their way to Sumburgh in the remote Shetland
Islands, 150 miles north of the Scottish mainland, the coast guard
said.
   After taking off from Shell Oil's Safe Felicia accomodation
platform near the North Cormorant oil rig, 75 miles northeast of
Sumburgh, the pilot of the S61 Sikorsky helicopter discovered one
engine afire, officials said.
   The pilot radioed for help and made a controlled descent onto
the ocean surface 17 miles east of Lerwick in the Shetlands,
despite rain, rough water, and heavy winds.
   The helicopter stayed afloat long enough for the passengers to
don survival suits and get into life rafts. Within 30 minutes they
were picked up by rescue helicopters and a lifeboat, said Bob
McQueen, general manager of British International Helicopters in
Aberdeen.
   Among the rescuers were men who took part in the rescue mission
after last week's Piper Alpha explosion and fire in the North Sea _
the world's worst oil rig disaster, in which 166 men were killed.
Sixty-four were saved.
</TEXT>
