<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LastVolkswagen     07-13 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Last Volkswagen,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volkswagen's Only U.S. Plant Closing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Last car scheduled from noon EDT to 3 p.m. May be led.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW STANTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volkswagen opened its only U.S. assembly
plant amid much hoopla, but the West German automaker laid on only
a simple farewell as it prepared to close the plant today, when the
last car moved down the line.
   ``People are saying goodbye to each other, people who have
worked together for 10 years,'' said VW spokesman Chet Bahn. ``It's
... a very personal day.''
   Volkswagen cited slumping sales and increased small-car
competition when it announced last fall it would close its U.S.
manufacturing venture, once one of the economic bright spots in
this rust-belt region of western Pennsylvania.
   The plant had been operating below capacity for the past five
years.
   Layoffs of 2,500 blue- and white-collar workers began in March,
when production of the Jetta model, now imported from West Germany,
ended. The last Golf model was scheduled to roll off the 1.5-mile
assembly line today. The Golf now will come from a plant in Mexico.
   About 700 to 800 employees will remain to help mothball the
plant, Bahn said. By mid-September, about 150 employees will be
left, he said.
   The plant was dedicated in 1976 amid rolling dairy farmland
about 35 miles southeast of Pittsburgh, bringing the promise of
prosperity and lifetime employment to an area already hit hard by
declining manufacturing.
   ``There was so much room for growth,'' said John Burish, 35, of
Penn Hills, who worked in the body shop for 10 years. ``When you
came into this place you knew this is where you were going to
retire.''
   The first car, a white Rabbit, was finished April 10, 1978, but
plans to produce 500,000 cars a year using workers on three shifts
a day never materialized.
   The plant has been making cars for sale in the 1989 model year.
Thousands of Golf and Jetta models are being stockpiled in the
plant's parking lot.
   The modern plant will be the largest single vacant manufacturing
facility in Pennsylvania, with more than 2.8 million square feet
under roof. Most of its production equipment will remain in place.
   Gov. Robert Casey has said finding a new occupant for the plant
is a top priority, but no one has expressed interest so far.
   ``I think most people are hoping somebody else will take it
over,'' said Joel Suter, chairman of the East Huntingdon Township
supervisors. ``I really think that will happen.''
   Meanwhile, many laid-off workers are finding it's hard to match
the $14 to $16 per hour they made on average at the plant.
   Volkswagen has been the largest employer in Westmoreland County,
where the unemployment rate in May was 6.2 percent, compared to 5.6
percent for the nation.
   ``There are a lot of people on the streets looking for a couple
good jobs,'' said Edward Prevenslik, 46, of Ruffsdale, a
maintenance worker at the plant. ``They can go through 50 or 75
before they hire one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
