<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLdWritethru a0817 07-13 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld Writethru, a0817,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closed Hearings Set In Iran-Contra Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after pvs 5th graf to add North's comments on
political timing of his trial; picks up pvs 6th graf bgng ``In
the...''
^By JAMES ROWLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case
on Wednesday scheduled two closed hearings next month about
classified information that fired White House aide Oliver L. North
wants to use in his defense.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell set arguments on Aug. 8
and Aug. 22 on North's proposed use of classified documents
gathered by independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh.
   Gesell also denied a defense motion to reconsider his June 16
ruling that the prosecution's investigation was not tainted by the
improper use of the congressional testimony North and two
co-defendants gave under limited grants of immunity from
prosecution.
   North is charged with conspiring with former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim and
retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord to illegally divert
profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Gesell has ordered separate trials for all four defendants and
has scheduled North's to begin Sept. 20.
   North last weekend criticized Gesell's scheduling of his trial
as being politically motivated, according to a published report.
   ``We will go to trial before the election in what is a truly
blatant effort to politicize this activity and create dissension
right at the time of a national election,'' North told a group of
supporters at a fund-raiser in Dallasaccording to excerpts of his
speech provided to the Washington Post.
   Reporters and photographers were barred from the event except
for a photo opportunity with the former national security aide
according to the account in Thursday's edition of the newspaper.
   In the order about classified documents, Gesell said that during
the Aug. 8 hearing he wanted to consider the prosecution's proposal
to substitute portions of classified documents with statements of
facts the material would prove if they were shown directly to the
jury.
   Such a procedure is provided by the Classified Information
Procedures Act, which contains rules for disclosing government
secrets in court.
   The judge said he is ``particularly interested in hearing the
government's explanation of a need to substitute where substitution
is challenged, and will expect defendant to show why the
substitutions proposed will conceal facts required by the defense.''
   Both hearings will be closed to the press and public to protect
the secret documents to be discussed.
   In a related development, former CIA officer Joseph Fernandez,
charged last month with conspiring to illegally set up a secret
arms network to the Contras, challenged the constitutionality of
the classified documents statute as it applied to his case.
   Fernandez, who was scheduled to appear before U.S. District
Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. on Thursday, contends that the law's
requirement that he notify the government of his intention to
disclose government secrets tramples on his right to a fair trial.
   Such disclosure in advance of trial would tip prosecutors to the
defense strategy, Fernandez's lawyers said in court papers.
   The defense noted that Walsh has indicated there are 60,000
classified documents that pertain to the case and there may be
``thousands of additional documents'' that are relevant.
   ``Testimony of virtually every government witness (and the vast
majority of likely defense witnesses) will inevitably contain a
great deal of classified information,'' the defense said.
   ``Even the identity of many of the witnesses in the case _
witnesses for both the government and the defense _ will be
classified,'' Fernandez's lawyers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
