<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Floods     07-13 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Floods,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Killed In Downpours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains in the nation's central
and southern sections triggered landslides and floods that have
killed at least six people this week, the National Counter-Disaster
Center reported today.
   Officials said four people died Wednesday when several homes in
valleys in Chunchon were buried under tons of mud and rocks.
Another reportedly was killed in the city, but details were not
available.
   The area east of Seoul was hit by 6.1 inches of rain during a
10-hour period Wednesday.
   Several other people reportedly were injured and about 100 homes
flooded in Chunchon, forcing residents to flee temporarily,
officials said.
   One person died earlier this week in the south.
   Flood and rain damage to homes, crops, highways and bridges has
caused losses the counter-disaster center estimated at $12 million.
   The Central Meteorological Observatory today issued a new
warning of torrential rains in central South Korea as a front moved
through the region toward the southern coast, dumping heavy rains.
   The summer rainy season is expected to last through the end of
next week.
</TEXT>
