<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--People-Godfrey     07-13 0107</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--People-Godfrey,0110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Challenger' Investigator Named State Medical Examiner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Larry Godfrey, who was senior medical
officer investigating the January 1986 explosion of the space
shuttle Challenger, has been hired as Montana's new state chief
medical examiner.
   The announcement Tuesday by Attorney General Mike Greely ends a
15-month national search for someone to replace Ron Rivers, who
resigned to become chief medical examiner for San Diego, Calif.
   Godfrey, 39, a nationally recognized expert in aircraft accident
investigations, helped conduct the probe into the January 1986
deaths of the seven Challenger astronauts.
   He holds the rank of major in the U.S. Army Medical Corps.
</TEXT>
