<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosings Bjt   07-13 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Plan To Close Military Installations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon is likely to propose closing 20
to 25 major military installations if Congress finally approves a
plan to permit the elimination of unneeded bases, a key congressman
says.
   ``That seems to be about the number that have been recommended
in the past,'' Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee, said as the House voted overwhelming approval
of the complicated plan.
   The 374-39 vote by the House late Tuesday afternoon sends the
plan to a House-Senate conference committee to be reconciled with a
Senate measure approved two months ago.
   While the congressional negotiators are working out the legal
details, a bipartisan nine-member commission appointed by Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci is already at work trying to come up
with a list of unneeded bases.
   The commission is headed by former Sen. Abe Ribicoff, D-Conn.,
and former Rep. Jack Edwards, R-Ala.
   Carlucci has estimated that between $2 billion and $5 billion a
year could be saved if unneeded bases were closed.
   But Congress, worried about the loss of jobs, has blocked the
Pentagon from closing any major bases since 1977. The commission
plan was developed as a way to take Congress off the hook, and it
is strongly supported by the Reagan administration.
   The commission is supposed to make its recommendations by Dec.
31. President Reagan would then have until Jan. 16, four days
before he leaves office, to accept or reject the entire list. He
could not approve a partial list.
   If Reagan approved the list, the action could be blocked only by
a majority vote of both the House and Senate. The closings would
begin after Jan. 1, 1990.
   The Pentagon has about 3,800 installations in the United States,
but only 355 are major bases that employ more than 300 civilians,
Aspin said. He said the 20 to 25 bases to be closed would come from
among that list of 355.
   Aspin said his figure is ``based on the historical record.'' He
noted that the Pentagon in 1985 had proposed shutting 22 bases.
   After World War II, the Pentagon generally was permitted to do
what it wanted with bases, with the exception of a handful
protected by key members of Congress. The Pentagon closed 3,600
installations between 1961 and 1977.
   But things changed after 1975, when the Air Force proposed
shutting down Loring Air Force Base in northern Maine. That state's
legislators blocked the move by requiring lengthy _ and costly _
environmental impact studies for the Loring closing and all future
closings.
   The chief author of the base-closing plan, Rep. Dick Armey,
R-Texas, said the vote ``will go a long way toward cutting fat
instead of muscle from our national defense.''
   Armey's plan was rejected in 1987 by a 199-192 vote, but he
offered the proposal again because he argued that a lame-duck
administration might be willing to approve the unpopular cuts.
   Rep. Chalmers Wylie, R-Ohio, told his colleagues: ``For too many
years, obsolete military bases have been treated as sacred cows and
the country cannot afford this anymore. ... The time has come for
Congress to stiffen its backbone.''
   House approval came after the chamber, on a voice vote, rejected
a proposed amendment that would have required closing overseas
bases before U.S. bases were shut down. There are about 1,900 U.S.
installations in other nations and the commission will study them,
but will not have authority to recommend that any of them be closed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Text     07-13 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Text,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transcript Of Dukakis' Announcement On Running Mate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of Gov. Michael Dukakis'
announcement Tuesday of his choice of Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas
as his running mate.
   I think Massachusetts likes Lloyd Bentsen. And Massachusetts
likes B.A. (Beryl Ann) Bentsen. And we love you, and doesn't my
bride look fantastic without that collar on.
   It is, as all of you know because you've been here a while,
exceedingly warm. So we're going to keep this brief. Let me begin
by thanking the chairman of our national committee, another son of
Massachusetts that you and I are very, very proud of, for what he
has done over the course of the past four years to create the kind
of winning spirit that will carry Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen to
the White House in January of 1989.
   And I don't have to tell you how I feel, this son of
Massachusetts in this historic place with this city's mayor, with
my colleagues the constitutional officers of this state, with some
great Democratic Party chairs from all over the country. Welcome to
Massachusetts all of you. Welcome to Massachusetts.
   I don't know why, Bonnie Campbell, but I look at you and I think
about Iowa and I think of how far we've come and it's great to have
all of you with us. Paul talked about what happened 28 years ago.
And many of you have heard me say so many times that the parallels
between 1960 and 1988 are very close indeed. Then we had had eight
rather amiable but sleepy years of Republicans in the White House.
We had a country that was ready for change, a son of Massachusetts
_ born in our hometown just a mile from where Kitty and I live _
winning that nomination, reaching out to the state of Texas, asking
a great senator from the state of Texas to join him on the
Democratic ticket. Well, the Republicans in 1960 did what they're
about to do in 1988. They nominated an incumbent Republican vice
president. Jack Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson beat that incumbent
Republican vice president in 1960, and Mike Dukakis and Lloyd
Bentsen are going to beat them in 1988.
   Selecting a running mate is probably the first presidential act,
if I can use those words, that I will do. And I don't have to tell
you how seriously I took this responsibility. I am very greatful to
some very special people who worked with me, one in particular,
Paul Brountas, who managed this process and who did a superb job.
Little could the Greek troika in the class of 1960 at Harvard Law
School possibly imagine that Dukakis would be the Democratic
nominee for president, Sarbanes would be a Democrat from Maryland
in the United States Senate, and our counselor and adviser and
friend would not only be the chairman of our campaign committee but
the person who managed this wonderful process which has brought us
Lloyd Bentsen. And I'm grateful to all of you and to all who worked
with you.
   Lloyd Bentsen brings to this ticket and will bring to this
nation years of experience, a deep commitment to civil rights and
equality of opportunity that goes way back to the 1940s, and if
there is one commitment that defines him, it is the commitment that
we share together and that is good jobs and economic opportunity
for every single citizen in this country, no matter who they are or
where they come from or what the color of their skin. And this
year, as one of the most respected Democrats and members of the
United States Senate, he has hit a grand slam homerun because as
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee he has personally and
successfully led the fight for welfare reform, for catastrophic
health insurance, for a thoughtful and responsible trade bill and
for a plant closing law that will give American workers at least 60
days notice before they're thrown out on the street. And my
friends, if Edwin Meese can give himself 30 days notice, the least
we can do is give honest hardworking American workers 60 days
notice before we lay them off.
   May I present to you, with respect, with affection, and with
great pride, the next vice president of the United States, Lloyd
Bentsen.
</TEXT>
