<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Echoesof1960     07-13 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Echoes of 1960,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Trying Out The Texas-Massachusetts Combo That Won In 1960</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael S. Dukakis, who frequently
invokes the legacy of Massachusetts' John F. Kennedy, has again
wrapped himself in the Kennedy mantle by picking a Texas senator as
his running mate.
   ``Many of you have heard me say, so many times, that the
parallels between 1960 and 1988 are very close indeed,'' Dukakis
said on Tuesday while formally announcing his selection of Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen.
   Like Kennedy, Dukakis was born in Brookline, Mass., and he has
spent a lifetime in Democratic politics. And like Kennedy, Dukakis
is competing for the presidency at the end of a two-term Republican
administration.
   On Tuesday, Dukakis added another similarity to the list: like
Kennedy, who picked Senate Majority Leader Lyndon Johnson as his
running mate, Dukakis turned his eyes to Texas when it was time to
fill out the ticket.
   Bentsen, for his part, shares some political roots with Johnson.
Both were proteges of the late House Speaker Sam Rayburn of Texas,
products of the moderate wing of the Texas Democratic Party, and
rose to powerful Senate posts.
   In 1960, the Republicans nominated their sitting vice president,
Richard Nixon, and lost a close election. Dukakis said Tuesday that
he hoped history would repeat itself.
   ``Jack Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson beat that incumbent Republican
vice president in 1960, and Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen and
going to beat them in 1988,'' he said.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, JFK's only surviving brother, gave his
blessing to Dukakis' choice.
   ``The Massachusetts-Texas combination got this country moving
again in 1960 _ and it will do the same for the nation in 1988,''
said Kennedy, whose own early decision not to run this year cleared
the way for Dukakis to enter the presidential race.
   Texas Rep. Martin Frost, a 10-year veteran of the House who
knows Bentsen, said even before Bentsen was picked, ``I've thought
there were parallels with 1960.''
   Unlike Bentsen, however, Johnson was actively seeking the
presidency for himself up until Kennedy was nominated. And by some
accounts, Kennedy offered Johnson the No. 2 spot in the belief he
would turn it down.
   Observers with ties to both Massachusetts and Texas were tickled
by Tuesday's turn of events.
   Texas transplant James ``Jim'' Howell, a vice president and
economist at the Bank of Boston, called it ``a great day for the
Republic of Texas.''
   ``I'm absolutely delighted that Gov. Dukakis shows such
remarkable timing and judgment,'' Howell said. He said Bentsen
could help Dukakis in Texas, where Dukakis is not all that well
known.
   ``My relatives have been calling repeatedly and asking who he
is,'' the banker said.
   But there's only so much Bentsen can do for the nominee, Howell
said.
   ``The Baptists will air-condition hell before Lloyd Bentsen can
teach Dukakis to talk Texan,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
