<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeficitCommission     07-13 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deficit Commission,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Hears Few Specifics From State, Local Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and local government leaders recommended
tax increases and reforms in entitlement programs to a national
commission studying ways to reduce the federal budget deficit, but
few of the witnesses had specific proposals.
   The witnesses offered their recommendations Tuesday to the
National Economic Commission, which will present its findings to
the new president and Congress in late December.
   New Hampshire Gov. John H. Sununu, chairman of the National
Governors' Association, called for the ``reform (of) major
non-means tested entitlements'' _ Social Security, Medicare,
veteran's benefits, farm subsidies and federal pensions.
   ``That is obviously the hard political decision,'' he told the
12-member bipartisan panel, which was holding its third public
hearing.
   Democratic Washington attorney Robert Strauss, co-chairman of
the bipartisan commission along with former Reagan administration
Transportation Secretary Drew Lewis, unsuccessfully pressed Sununu
for details, saying, ``We're trying to craft a political solution
that's salable.''
   Sununu replied: ``It is one of the luxuries that I have now of
being on this side of the table, with you on that side of the table
charged by Congress to address those tough decisions, that I say,
`We're proud you're there and we hope you make the right choice.'''
   Sununu, a close adviser to Vice President George Bush, did not
talk specifically about tax hikes, but he said ``revenue options''
should be considered only after a spending restriction and other
reforms are enacted.
   He said spending on domestic programs should be allowed to rise
at about half of the rate of inflation, while military spending
should increase at 1 percent to 3 percent above the rate of
inflation.
   In contrast, John H. Stroger Jr., a Cook County, Ill.,
commissioner, called for tax hikes for the richest 10 percent of
individuals and corporations.
   Stroger, who was representing the National Association of
Counties, said various tax cuts passed during the Reagan
administration have had the net effect of reducing tax revenue by
$158 billion next year, probably enough to wipe out the projected
1989 budget deficit.
   ``Those who benefited from tax cuts should now pay their share
towards deficit reduction,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, some
policy-makers want to avoid the hard decision to increase revenues
by looking only at the expenditure side of the budget equation.''
   ``Any comprehensive solution to the deficit problem ... must
look at that terrible `T' word. Call it revenue enhancement, or
whatever, we simply must pay for our needs,'' agreed Trenton, N.J.,
Mayor Arthur J. Holland, president of the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
   Calls for more taxes were greeted by skepticism from members of
the commission.
   ``It's going to be extremely difficult for us to accommodate the
needs of various groups like yours when our fundamental job is to
cut spending,'' Lewis, now head of Union Pacific Corp., told
Stroger.
   The witnesses were unanimous in urging the commission to avoid
recommending new federal taxes in areas traditionally reserved for
the states, such as sales taxes.
   ``I urge you to reject proposals for a national sales or
value-added tax,'' said Colorado state Sen. Ted Strickland,
president of the National Conference of State Legislatures.
``States rely heavily upon sales taxes. ... The impact (of a
national sales tax) on state fiscal systems would be severe.''
</TEXT>
