<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BeachWaste     07-13 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Waste,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Outage at Sewage Plant Closes Beaches _ Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power outage affecting thousands of Staten
Island customers Tuesday caused a treatment plant to spew 2 million
gallons of sewage an hour into New York Harbor and gave the city a
new reason to close beaches.
   The outage began Monday and continued until 4:30 p.m. Tuesday,
except for a two-hour respite Tuesday morning, authorities said.
   Parks Commissioner Henry Stern Tuesday announced the closing of
Coney Island, Brighton and Manhattan beaches in Brooklyn, and
South, Wolfe's Pond Park and Midland beaches on Staten Island.
   Midland Beach already was closed because of the discovery of
blood samples and other medical-type debris beginning last
Wednesday there and on Long Island beaches, where beaches had
reopened by Tuesday.
   ``Just when you thought it was safe to go back in the water,
misfortune strikes again,'' said Stern.
   ``Once power is restored, it will be very quick to open on
Control Plant between Staten Island and Bayonne, N.J., said Tina
Casey, a spokesman for the Department of Environmental Protection.
   In another beach pollution development, state Health
Commissioner Dr. David Axelrod said Tuesday in Albany that a vial
that washed ashore last week on Long Island contained blood from a
person exposed to the AIDS virus.
   Tests showed that the seal on the vial, and on two other glass
vials containing human blood that were found on Long Island beaches
last week, hadn't leaked and allowed tainted blood to escape,
Axelrod said.
   While the results ``confirm some of our fears'' about the
dangers of the medical debris that washed up on the shoreline last
week and temporarily closed some beaches, Axelrod said ``we do not
feel the presence of these materials represents a significant
public health hazard.''
   ``While there is always the remote possibility of transmission
of the virus by someone's stepping on a tube of blood, breaking the
containers, sustaining a cut and in effect, injecting himself with
the blood containing a sufficient dose of the live virus, we do not
believe that this is a significant likelihood,'' Axelrod said.
</TEXT>
