<HEAD>Rebels Kill 17 Soldiers In Surprise Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist guerrillas used rockets,
grenades and automatic weapons in a surprise attack on an army base
that killed 17 soldiers and wounded eight, the army said.
   It said fighters from the National Liberation Army, a pro-Castro
group, and the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, a pro-Soviet
group, attacked the base in Puerto Lopex, 210 miles north of
Bogota, early Tuesday.
   Military sources said they presume the guerrilla suffered some
casualties, but no figure was available.
   Army helicopters helped the soldiers pursue the rebels.
   It was the largest guerrilla attack on the Colombian army since
June 16, 1987, when a Revolutionary Armed Forces group killed 25
soldiers in Caqueta province in the Amazonian jungle south of the
capital.
