<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Ronstadt     07-13 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ronstadt,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Linda Ronstadt Sings in Spanish on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Linda Ronstadt's ``Canciones de mi Padre'' has
brought songs of her father, Gilbert Ronstadt, and his father, who
lived in Sonora, Mexico, to Broadway's Minskoff Theater.
   It's an impressive evening, with changes of scenery, lighting
and costumes and usually a dozen musicians on stage, the Mariachi
Vargas de Tecalitlan, for 18 performances, from Tuesday, opening
night, through July 30.
   She sings with the moon, by a fountain and enters once on the
cowcatcher of a giant locomotive. She wears braids, red poppies in
her hair, embroidered bolero suits and, in a section of
revolutionary songs, crossed bandoleers.
   There are three dance couples, choreographed by Michael Smuin,
whose Broadway credits include the much different ``Duke
Ellington's Sophisticated Ladies.''
   Miss Ronstadt is no dilettante with these Mexican songs. She
makes her voice break as she seems to pour forth her entire
emotional arsenal through the words and music.
   But she remains musical, conveying urgency without being quite
strident. Her vocal tone even remains pretty through the near-growl
of anguish. In the soft songs, the sweetness of her voice is heard.
   Mexican songs, happy, sad or dancehall fast, are generally very
emotional. Miss Ronstadt has the style admirably and the audience
gets both strong delivery and an entirely musical experience.
   She sings duets and at times the mariachi band sings backup. The
dancers are spotlighted from time to time through the evening,
wearing costumes of different regions. The women go from fluffy
white to full, bordered skirts that look like ribbon candy when
swirled high.
   Ira Koslow produced. Smuin directed. Tony Walton designed sets
and Jules Fisher did lighting.
   Miss Ronstadt became famous as a fine rock singer, went on the
legitimate stage in New York, recorded standards from the 1930s and
'40s. Her latest effort lives up to its billing as a ``Romantic
Evening in Old Mexico.''
</TEXT>
