<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua     07-13 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Says Crackdown Is Negotiating Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition leader says the
Sandinista government's crackdown on domestic critics is meant to
improve its negotiating position in future peace talks with Contra
rebels.
   Adan Fletes, a director of the Social Christian Party, also said
Tuesday that the leftist government's expulsion of eight U.S.
diplomats, including Ambassador Richard Melton, reflected an
``extreme radicalization'' in policy after President Daniel
Ortega's June 27-30 visit to Cuba.
   The government on Monday accused the Americans of inciting
unrest and gave them 72 hours to leave the country. Melton left
Nicaragua Tuesday. The U.S. Embassy said the seven others will
leave Thursday.
   In Washington, President Reagan retaliated by ordering
Nicaragua's ambassador and seven other Sandinista diplomats out of
the United States.
   Also Monday, the government closed the Roman Catholic Church's
radio station, Radio Catolica, and shut down the only opposition
newspaper, La Prensa, for 15 days.
   The actions mark a sharp setback in democratic reforms made in
recent months to comply with a regional peace plan that aims, in
part, to end Nicaragua's nearly 7-year-old civil war.
   Fletes told The Associated Press the Sandinistas are seeking to
use the crackdown on dissent as a bargaining chip in future peace
talks with the U.S.-supported Contras, who suffered a major blow in
February when Congress refused Reagan's request to continued
supplying them with military aid.
   Fletes said the government could offer an easing of press
restrictions and more political freedom in exchange for rebel
concessions.
   He did not say what advantages the government could seek.
   The Sandinistas said part of an alleged U.S. plan to destabilize
their government was put into effect Sunday in Nandaime, a town 40
miles south of the capital, where fighting broke out between
security forces and some of the estimated 10,000 demonstrators at
an anti-government rally.
   The Sandinistas called the alleged plan between the embassy and
the domestic opposition ``Plan Melton.''
   Some U.S. Embassy personnel attended the rally, but the embassy
said it is normal for its diplomats to maintain contact with
Nicaraguans.
   Ortega said the decision to expel the diplomats was made so the
United States would ``learn to respect this country and its
people.'' He said Nicaragua is ``prepared to confront any type of
American escalation'' as a result.
   State-run television reported Tuesday night that the government
had determined the eight U.S. diplomats were CIA agents. It did not
elaborate.
   An Interior Ministry statement charged La Prensa with violating
internal security and national defense. It said the paper incited
violence and subverted public order.
   The Sandinistas claim La Prensa is the ``voice of the CIA.'' The
paper receives U.S. funding through the National Endowment for
Democracy.
   On Sunday, Radio Catolica's programming included Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo's homily in which he defended ``the right of the
people to civic protest.''
   Cristina Chamorro, assistant director of La Prensa, said the
closings of the opposition daily and Radio Catolica ``flagrantly
violate the commitments signed by the Sandinista government'' under
the regional peace plan and a March 23 preliminary peace accord
with the rebels.
   ``The government of President Daniel Ortega, demonstrating its
incapacity to fulfill its obligations to initiate a democratic
process in Nicaragua, has decided to silence the Nicaraguan
people,'' she said in a statement Tuesday.
   In compliance with the regional peace plan signed last August,
the Sandinistas allowed Radio Catolica and La Prensa to reopen in
October after keeping them shut for more than a year.
   The government also began authorizing opposition demonstrations,
including Sunday's rally.
   The Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate, an umbrella organization
of opposition groups that organized Sunday's demonstration, charged
Tuesday that hundreds of its members were being rounded up by
police.
   There was no confirmation from the government.
   A Coordinate delegation will meet with President Oscar Arias of
Costa Rica in San Jose on Thursday, said Alberto Saborio of the
Conservative Party.
   Arias won last year's Nobel Peace Prize for authoring the
regional peace plan.
</TEXT>
