<DOCNO> AP880713-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen-Ancestor     07-13 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen-Ancestor,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator's Relative Was Mass. Senator and Vice President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In accepting Democrat Michael S. Dukakis' offer to
run for vice president, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen referred to a
distant relative who took the same route from the Senate to the
second-highest post in the land.
   But he left out one detail: his great-great-uncle Henry Wilson
was a Republican.
   ``I'm delighted to be back in the state where my
great-great-uncle was a senator from Massachusetts and became vice
president of the United States and we're out to duplicate that
record today,'' Bentsen said Tuesday as he accepted Dukakis' offer.
   Henry Wilson, vice president from 1873-75 under Ulysses S.
Grant, was a staunch abolitionist crediting with helping found the
Republican Party in the 1850s.
   Bill Maddox, a spokesman for Bentsen, confirmed that the senator
and Wilson are related but did not know the lineage.
   Wilson was senator from Massachusetts from 1855 until 1873, when
he became vice president. Before that, he served in both houses of
the Massachusetts legislature and was state Senate president but
was defeated when he ran for governor in 1853.
   Wilson's portrait hangs in the Massachusetts Senate Reading
Room. After addressing the state Senate on Tuesday, Dukakis,
Bentsen and Bentsen's wife, Beryl, made a brief detour into the
Reading Room to view the portrait.
   In remarks to the Massachusetts House, Bentsen noted that his
great-great-uncle had served 18 years in the U.S. Senate _ just
like Bentsen _ then went on to become vice president. He said that
``sounds like a good idea to me.''
   According to the U.S. House of Representatives history office,
Wilson was a delegate to the Whig party national convention in 1848
but withdrew from the party because it rejected an anti-slavery
resolution.
   Wilson died in office in the Capitol building on Nov. 22, 1875,
at the age of 63.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
