<HEAD>Deaver Sentencing Set For Sept. 23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Michael K. Deaver is
scheduled to be sentenced Sept. 23 for lying to a grand jury and a
House subcommittee about his lobbying business.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson on Tuesday also
scheduled a Sept. 15 hearing to take testimony about Deaver's
problems with alcohol, which the defense contended impaired
Deaver's memory when he gave sworn testimony two years ago.
   Testimony about Deaver's alcoholism would be offered by the
defense to show there were mitigating circumstances to warrant a
short sentence or probation.
   A recovering alcoholic, Deaver was convicted Dec. 16, 1987 on
three counts of lying to a grand jury and a House subcommittee
about the lobbying business he formed in 1985 after resigning as
President Reagan's deputy chief of staff.
   He could be sentenced up to five years in prison for each of the
perjury convictions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Groups Plan 25th Anniversary March On Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights groups are organizing a 25th
Anniversary March on Washington Aug. 27. to focus on the need ``to
reorder the national agenda.''
   ``It's not only a commemorative service,'' the Rev. Joseph
Lowery, president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
said after a planning meeting Tuesday.
   ``We have to realize that after seven long, hard, difficult
years of opposing this administration's efforts to dismantle
affirmative action, reverse civil rights laws there is a need now
... to go on the offensive.''
   Lowery and Coretta Scott King are leading plans for the march,
which will mark the 25th anniversary of the 1963 rally at the
Lincoln Memorial that gave momentum to the civil rights movement.
   Major issues that will be highlighted under the march's ``Jobs,
Peace and Justice'' banner include employment, wages, education,
homelessness, and aid to struggling families and the working poor.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hanoi Talks Set on Emigration of pro-American Vietnamese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials will meet in
Hanoi on Thursday and Friday to plan the move to the United States
of thousands of Vietnamese detained after the Indochina War because
of their American connections.
   The two governments agreed to the talks ``to discuss the
resettlement in the United States of Vietnamese re-education camp
detainees who wish to come,'' State Department spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley told reporters on Tuesday.
   The State Department has estimated that 900,000 former employees
of the U.S. government in South Vietnam and officials of the
defeated Saigon government were sent to political re-education
camps after the fall of Saigon and unification of the country in
1975.
   ``We have repeatedly affirmed our strong humanitarian desire to
resettle those who wish in the United States as soon as possible,''
Mrs. Oakley said.
   Robert L. Sunseth, senior deputy assistant secretary of state
for refugee programs, will head the U.S. delegation to Hanoi, she
said.
