<DOCNO> AP880713-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BentsenProfile 1stLd-Writethru a0437 07-13 0940</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Insider Bentsen Provides Ticket Balance For Outsider
Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf pvs, bgng Bentsen, 67, to add that Bentsen
speaks Spanish; picks up 6th graf pvs, He is.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Sen. Lloyd Bentsen was being suggested as
a possible candidate for vice president in 1984, he mentioned to a
friend that the No. 2 job had been pure misery for fellow Texan
Lyndon B. Johnson.
   ``LBJ had been one of the most powerful members of government
when he was in the Senate and was second banana at the White House,
taking orders from Kennedy's aides,'' the friend remembered Bentsen
complaining.
   Four years later, political realities and Bentsen's horizons
have changed. He eagerly announced Tuesday he was accepting an
invitation from Michael S. Dukakis to be his running mate.
   ``We're going to fight for every state in the union and we're
going all out to win,'' he vowed in Boston, with Dukakis at his
side.
   Bentsen, 67, is tall, thin and well-dressed, a millionaire, a
highly decorated World War II bomber pilot, lawyer, Presbyterian
and native Texan who has close ties with business, a strong record
on civil rights and a history of supporting two of his home state's
biggest industries: oil and the military. Like Dukakis, he speaks
fluent Spanish.
   He is a forceful chairman of the Senate Finance Committee who is
seldom heard to raise his voice, a congressional insider who in
1976 made a short-lived run for the presidency. Bentsen is credited
with having the strongest political organization seen in Texas in
modern times; it was he who denied George Bush a seat in the Senate.
   Bentsen's marked success at fund-raising produced the only thing
approaching a personal scandal during his time in Washington.
   Immediately after ascending to the chairmanship of the Finance
Committee in January 1987, Bentsen sent word to lobbyists and other
potential contributors that he would be glad to have breakfast with
them once a month _ for a $10,000 contribution. Once the story
broke and critics raised the specter of a powerful lawmaker
offering himself for sale, it took Bentsen only a couple days to
back down.
   ``I'm not known to make many mistakes, but when I do it's a
doozy,'' he said in a statement, ``and in forming that breakfast
club I really blew it.... The last thing I want is anything that
would reflect on my integrity.''
   Until taking over the Finance Committee, Bentsen was little
known outside the Washington establishment, despite six years in
the House and 16 years in the Senate.
   He had had a stint in the late 1970s as chairman of the Joint
Economic Committee, a panel that does not write legislation, and
used the post to advocate tax cuts to spur investment and savings _
long before President Reagan came to power with promises of such a
program.
   By the time Sen. Russell B. Long, D-La., retired as chairman of
the Finance Committee in 1986, giving Bentsen a chance to push his
own ideas, Reagan's plan had been written into law.
   Bentsen often is described as a centrist. In 1986, a
conservative rating group gave him a 50 for his Senate votes; a
liberal group rated him at 45. He supported Democratic party-line
votes 46 percent of the time and opposed them 50 percent of the
time.
   As chairman of the Finance Committee, Bentsen is well-placed to
put his mark on legislation dealing with taxes, trade, welfare,
health insurance and Social Security. As chairman, he seems to push
for the middle ground as often as he was pulled toward a consensus
in earlier days on the committee.
   Thus, in an effort to get a trade bill that President Reagan
would sign, Bentsen accepted several House provisions, especially
those aimed at protecting U.S. workers and at retaliating against
unfair trade practices, that were less than he wanted.
   Republicans controlled the Finance Committee when the massive
1986 tax overhaul was enacted, and Bentsen faced the prospect of
voting to repeal major provisions _ including the investment credit
and capital-gains preferences _ that he had supported. In the end,
he voted for repeal in order to pay for a significant rate
reduction for most individuals and corporations, but he was never
enthusiastic about the package.
   The Texan has fought feverishly to retain special tax treatment
for the oil industry, especially the independent companies not
affiliated with the giant major firms.
   But his biggest battle over the 1986 bill was waged for the
benefit of real-estate developers, not the oil industry. And
ironically, it was Bentsen himself who had spurred the committee to
eliminate some tax incentives for investment in commercial real
estate; he pointed to a 35 percent vacancy rate in Houston offices
buildings to support his case.
   Under Bentsen's leadership, the Finance Committee this year has
cranked out landmark bills overhauling the welfare system and
expanding Medicare to cover some costs of catastrophic illness.
   Bentsen, who served briefly as a county judge, used his family's
considerable wealth to win election to the House for the first time
in 1948. At age 33, he retired after three terms to run his own
lucrative insurance business.
   He won election to the Senate in 1970 by unseating liberal Sen.
Ralph Yarborough in the Democratic primary. He defeated Bush in
November with 54 percent of the votes and was re-elected in 1976
with 57 percent and in 1982 with 59 percent.
   Bentsen has been married for 44 years to Beryl Ann Bentsen _
known as B.A. _ a former fashion model. They have three grown
children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
