<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--LargestAquarium     07-13 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Largest Aquarium,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Open World's Largest Fish Tank Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's biggest aquarium, featuring
more than 5,000 fish in glass-bottomed tanks as large as
Olympic-sized swimming pools, opened today.
   The Guiness Book of World Records recognizes the $24 million
aquarium at Darling Harbor in downtown Sydney as the world's
largest, with 780,000 gallons of water.
   Aquarium director John Burgess told a news conference that 1
million visitors a year are expected to visit the complex.
   The aquarium has two large oceanariums, a crocodile pool with
three saltwater crocodiles and 50 tanks for fish, turtles and coral.
   Moving walkways along the base of the oceanariums, with the
water arching overhead, give visitors an ocean-floor view of sea
life. One houses sea life found in Sydney Harbor, the other has
marine life found in the open ocean, such as gray nurse sharks.
   Only a layer of glass lies between visitors and the overhead
water.
</TEXT>
