<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Terrascope Bjt   07-13 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Terrascope, Bjt,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Propose $4.2 Million, High-Tech Quake-Monitoring System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers want to build a
high-fidelity ``telescope'' network to peer inside the Earth for
signs of big, small and ``silent'' earthquakes and to track the
drift of continental plates.
   The proposed $4.2 million Terrascope system of 10 earthquake
monitors would quickly provide detailed information about quakes,
letting scientists ``learn as much as possible as fast as possible
so we can keep the public informed about what is happening,''
seismologist Don Anderson said Tuesday.
   Terrascope would be the world's largest continuously operating
scientific instrument, said Robert Finn, spokesman for the
California Institute of Technology. Some arrays of dish-shaped
radio telescopes are spread over a larger area, but they don't scan
the heavens continuously, he said.
   The system is called a terrestrial telescope because it would
use seismic waves to make pictures of Earth's interior, just as
optical telescopes use light waves to make pictures of objects in
space, said Anderson, director of the Caltech's seismological
laboratory.
   The contrast between the proposed network of seismic monitors in
Southern California and existing quake-monitoring networks ``is
like comparing a compact disc recording with the original
phonographs,'' Anderson said.
   ``This new array will be able to detect the very smallest
earthquakes as well as the very largest earthquakes with equal
fidelity,'' which existing seismic networks can't do, said Anderson.
   ``Small earthquakes tend to have very high frequencies like a
violin,'' Anderson said. ``Large quakes tend to be more booming,
like the bass section of an orchestra.''
   Terrascope should let scientists ``provide detailed information
on the characteristics of an earthquake within minutes after its
occurrence, maybe even while it is still happening,'' said Caltech
geophysicist Hiroo Kanamori.
   Even with the existing seismometers, which record quake waves as
they happen, Caltech scientists need 20 minutes or more to analyze
a quake's location and magnitude.
   Anderson said the seismometers also would measure ``silent''
quakes, which can have large magnitudes and generate giant sea
waves, but break the ground too slowly to be detected by the
existing Caltech-U.S. Geological Survey array of 250 conventional
seismometers.
   Each Terrascope station also will be equipped to transmit
signals to satellites in the government's Navstar Global
Positioning System. Such signals allow scientists to pinpoint the
location of each ground station so they can measure continental
drift, the slow movement of the plates that make up Earth's crust.
   Unlike conventional seismometers, Terrascope also would detect
very long-period waves generated as ``the Earth rings likes a bell
for months after a giant earthquake,'' Anderson said.
   By studying those waves, Terrascope ``will allow us to get a
better look at the structure of the Earth's interior'' using
seismic tomography, a method similar to the CAT scans that use
X-rays to make pictures of the inside of a human body, he added.
   Scientists from Caltech, Harvard University, the University of
Southern California and USGS installed the first of Terrascope's 10
seismometers about six months ago in Caltech's Kresge Lab, near the
Rose Bowl, at a cost of about $100,000.
   Researchers are talking to the governor's staff, state lawmakers
and private donors to raise the remainder of Terrascope's $4.2
million cost, Anderson said.
   The terrestrial telescope system would be part of a global
network of high-fidelity seismometers operated by the
Virginia-based Incorporated Research Institutions of Seismology,
which already has 10 of the devices operating around the world on a
non-continuous basis, Anderson said.
   When information from Terrascope and the Virginia-run network is
combined, ``we will be able to build up a three-dimensional picture
of Earth's interior with unprecedented clarity,'' Caltech
geophysicist Robert Clayton said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
