<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-13 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell sharply this morning on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange but regained ground in the afternoon to close
slightly lower, and the dollar inched down against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei stock average of 225 selected shares, the exchange's
main index, dropped 79.74 points, or 0.28 percent, to close at
28,020.10 points.
   The index, which moved above the 28,000 mark Tuesday first time
in three weeks, fell 187.69 points due to profit-taking to end the
morning session at 27,912.15.
   Investors, however, took advantage of the lower prices and
heavily bought such issues as steel and ship-building shares in the
afternoon, brokers said.
   The volume traded on the exchange's first section was estimated
at 2 billion shares.
   Stock brokers said there was no particular reason why share
prices fluctuated.
   ``Today's activities reflected mixed feelings in the market,''
said a broker at a major securities firm who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``Some investors are completely sidelined until the
release of the U.S. trade figures at the end of the week, while
others want to sell shares after the 18-point overnight fall in New
York.''
   The U.S. Commerce Department is scheduled to release its May
trade report Friday in Washington.
   In the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 132.47 yen,
down 0.23 yen from Tuesday's close.
   After opening at 132.33 yen, the U.S. currency traded in a range
of 132.27-132.58 yen.
   Exchange dealers also said activities were slow because traders
were awaiting the release of the U.S. trade figures.
   ``The market had no direction all day today,'' said a dealer at
a U.S. investment bank in Tokyo, who also spoke anonymously.
``Scattered pieces of information and speculation moved the rate
briefly, but it came right back to the lower- and mid-132.00's.''
</TEXT>
