<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0500EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Doc'sFastFood     07-13 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Doc's Fast Food,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Well-Known Transplant Doctor Draws Criticism With Fast-Food
Restaurant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationally known transplant physician has
surprised some nutritionists by opening a fast-food restaurant
featuring fried foods that have been linked to heart disease.
   Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and Biscuits, the new fast-food
restaurant that Dr. John Najarian opened Tuesday in Minneapolis,
offers fried chicken, onion rings, french fries and buttermilk
biscuits, among other fare.
   ``I think it's an embarrassment. ... The problem is his name
brings credibility to the food. (People will say,) `If the chief of
surgery is promoting this food, then it must be good for (you),'''
said Bonnie Liebman, director of nutrition for the Center for
Science in the Public Interest, a consumer-oriented group based in
Washington, D.C.
   ``I'm expecting it's going to be a real lean chicken, I mean,
(coming) from a surgeon,'' said Mark Anderson, editor of the
Whittier Globe, the neighborhood newspaper.
   Najarian, chief of surgery at the University of Minnesota
Hospital and personal physician to the late Hubert Humphrey,
defended his investment.
   ``It wouldn't be like backing a cigarette company or something
like that,'' said the 60-year-old kidney- and liver-transplant
physician. ``Today, the important thing is to get away from beef
and red meat. So what we stress, as physicians, is chicken and
fish. ... It's a heck of a lot better than Burger King or Wendy's.''
   Among his friends, Najarian's fast-food business is seen as in
keeping with his personality. ``He's country. ... He likes to go
down to the State Fair and munch on doughnuts,'' said Jim Johnson,
a long-time friend.
   Najarian, as president of Cajian Inc., holds the franchise
rights along with his family for Popeyes in the Twin Cities.
   A study of fast foods released by the Center for Science in the
Public Interest in 1986 said that Popeyes' french fries had the
second-highest percentage _ 55 percent _ of saturated beef fat,
surpassing both McDonald's and Wendy's. Saturated fat, according to
medical experts, tends to raise cholesterol levels in blood and
increases the risk of heart disease.
   Najarian's son, David, said the Cajun-style chicken at the
family's restaurant would be fried in vegetable oil, which is
considered less harmful to the health. But a Popeyes regional
official in Chicago said Tuesday that Najarian had misspoken.
   ``It's not vegetable oil,'' said Richard Karlsen, regional
operations manager for Popeyes' 153 Midwest locations, including
Minneapolis. He said all Popeyes use the same ingredients and
cooking methods, but he declined to say what shortening is used.
   Popeyes comprises more than 700 restaurants in 40 states and was
started in New Orleans in 1972.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
