<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Landing, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0473,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Makes Emergency Landing In Rice Paddy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th pvs, The pilot... to UPDATE with
Japanese sources saying plane flew hundreds of miles out of its
way. Pick up 8th pvs, The paper...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A domestic airliner carrying 173 people wound up
in a rice paddy when it ran short of fuel and made an emergency
landing, an official report said today.
   None of the 162 passengers, including 100 foreigners, or the 11
crew members were injured in the landing Monday evening, the
Guangming Daily said.
   The pilot landed the plane at the Jiujiang airport in eastern
China's Jiangxi province, but could not stop the plane in time and
ran off the runway into an adjoining paddy, the paper said.
   Japanese television on Tuesday night showed film shot by a
Japanese passenger of people climbing off the wings into the rice
paddy.
   The Guangming Daily said the runway was too short for landing
planes as large as the Soviet-designed Tupolev TU-154, a
three-engine plane that can accommodate up to 180 passengers.
   The plane was flying from Canton to Shanghai when it ran into
bad weather.
   The pilot increased altitude, but his navigation equipment and
radio failed, the paper said. After flying for an hour, he ran
short of fuel and decided to make an emergency landing in Jiujiang.
   Japanese sources said the plane began flying to Shanghai from
Urumqi in northwestern China's Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region,
but diverted to Canton, hundreds of miles out of its way, to pick
up parts after developing an unspecified mechanical problem.
   Canton is 740 miles southwest of Shanghai and well off a direct
Urumqi-Shanghai flight path. It was not clear why the pilot needed
to go to Canton for the parts.
   The paper said the plane was stuck in the paddy, but did not say
what efforts were being made to pull it out.
</TEXT>
