<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PresserFuneral     07-13 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser Funeral,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Says Presser Was Courageous</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ranking member of the Senate
Labor Committee eulogized Teamsters President Jackie Presser as a
courageous leader who laughed off ``bitter taunts that would have
hurt lesser men.''
   ``He could walk in all circles of our society and never lose
touch with himself. I hope Jackie Presser will be remembered for
what he accomplished,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch said Tuesday.
   Presser, a flamboyant, 350-pound figure who molded a large
Teamsters local in Cleveland and rose to the top job in the 1.6
million-member union in 1983, died at age 61 Saturday after a
battle with cancer.
   At his death, the president of the nation's biggest union was
under indictment on charges of taking part in a $700,000
payroll-padding scheme at his local. The trial had been delayed
indefinitely because of his health.
   Last month the government filed suit to oust the union
leadership and rid the Teamsters of alleged Mafia control.
   About 800 people jammed a funeral home for the memorial service
Tuesday.
   Hatch commended Presser for bringing the Teamsters back into the
AFL-CIO fold 30 years after they were expelled over corruption
allegations and for being the first Teamsters president to appear
before a Senate committee.
   ``He wanted people to know that there were people in the
Teamsters willing to stand up and face the public,'' the Utah
Republican said. ``He believed in the labor movement and he wasn't
afraid to stand up and say so, and I know what he went through. He
was courageous.''
   He said Presser ``was a tough guy but one with a heart. He
laughed infectiously at bitter taunts that would hurt lesser men.''
   Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich, a Republican candidate for
Senate, said Presser was a major civic force for Cleveland who
helped the city out of default. Presser was vice president of a
state-appointed commission that oversaw Cleveland finances until a
year ago.
   ``I will remember Jackie Presser as a man who cared about his
city. I will miss him and pray for him,'' Voinovich said.
   Presser was buried next to his father, William ``Big Bill''
Presser, a president of the Ohio Conference of Teamsters who was
close to former Teamsters boss Jimmy Hoffa. William Presser died in
1981.
   The entire executive committee of the Teamsters, including
acting president Weldon L. Mathis, attended the Jewish memorial
service and funeral. Presser had taken a medical leave of absence
May 4.
</TEXT>
