<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0464 07-13 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Said to be Hastening Selection of Running Mate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts. Bush speech at 11:30 a.m. EDT; top expected.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' selection of Lloyd Bentsen as
his vice presidential choice likely will hasten George Bush's own
decision on a running mate, a spokeswoman for Bush says.
   Spokeswoman Sheila Tate said Tuesday that Bush, the certain
Republican presidential nominee, would meet with campaign
strategist and pollster Robert Teeter over the next few days to
discuss options. Teeter is overseeing the selection process.
   But Ms. Tate said Bush still does not intend to announce his
choice until the Republican National Convention in mid-August in
New Orleans.
   Meanwhile, Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater told reporters,
``The Democrats have thrown away the vice presidential selection as
far as I'm concerned.''
   Bentsen, who defeated Bush in a 1970 Senate race, will not carry
Texas for the Democrats, Atwater declared. ``George Bush is going
to win Texas,'' he said.
   Bush's only comment to reporters on Dukakis' selection of the
Texas senator was, ``That's interesting; that's what I think about
it.''
   Bush made the brief comment aboard Air Force Two on the ground
before flying to Cincinnati for the All-Star baseball game.
   When pressed for further comment, Bush suddenly noticed that a
guest _ the crown prince of Kuwait _ had just boarded the plane.
``Gotta go,'' Bush said.
   In Cincinnati's Riverfront Stadium, Bush _ first baseman and
captain of the 1948 Yale baseball team _ strode to the mound,
removed his blue warm-up jacket with a flourish, and threw the ball
over the head of National League catcher Gary Carter.
   Carter, of the New York Mets, leaped high and gloved Bush's
pitch.
   On Air Force Two, Bush waited until the plane was taxiing before
coming back to chat with reporters.
   ``What kind of reviews did I get on that throw?'' he asked. When
told it was kind of ``up there,'' Bush said, ``Way up there.''
   Then, before any further questions could be asked, the plane
began taking off _ and Bush rushed forward to take his seat in the
front, not to be seen again.
   Bush was to address a meeting of the Farm Bureau Federation here
later today and also was to meet privately with President Reagan.
   On Thursday, he will attend a fundraising breakfast in Baltimore.
   Aides said that Bush will spend Friday through Sunday fishing in
Wyoming with Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, who is expected
to become his campaign chairman later this summer.
</TEXT>
