<DOCNO> AP880713-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0850EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Trains     07-13 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Trains,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commuter Trains Desegregated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All commuter trains in South
Africa have been desegregated, and integration of long-haul
intercity trains is being considered, railroad officials said today.
   ``From now on segregation will be based only on economic
principles. South African Transport Services is a business
enterprise,'' said Transvaal province railroad manager J.C. van Der
Merwe.
   ``Whites Only'' signs on first-class commuter trains, which cost
about twice as much to ride as third-class, began coming down
Tuesday all over the country, railroad officials said. There is no
second-class service on commuter trains.
   Beginning in 1985, the Transport Services began integrating
restrooms, waiting areas, railroad cafeterias and other amenities
at train stations. Most carriages continued to be segregated,
although in 1985 a few first-class trains were declared open to all
races.
   Leon Els, a spokesman for Transport Minister Eli Louw, said
today in reference to the continued segregation on the country's
120 intercity trains: ``Nothing can change overnight. We still have
partial segregation on the intercity trains but it is being looked
at. We haven't put a time schedule to that. We have to see what is
practical.''
   Els said the considerations that have so far prevented
integration of intercity trains are the long travel distances
involved and the fact that ``the intercity trains are overnight
trains and people sleep in the compartments. People would be
sleeping in a compartment together.''
   One intercity train, the luxury Blue Train between Johannesburg
and Cape Town, is designated as an international service and always
has been desegregated.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
