<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     07-13 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Writers File Antitrust Suit Against Leading Hollywood
Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The striking Writers Guild of
America has filed an antitrust suit claiming leading Hollywood
producers interfered with union efforts to sign contracts with
independent production companies.
   Among the 19 defendants named by in suit were the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers, the three TV networks and
several Hollywood studios, including Disney, Universal and Colombia.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court on Tuesday, seeks a
declaration that the defendants violated the law and an order that
they halt such activity.
   The 9,000 film and TV scriptwriters went on strike March 7 over
creative control and residuals. The union has signed interim
contracts with several independent production companies, allowing
some writers to go back to work.
   Guild attorneys said they had evidence that the defendants had
``refused to deal'' with some of the 151 companies that have signed
interim contracts.
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said the allegations ``have no
merit.''
   Representatives of independent film companies have telephoned
the guild complaining of pressure to reject interim agreements,
union officials said.
   All three networks have vowed to refuse programming produced by
the independents during the strike, now in its 19th week.
   The producers' behavior ``is sad and lacks compassion,'' guild
president George Kirgo said.
   However, Steinberg said, ``The action only diverts attention
from the real issue, which is resolving the strike.''
   The suit was filed as a leading Hollywood figure lamented the
effects of the strike in Tuesday's Hollywood Reporter, an
entertainment industry newspaper.
   ``People are getting hurt,'' Bill Welsh, president of the
Hollywood Chamber of Commerce, said in an open letter to the WGA
and the alliance.
   Welsh, noting that the strike has forced many companies to shut
down, said: ``We ask you to reconvene your bargaining sessions. We
ask you to go that `extra mile' that will mean a settlement. We ask
you to end a calamity that is becoming a disaster.''
   The producers alliance has said that its last contract offer,
which the WGA rejected by a 3-1 margin June 22, is final.
   The strike has resulted in widespread layoffs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
