<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrokerageShooting     07-13 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brokerage Shooting,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gun Shop Agrees To Pay $500,000 Settlement In Stockbroker Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A store that sold a .357-caliber pistol less than
an hour before a distraught investor used it to kill a stockbroker
and paralyze another has agreed to pay $500,000 to settle a
negligence suit, a lawyer said.
   Arthur H. Katz, a former Kansas City, Mo., lawyer who lived in
Miami as a protected government witness under the name Arthur Kane,
used the weapon to kill himself after the Oct. 26 shooting at a
Merrill Lynch office here.
   In selling the weapon, the Tamiami Gun Shop violated a Florida
law requiring a cooling-off period between the purchase and pickup
of a gun, the suit contended. Katz bought the weapon 45 minutes
before the shootings.
   The settlement will be divided between the estate of the late
Jose Argilagos, 51, manager at the Merrill Lynch office, and Lloyd
Kolokoff, 39, who was paralyzed from the waist down in the attack.
   ``We're not satisfied, but that's the best we could do,'' George
Vogelsang, a lawyer for Kolokoff, said Tuesday. A separate lawsuit
is pending against Katz's estate and his widow, Vogelsang said.
   Edward Carhart, representing the gun shop, said the store denied
it was negligent or responsible for Katz's actions but decided to
settle instead of risking a larger verdict at trial.
   Katz, 53, became an informant during a 1976 investigation of
insurance fraud in Kansas City.
   The government contended his life was threatened, and he was
placed in the witness protection program in 1977. Katz pleaded
guilty to fraud in 1978 and served six months in a halfway house.
   After being relocated to Miami under a new name, Katz amassed a
huge stock portfolio but lost $10 million to $15 million in the
October crash. He was a clerk with the Social Security
Administration, a job the government had arranged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
