<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-OilRig     07-13 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Oil Rig,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weather Delays Search for Bodies In Oil Rig Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rough weather today again kept
disaster specialists from searching for bodies and capping the
burning wells of the Piper Alpha platform, one week after the
world's worst oil rig disaster.
   Police said two more bodies were found Tuesday, bringing to 22
the total recovered.
   Assistants to Red Adair, the 73-year-old Texas oil
troubleshooter, Tuesday night visited the oil and gas platform
where 166 of the 230 men on board died when explosions ripped apart
the structure, according to a spokeswoman for Occidental Petroleum
Corp., the platform's operator.
   But the spokeswoman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Adair's men were forced to return because of high winds and rough
seas in the area of the platform, 120 miles off Scotland's east
coast.
   Bad weather since Sunday has frustrated Adair's plans to clear
debris from the twisted, tilting platform and to seal three
wellheads still burning.
   Adair's team is based aboard a semi-submersible rig, the Tharos,
stationed alongside the platform, which is approached from a basket
suspended from a crane.
   Occidental said a miniature submarine which has circled the
platform Tuesday sighted what was believed to be the housing module
in which most of the men are thought to have died. But Occidental
officials said that divers cannot begin searching for bodies until
the wells are capped and the structure is strengthened.
   Occidental executives have said they believe a gas leak caused
the disaster.
</TEXT>
