<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Prison     07-13 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Prison,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Opponents File Suit Seeking to Force Disclosure of Memos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of a planned state prison in the tiny
town of New Braintree have filed suit seeking to force Gov. Michael
Dukakis to divulge documents detailing the prison siting process.
   The suit seeks to force disclosure of 198 documents relating to
the state's decision to locate a new medium-security prison on the
site of a former boarding school in the farming community of New
Braintree.
   ``There isn't anything about the process that has gone
straight,'' New Braintree Selectman Dorothea Vitrac charged at a
news conference after the suit was filed Tuesday in Worcester
Superior Court.
   Prison opponents have raised questions about the propriety of
the siting decision, suggesting that the administration engineered
a deal that could mean millions of dollars in profit for the site's
current landowners, one of whom has contributed to Dukakis
campaigns.
   The FBI is conducting a preliminary inquiry into the matter but
says it is not investigating Dukakis personally.
   The investigation has been a political embarrassment to Dukakis,
the likely Democratic presidential nominee. He has defended the
siting decision, maintaining the targeted documents are covered by
``executive privilege'' and are not public records, as the suit by
prison opponents argues.
   A Norwood, Mass., development firm owned by Daniel Striar and
Gary Jacobson purchased the land from the Seventh-day Adventist
Church in December 1985 for $3 million. The purchase occurred one
month after the state listed the land as a possible prison site.
   Questions surrounding the prison arose when the owners offered
to sell the land to the state for $9.5 million. A state-funded
appraisal of the property in 1986 valued the land at $8.7 million.
   But last week, based on fresh appraisals, the state Division of
Captial Planning and Operations offered to pay $5 million. Striar
and Jacobson immediately rejected the offer, and Dukakis has said
the state will take the land by eminent domain if necessary.
   Dukakis has said that he did not know who owned the land when
the site was picked and that he met Striar only once. Jacobson grew
up in the same neighborhood as Dukakis and has donated to his
campaigns, but both men said they are only casual acquaintenances.
</TEXT>
