<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusSafety     07-13 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Safety,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Recommends Pop-Out Bus Window Exits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Board of Education committee is
recommending pop-out window exits be required in all new school
buses, a measure prompted by a fiery bus-truck accident near
Carrollton May 14 that killed 27 people.
   The board's finance committee made the recommendation Monday.
   The accident on Interstate 71 occurred when a pickup collided
head-on with a converted school bus.
   The bus burst into flames, and the victims died of smoke
inhalation when they couldn't escape through a rear door _ one of
only two exits on the bus.
   Since then, Gov. Wallace Wilkinson has called for mandatory
inspections of such buses, and questions have arisen about the
safety of buses designed with the fuel tank under the front door _
the other exit on the buses.
   The National Transportation Safety Board will examine the
accident during a three-day hearing next month. NTSB Chairman Jim
Burnett will preside at the hearing set for Aug. 2 in suburban
Louisville, the agency said Tuesday.
   Parties to the hearing are the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration; Ford Motor Co., which manufactured the bus chassis;
Sheller-Globe Corp., which made the bus body, and the state of
Kentucky.
</TEXT>
