<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Showdown, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Selection Of Bentsen Is Home-Turf Challenge To Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf to add first reference to Texas governor.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texans took for granted their state's
importance as a 1988 election battleground long before Michael
Dukakis picked Texan Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate.
   But Dukakis' choice on Tuesday of a political partner who can
challenge Republican George Bush on his adopted home turf
guarantees a fight as hot as Texas-style chili.
   Democrats said picking Bentsen was the best kind of Southern
strategy.
   ``Democratic prospects in Texas, Oklahoma, and Louisiana will be
boosted immediately,'' said Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., a former
Democratic presidential contender.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen helps win Texas,'' echoed New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo.
   Texas Republicans, naturally, declared that the Democrats won't
carry the state, even with Bentsen on the ticket.
   Bentsen beat Bush in a Senate race 18 years ago. But the
Republicans were quick to dismiss that matchup.
   ``It's important to look again at 1970. Texas has changed,''
said former congressman Tom Loeffler, co-chairman of Bush's Texas
campaign. ``Texas is now a Republican-leaning state.''
   ``I believe Mike Dukakis made a critical mistake in thinking
Texas will bail him out,'' Loeffler said. ``It's a riverboat
gamble, and Michael Dukakis will lose that gamble in a very big
way.''
   Texas Gov. Bill Clements concurred. Now Texans will have a
choice between one of their own for the top job or for No. 2, and
they're likely to go for the big prize, he said.
   ``Given the choice of a Texan president or a Texan vice
president, the people of our state will certainly choose a Texan
president,'' Clements said.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, co-chairman of the Bush campaign in
his state, said flatly that Bentsen ``will not carry Texas for
Dukakis.''
   Some national pollsters said Bentsen gives Dukakis a shot to win
Texas and its 29 electoral votes. But they, too, called it a gamble.
   ``It's a high-risk technique. You've got to beat George Bush in
his home state,'' said Claibourne Darden, an Atlanta-based
pollster. ``If Dukakis can do that, George Bush will be whupped.''
   A statewide poll in Texas in mid-June had Dukakis trailing Bush
by 23 points. But when Bentsen was proposed as Dukakis' running
mate, the Democrats closed to just 5 points.
   Picking Bentsen ``makes Texas a competitive state,'' said Brad
Coker of Mason-Dixon Opinion Research, which did that poll. ``If
there's a drawback, it's that Bentsen doesn't guarantee Texas. That
makes it risky for Dukakis.''
   Jim Oberwetter, who helped run Bush's primary campaign in Texas,
said Bentsen's name on the Democratic ticket wouldn't be a rerun of
the 1960 success of the last ``Boston-Austin'' ticket _ John F.
Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson.
   Oberwetter noted that in 1960, Kennedy and Johnson carried the
state by just over 40,000 votes. ``And that was a Texan who was a
powerhouse,'' he said.
   Still, the Democrats said Dukakis' choice amounted to the best
Southern strategy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
