<2ND_LINE>PM-Ferry Capsize,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Capsizes, Two Dozen Hurled Into Colorado River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUGHLIN, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ferry boat hit another vessel and
capsized, spilling 26 gamblers and casino workers into the Colorado
River, authorities said.
   At least two dozen people were injured, none seriously, in the
accident Tuesday night, said Janet Smith, a spokeswoman for Mercy
Ambulance.
   The pontoon ferry boat lost power while docking in Bullhead
City, Ariz., and struck an unoccupied pleasure craft, said Las
Vegas Metro Police spokesman Robert Nixon.
   The 25-foot ferry boat operated by Edgewater Casino carries
gamblers and casino workers between Bullhead City on the river's
eastern shore and this gambling resort on the other side, 90 miles
southeast of Las Vegas. The river is about 100 yards wide.
   Eighteen divers and officers from the Nevada Fish and Game
Department helped rescue the passengers, Nixon said.
   Twenty-two were taken to Bullhead Community Hospital and treated
for hypothermia, head and back injuries and shock, said
administrator Joe Harrington. Most were released after treatment.
   Mojave Valley Medical Center also received some passengers but
refused to give details.
