<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BentsenReaction 1stLd-Writethru a0451 07-13 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen Reaction, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Dems Hail Bentsen As Winning Coalition Builder</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 3 grafs after 9th graf bgng: ``He knows ... to UPDATE
with Mondale comments. Picks up 10th graf pvs bgng: Said Paul ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the highest praise of Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen's selection as running mate for Democrat Michael S. Dukakis
came from a Republican colleague, but a fellow Texan disputed
Bentsen's impact on the race.
   Dukakis ``couldn't have picked a better man,'' said Senate
Minority Leader Bob Dole, who ran unsuccessfully for his party's
nomination this year. ``It's an excellent choice and I think that
will come from both sides of the aisle.''
   Fellow Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, a Republican, said Bentsen still
will not carry Texas for the Democrats.
   ``I don't think Republicans are going to run against Lloyd
Bentsen,'' Gramm said Tuesday. ``Republicans are going to run
against Michael Dukakis. The distinctions between George Bush and
Michael Dukakis are so clear that Bentsen is not an issue.''
   Gramm, like many other Republicans, passed up opportunities to
criticize Bentsen's record, a record that includes expertise on
taxes, trade, health and welfare.
   Vice President George Bush also claims Texas as home base, and
Gramm said that given a choice between electing a Texan to one of
the nation's two top positions, Texans will choose the presidency
every time.
   Democrats in Congress and elsewhere hailed Bentsen as a moderate
coalition builder who will give the ticket a strong chance in the
South and across the nation.
   Bentsen has the added advantage, they said, of having entered
the Senate in 1970 by beating Bush, then a Texas Republican
congressman.
   ``He knows how to beat George Bush,'' said Sen. Barbara
Mikulski, D-Md. ``He did just that in 1970.''
   Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale, the 1984 Democratic
presidential nominee, said Dukakis made a ``superb choice.''
   ``Senator Bentsen is regarded as one of the nation's top experts
in financial and economic affairs and is one of the most thoughtful
minds in international security and defense matters,'' Mondale said
Tuesday.
   ``More than that, he has been a source of good sense, moderation
and decency throughout his years of public life,'' he said. ``He
will make an excellent vice president and Governor Dukakis deserves
a straight A on his first choice.''
   Said Paul Simon, D-Ill, a former Democratic presidential
candidate: ``Democratic prospects in Texas, Oklahoma, and Louisiana
will be boosted immediately, and when the American people get to
know Lloyd Bentsen, it will strengthen the ticket everywhere.
   ``More important than anything else, if there should be a
tragedy, Lloyd Bentsen would make a superb president.''
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, who had been on Dukakis' short list of
prospective running mates, said he heard of the choice with ``some
regrets at not being selected.''
   ``Disappointed would be overstating it,'' said Glenn.
   Responding to questions, Glenn said Jesse Jackson has made a
valuable contribution to American politics, assuring that no black
person will ever again be ruled out of presidential politics merely
because of his race.
   But some of Jackson's supporters described the choice as a
``slap in the face.''
   ``It's safe to say there are many, many people in this country
who are enthusiastic supporters of Jesse Jackson who will look with
disfavor and pain at this nomination,'' said Rep. Ronald Dellums,
D-Calif.
   Dellums said choosing Bentsen creates the impression that
Dukakis either walked away from Jackson and his backers or chose to
ignore ``the issue of race.''
   But other Democrats disagreed.
   ``I think on the issues of the big constituencies Lloyd Bentsen
has been right: right on civil rights, right on womens' issues ...
He is acceptable to blacks and business and that's the key,'' said
Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La.. ``You've got to build a coalition
broad enough to get elected and Lloyd Bentsen will help to do
that.''
   Union activists also praised Bentsen, saying he has recently
shored up a relatively poor labor record with his deft handling of
legislation on trade and mandatory notice of plant closings and
massive layoffs.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said the choice gives the
nation the same ``Massachusetts-Texas combination'' that carried
President John F. Kennedy to victory in 1960 after his selection of
Texan Lyndon B. Johnson as his running mate.
</TEXT>
