<2ND_LINE>PM-Delvalle-Miami,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama President in Miami For Medical Checkup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Panamanian President Arturo Delvalle has
flown here for a routine heart checkup but is expected to go back
in a few days to ``return Panama to democracy,'' said the nation's
ambassador to the United States.
   Delvalle had heart bypass surgery about 10 years ago and is
supposed to have a checkup every six months, Ambassador Juan Sosa
said in Washington on Tuesday.
   He said the president is not hospitalized and was being tested
by his private physician at an undisclosed location.
   The U.S. government recognizes Delvalle as his nation's chief of
state despite his February removal by Panama's military ruler, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Delvalle has been in hiding in Panama with the help of the
United States since Noriega replaced him with Manuel Solis Palma.
   Delvalle arrived secretly on Sunday, according to Panama's Miami
Consul Roberto Dominguez. For security reasons, officials would not
say how or when Delvalle was leaving.
   In Panama, the pro-government La Republica newspaper said
Delvalle suffered a minor heart attack Monday and flew abroad for
treatment.
