<HEAD>Police Foil Theft Involving U.S. Commisarry Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today foiled an attempt to
steal about $75,000 worth of goods from a U.S. military truck en
route to the U.S-run Clark Air Base, the Philippine News Agency
said.
   The state-run agency quoted police as saying three U.S.
Commissary trucks have been robbed since January.
   Maj. Efren Alamares, who led the police raid, said officers
received an intelligence report about the plan and set up a
surveillance team on a highway leading to Angeles City, about 50
miles north of Manila, where Clark is located.
   The truck drove from Subic Bay Naval Base, about 35 miles
southwest of Angeles.
   But about 12 miles before reaching Angeles, the truck left the
highway and entered a private compound where the goods were
supposed to be transferred to a waiting truck, police said.
   Officers moved in and arrested the truck driver. The rest of the
would-be thieves escaped, they said.
   The truck carried American cigarettes, canned goods and other
groceries.
