<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     07-13 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conscientious Objectors Charge Government Harrassment, Troops
Dynamite Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Israeli reserve soldiers who refuse
to serve in the occupied territories today accused the government
of harassing them with security checks and urged the attorney
general to drop an inquiry into their activities.
   A spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, whose office
oversees the Shin Bet security service, said he could not respond
to the charges of unusual security checks and mail tampering. But
he said the conscientious objectors were engaged in clearly illegal
activity.
   ``There are democratic ways in Israel to express one's opinion,
and engage in political struggle,'' said the spokesman, Avi Pazner.
``The problem with these people is they think they can be their own
judges and do whatever they like.''
   About 600 soldiers who refuse to serve in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip belong to a group calling itself Yesh Gvul, Hebrew
for ``There is a Limit.'' Twenty-nine have been jailed on charges
of disobeying orders.
   The latest to be sentenced was Capt. Nissim Kedem, 33, a member
of a tank division who today was ordered to serve a 21-day term,
Yesh Gvul spokesman Ronen Shamir said.
   Attorney General Yosef Harish has ordered a police inquiry into
whether Yesh Gvul members are guilty of incitement for encouraging
reserve soldiers to refuse orders to serve in the territories.
   Yesh Gvul spokesman Shamir said tactics used against his group
included a rigorous security check of a group member returning to
Israel from abroad and a case where 20 letters the group mailed to
other countries were returned with the envelopes opened.
   ``This indicates there is a storehouse of data on members of the
group that marks them as posing a danger to the country,'' Shamir
said.
   Also today, Israeli troops dynamited the homes of two
Palestinians suspected of hurling firebombs at military patrols in
the occupied West Bank. The sound of the explosions was broadcast
on Israel army radio.
   The predawn demolitions were in the villages of Ras Karkar and
Janyeh near Ramallah, north of Jerusalem. An army spokesman said
the homes belonged to suspects in a June 9 firebombing in which two
army officers were badly burned.
   The home of a fourth suspect in the firebombing was sealed, the
army said.
   Three other homes in Atil, near the northern West Bank city of
Tulkarem, also were sealed shut, the army said, adding that the
homes belonged to Palestinians suspected of burning and stoning
buses in April.
   The army recently has issued troops with new fireproof suits
because of the frequency of firebomb attacks in the occupied
territories, army radio said.
</TEXT>
