<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0584-91-97 07-13 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584-91-97,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Azerbaijan Cancels Secession Declaration of Disputed Region</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: COMBINES urgent series.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leadership of Azerbaijan annulled
Nagorno-Karabakh's decision to secede from the republic and accused
officials in the disputed region of breaking the law and defying
higher authorities, Tass said today.
   The official news agency said the Presidium, or executive
committee, of Azerbaijan's parliament met Tuesday night, a few
hours after the secession declaration by Nagorno-Karabakh's
legislature.
   The legislature ``failed to secure strict compliance with
principles of legality'' and ``openly encroached on the
national-state composition of the republic,'' Tass quoted the
Azerbaijan Presidium as saying in a resolution.
   Tass said the Presidium proclaimed Nagorno-Karabakh's
declaration of secession ``null and void and revoked it.''
   Armenians have been pressing for five months for
Nagorno-Karabakh to be annexed to the republic of Armenia.
Nagorno-Karabakh, a mountainous region of 160,000 people, is mainly
Armenian.
   The campaign has brought Nagorno-Karabakh's Armenians into
direct confrontation with central authorities in Moscow and with
Azerbaijani authorities, who oppose any change in the territorial
status of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   In February, the ethnic tension led to riots in the Azerbaijan
city of Sumgait. At least 32 people were killed.
   Nagorno-Karabakh's declaration of secession was the first such
action in the 70 years of Soviet history. It immediately raised
constitutional and legal questions. Dissident historian Roy
Medvedev told The Associated Press the action was clearly
unconstitutional and illegal.
   The Soviet Constitution gives citizens the right to
self-determination, but it requires a republic's consent for any
proposed changes in its boundaries. Nagorno-Karabakh has been an
autonomous region of mostly Moslem Azerbaijan since 1923, even
though more than three-quarters of its residents are ethnic
Armenians, who are predominantly Christian. Armenians consider
Nagorno-Karabakh to be part of their ancestral homeland.
   On Feb. 20, Nagorno-Karabakh's legislature asked the Azerbaijani
and Armenian governments to approve transfer to Armenia. Armenia's
legislature agreed June 15, but Azerbaijan's said no two days later.
   The Nagorno-Karabakh legislature announced Tuesday the area was
being renamed the Artsakh Autonomous Region of Armenia.
   Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh and Armenia have been striking and
holding street rallies sporadically since February. Today, Tass
said the Nagorno-Karabakh legislature had asked residents to return
to work, but that in the region's main city, Stepanakert, ``all
industrial enterprises in the city remained idle on July 13, public
and city transport did not function, all shops selling manufactured
goods were closed, so were consumer service outlets.''
   A worker at the Stepanakert radio station said the city was
suffering as a result of the strike.
   ``The food situation has become very critical,'' said the worker
in a telephone interview. He refused to be identified. ``We are
producing our own bread and milk, but other foodstuffs are lacking.
Nothing is coming to us from Azerbaijan.''
   He said troops were deployed on city streets and in other parts
of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   In Baku, the Azerbaijani capital, a reporter for the republic's
official news agency said the dispute was being resolved according
to the new policies of Soviet Communist Party general secretary
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``It's being decided in a democratic way. Some people say one
thing; others say something else,'' the reporter said in a
telephone interview. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Gorbachev has said more attention should be paid to the concerns
of the Soviet Union's more than 100 national groups but that some
are abusing the new openness of society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
