<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--Guardianship     07-13 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Guardianship,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guardianship Bill Passed, Sent To Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation expanding the discretion of
judges in cases involving elderly and minor guardianships awaits
action by Gov. Henry Bellmon.
   The Legislature passed the bill Tuesday as it wrapped up the
1988 session.
   The measure would give judges more discretion in determining
which wards need full-time guardians. It also brings into one
statute all laws on guardianship.
   Rep. Don McCorkell said judges, lawyers and advocates for the
elderly had worked to develop a compromise that was fair to
guardians and protected the rights of wards. Opponents in the House
argued the bill was too complex and cumbersome.
   Oklahoma's guardianship laws have not been substantially changed
since the 1950s.
   An Associated Press series examined guardianship laws nationwide
in 1987 and found a network of overburdened courts that routinely
fail to monitor wards under their jurisdiction.
</TEXT>
