<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeanFieldWar     07-13 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bean Field War,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer Blasts Into Lake To Irrigate Bean Crop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAPEER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer who dynamited his way into a
private lake to get water for his bean crop said today he has
stopped pumping from the lake.
   Gary Bulzan said he turned off the pump Tuesday, shortly before
a judge barred him from taking water from Lake Pleasant. The
pumping angered many of the 200 families who own homes around the
lake, 50 miles north of Detroit.
   Bulzan blasted a hole last week near the 130-acre lake, allowed
the crater to fill and began pumping water to a sprinkler that
sprayed his adjacent 75-acre field.
   Sgt. Tim Burke of the Department of Natural Resources said
Bulzan failed to apply for a permit to pump the water but probably
would have received one if he had.
   Dorothy Nadrowski, whose home overlooks the lake, said the pump
ran constantly for three days. One neighbor said the lake dropped
more than an inch since the pumping began.
   Bulzan's attorney, Emory Clark, said the farmer was just trying
to save his crop from the drought.
   ``If the water is up to your bellybutton now and it goes down an
inch, I can't see where that matters more than a farmer who is
paying $100 an acre to farm the land and stands to lose his whole
crop,'' Clark said.
</TEXT>
