<HEAD>Conductor Mehta Appeals for Release of Soviet Refusenik</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zubin Mehta, the conductor of the New
York and Israeli philharmonic orchestras, said today he has
appealed to Soviet officials to release a woman denied permission
to immigrate to Israel for 14 years.
   Mehta told reporters he met the woman, Elena Keiss-Kuna of
Leningrad, during a recent tour of the Soviet Union with the New
York Philharmonic.
   He said he also asked Secretary of State George P. Shultz and
oil magnate Armand Hammer to intervene on Mrs. Keiss-Kuna's behalf.
``If anyone can gain her release, those two people can,'' Mehta
said at a news conference.
   Mrs. Keiss-Kuna's sister, Anna Rosnovsky, immigrated to Israel
14 years ago and is a violinist in the Israeli Philharmonic
Orchestra. Soviet authorities denied Mrs. Keiss-Kuna an exit visa
at the time, contending her job as a chemical engineer gave her
access to state secrets.
   ``When I spoke to Soviet officials, I told them the only state
secrets this woman knows is the recipe for borscht,'' Mehta said.
