<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-SovietBase     07-13 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Soviet Base,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Publishes Satellite Photo of Key Soviet Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane's Defense Weekly today published a clearly
detailed satellite photograph which it said shows the headquarters
of the Soviet Northern Fleet at Severomorsk, in the northwestern
Soviet Union near northern Finland.
   The photograph in the respected military affairs weekly shows
the main docking area for Kiev class aircraft carriers and battle
cruisers as well as the naval aviation airfield at Severomorsk,
which lies on the Kola peninsula near Murmansk.
   Jane's said Severomorsk is the largest of nine main Northern
Fleet surface vessel bases, but is only ``a small fraction of the
massive Soviet military presence on the Kola,'' making the
peninsula ``home for the densest gathering of military
installations in the world.''
   It said the photo was taken by the French SPOT satellite and
enhanced by computer techniques. It did not say how it obtained the
photograph, or on what date it was taken.
   The photo clearly shows an aircraft carrier-sized vessel docked
in the bay, and smaller warships berthed perpendicular to the
coastline.
   Inland, a 4,000-yard landing strip is visible, surrounded by
what Jane's described as a ``characteristic configuration of
hardened aircraft shelters around the base.''
</TEXT>
