<1ST_LINE>u i PM-British-Blast 4thLd-Writethru a0552 07-13 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-British-Blast, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0552,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two IRA Bombs Injure Nine British Soldiers At Barracks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with police saying explosion
caused bt two bombs sted one. Pick up 3rd pvs, At about... SUBS 6th
pvs to conform. Pick up 7th pvs, The building...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ERICH REIMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUISBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs blasted through a
British army barracks early today, tearing off part of the roof and
injuring nine soldiers. The Irish Republican Army claimed
responsibility.
   Police said the bombs were placed side by side near an outside
wall of the soldiers' living quarters and tore a 3-by-6-foot hole
in it.
   Police originally said the blast was caused by only one bomb,
but later announced two bombs had gone off.
   At about the time of the explosion, shots were fired from a
passing automobile at a police car in the same area, but no one was
injured, police said. They said the passing automobile had Dutch
license plates.
   In Dublin, the IRA said in a statement circulated to the media
that it carried out ``the bomb attack in West Germany against crown
forces.'' It did not elaborate.
   The IRA, which is waging a guerrilla campaign to drive the
British out of Northern Ireland, recently has stepped up attacks on
British targets on the European continent.
   A police statement said the bombs went off at about 3 a.m. at
the Glamorgan Barracks in Duisburg, about 30 miles north of Cologne.
   The building, which British army officials say houses about 100
soldiers, is in a residential section of Duisburg.
   ``Innocent sleeping soldiers were the targets. This avoids the
risk of confronting people who are awake,'' said a spokesman for
the British army in West Germany who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Maj. John Wilkinson, another British army spokesman, said,
``Nine were hurt, but none were hospitalized and all were treated
at the scene.''
   After the blast, a hole was found in a security fence protecting
the barracks, said Duisburg police spokesman Reinhard Pape.
   ``We suspect they cut a hole in the fence to get to the
barracks,'' Pape said, adding that police did not know whether
there was a connection between the bomb blast and the shooting.
   Assailants fired a machine pistol or an automatic weapon at the
police car but no one was injured, he said.
   He said police were searching for a yellow BMW with Dutch
license plates in connection with the shooting.
   The soldiers targeted in the bomb attack belong to the 35th
Squadron of the Royal Corps Transport, a part of the 3rd Armored
Division Transport Regiment, said Maj. John Wilkinson, another
spokesman for the British army at Moenchengladbach.
   ``This is a small barracks, and not a major facility,''
Wilkinson said.
   About 56,000 British soldiers are stationed in West Germany.
   The mainly Catholic IRA seeks to unite the predominantly
Protestant province with the Irish Republic.
   On March 6 in Gibraltar, British commandos killed three unarmed
IRA guerrillas.
   IRA terrorists on May 1 killed three British airmen in the
Netherlands in two separate attacks.
   Two days later, a car bomb was found at a British military base
in the central West German city of Bielefeld. The car bomb was
disposed of before it could explode.
   A March 1987 bombing of the British Army of the Rhine
headquarters in the West German city of Rheindahlen was the first
IRA attack in continental Europe in about a decade. That blast
injured 31 people.
   Tuesday was the anniversary of the 1690 Battle of Boyne, in
which Protestant King William III defeated Catholic King James II.
   Throughout the British province on Tuesday, thousands of
Protestant loyalists marched to celebrate the victory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
