<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Hayden     07-13 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hayden,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Past And Present Clash As Tom Hayden Returns To Home State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Echoes of the turbulence of the 1960s followed
Tom Hayden when he returned to his home state to promote a new book.
   Hayden, 48, who was born in the suburb of Royal Oak and attended
the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor, faced familiar hostility
Tuesday while discussing his book, ``Reunion.''
   Callers to a Detroit radio talk show criticized Hayden and his
wife, Jane Fonda, for their anti-Vietnam War activities. More of
the same came from about a dozen veterans who protested outside a
hall in Warren where Hayden appeared.
   Hayden said his home state figured prominently in his book. He
and other activists founded Students for a Democratic Society in
1962 in Port Huron, Mich.
   The book also describes the end of 14 years of estrangement from
his father, Jack Hayden, who died the night Hayden was elected to
the California Assembly in 1982, Hayden said. Hayden's mother died
in 1986.
   ``As best I can sort it out, I wrote the book first out of
compulsion to find out something about myself and my parents,''
Hayden said.
</TEXT>
