<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Helicopter, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0622,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter with 21 Aboard Ditches in North Sea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs with all reported safe. Picks up 2nd pvs,
`The coast...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter with 21 people aboard
ditched into the North Sea today, and two helicopters and a
lifeboat rescued all the occupants, the coast guard said.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries.
   The coast guard in Aberdeen said the Sikorsky helicopter made a
controlled landing onto the ocean surface 17 miles east of Lerwick
in the Shetland Islands.
   Most helicopter traffic in the area serves the oil rigs of the
North Sea, but it was not immediately known whether this one was
ferrying oil workers.
   Press Association, the domestic news agency, said the helicopter
landed upright and stayed afloat with the occupants remaining
inside, but it said weather conditions were rough.
   The coast guard said it sent a helicopter from Sumburgh in the
Shetlands to mount a rescue operation, along with a Shell Oil Co.
helicopter and a lifeboat from Lerwick.
</TEXT>
