<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   07-13 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: national security.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July 10
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on the state district judge
protesting what he called prejudice in the judicial system:
   Alberto Miera presents a truly troubling stain on Minnesota's
landscape.
   Miera is the suspended Ramsey County District Court judge who
last week called an end to a hunger strike he said was intended to
raise public awareness of unequal treatment accorded by the state's
judiciary to ``socially vulnerable'' minorities such as himself.
   Miera is a 37-year-old Hispanic-American and self-professed
bisexual. He had been convicted of sexual harassment for forcibly
kissing a male court clerk. The state Supreme Court voted to
suspend Miera for one year without pay rather than remove him from
the bench.
   We are, we admit, suspicious of Miera. After all, his plaints of
racial bias were not raised until after he had been found guilty on
the harassment charge. And he has offered no specific incidents of
alleged bias agaist anyone other than himself. It seems he has
sought to shift the focus of his protest from his deeds to some
vague societal misdeeds.
   Yet, repeated claims of racial and sexual bias are serious and
disturbing. They are particularly so here in Minnesota, where we
pride ourselves and our state on our liberal attitudes and
equitable legal standards for all our citizens. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 9
   The Miami Herald on the impeachment proceedings against U.S.
District Court Judge Alcee Hastings:
   Alcee Hastings worked long and hard to serve his community and,
especially, the cause of black equality in that community. If he
wants to serve his community further rather than divide it, and
advance equality rather than retard it, U.S. District Judge
Hastings should resign. His only remaining defense is that a black
judge need not meet the same high standard as other federal judges.
That defense makes a mockery of Judge Hastings' long and
distinguished civil-rights career. ...
   Judge Hastings can expect a trial in the Senate that could
remove him. At best, that trial would leave him on the bench, but
utterly bereft of the trust of prosecutors, defense attorneys and
fellow jurists and fellow attorneys _ trust a judge must have to
operate effectively.
   Alcee Hastings has too much intelligence, wit, and charisma to
waste it in such a hollow role. The community has other, more
constructive, work for a man of his abilities.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 8
   Brattleboro (Vt.) Reformer on the resignation of Attorney
General Edwin Meese:
   Claiming vindication is Meese's clumsy way to save face as he,
at the same time, gives in to pressure from fellow conservatives
and from Vice President George Bush that he resign.
   Like-minded right-wingers lost patience with Meese back when it
became clear that his legal problems were making it impossible for
him to be an effective leader on issues dear to the right's heart,
such as taking away women's right to abortion or getting ideologues
onto the Supreme Court. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 8
   The Journal, Providence, R.I., on the shortage of tuba players:
   We possess no statistics to bolster our impression, but the word
is out that America will soon be suffering from a serious shortage
of tuba players. ...
   The present situation is said to be influenced by a perceived
decline in musical training among the young, as well as the cost of
the instrument _ which is measured in the thousands of dollars.
   ....Another obvious factor is sound. The tuba sounds very much
as it looks, which is not especially elegant.... What the tuba does
do well, however, is furnish a full-bodied sound to a band or
orchestra _ a sound without which many major works are rendered
simply shadows of themselves.
   If tuba lovers want to demonstrate the importance of the
survival of their instrument, they need only play a Sousa march _
first without, then with, the endangered tuba. The difference is
astounding.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
