<2ND_LINE>PM-Starr Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0620,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Of Bart Starr's Son Ruled `Accidental, Cocaine'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `The elder ...' with two grafs to ADD
comment from Bart Starr.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bret Starr, the 24-year-old son of NFL Hall
of Famer Bart Starr, died of cocaine use, authorities ruled today.
   ``The official ruling from the medical examiner is cardiac
arrhythmia due to acute cocaine indulgence,'' said Hillsborough
Sheriff's spokesman Jack Espinosa. ``It's not necessarily an
overdose.''
   Starr died July 4 or 5 in his suburban home, authorities said.
His body, unrecognizable because of decomposition, was found July 7
when his father, unable to contact him, went to the house.
   The elder Starr, the quarterback who led the Green Bay Packers
during the glory years of the 1960s and later returned as coach,
said at a news conference in Green Bay, Wis., today: ``Drugs do
kill. He only had traces and yet the traces killed him.''
   The football star talked about his son's battle with cocaine in
his recent book, ``My Life in Football: Starr.''
   ``Unbeknownst to us, by the time Bret graduated from high school
he was well on his way to a cocaine addiction,'' the father wrote,
explaining the family's repeated efforts to get him help.
</TEXT>
