<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RareBook     07-13 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rare Book,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Donated Collection of Ezra Pound's Poems Worth $25,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare collection of Ezra Pound's poems
valued at $25,000 has been found in a carton of old books donated
to the University of North Carolina.
   The book was discovered by librarian Charles McNamara, the
school said Tuesday.
   ``I was kind of stunned,'' said McNamara. ``I was saying to
myself, `This can't be true.'''
   The book, ``A Lume Spento,'' was published in Italy in 1908, and
most of the 100 copies were given by the American poet to his
friends, McNamara said.
   The book found last year is inscribed by Pound to Dr. Margaret
E. Hennessey, a great-aunt of Elizabeth Brainard of Chapel Hill,
who donated the books with her husband, Harry, an alumnus of the
school.
   Pound was born in Idaho in 1885 and died in Italy in 1972.
   McNamara said he contacted the Brainards to tell them about the
value of the book, but the Brainards didn't want it back.
   ``We just thought it belonged in a university library,'' said
Brainard, a professor emeritus at Michigan State University.
</TEXT>
