<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen-Mr.Insider     07-13 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Mr. Insider,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen: Texas Millionaire Is Quintessential Washington Insider</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen retired from the House of
Representatives in 1954 at the age of 33, declaring he wanted to
make some real money. Announcing for the Senate 16 years later, the
new millionaire explained, ``I want to be ... remembered for
something other than my financial statement.
   ``I think people are a little bit like ivy,'' the Texas Democrat
added, ``They ought to be repotted once in a while.''
   At 67, Bentsen is looking to be repotted once again _ as vice
president. Likely Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
named Bentsen as his running mate Tuesday.
   Bentsen brings to the ticket more than a Southwestern flavor and
a chance for Democrats to carry his big home state. After 17{ years
in the Senate, 1{ years as chairman of the Finance Committee and a
stint as chief fund-raiser for Democratic senators, he is as much a
Washington insider as Dukakis is not _ a situation reminiscent of
the Carter-Mondale ticket in 1976.
   Bentsen is tall, slim and dapper, a millionaire with a patrician
air. He is also a highly decorated World War II bomber pilot,
lawyer, Presbyterian and native Texan who has close ties with
business, a strong record on civil rights and a history of
supporting two of his home state's biggest industries: oil and the
military. Like Dukakis, he speaks fluent Spanish.
   He is a forceful committee chairman who is seldom heard to raise
his voice and who rarely seeks out the television cameras. Like
Dukakis, he speaks fluent Spanish. Although he flopped at his own
try for the presidency in 1976, Bentsen is credited with having the
strongest Texas political organization in in modern times; it was
he who denied George Bush a seat in the Senate in 1970.
   Publicly, at least, Bentsen has done little in Washington to
ruffle feathers. He admitted fault so quickly in his only hint at
personal scandal that he almost turned it into a plus.
   That came in January 1987, immediately after he took over as
Finance Committee chairman, when he solicited lobbyists to have
breakfast with him once a month for a $10,000 campaign
contribution. Once the story broke and critics raised the specter
of a powerful lawmaker offering himself for sale, it took Bentsen
only a couple days to back down.
   ``I'm not known to make many mistakes, but when I do it's a
doozy,'' he said in a statement, ``and in forming that breakfast
club I really blew it. ... The last thing I want is anything that
would reflect on my integrity.''
   Until taking over the Finance Committee, Bentsen was little
known outside Washington.
   He had had a stint in the late 1970s as chairman of the Joint
Economic Committee, a panel that does not write legislation, and
used the post to advocate tax cuts to spur investment and savings _
long before President Reagan came to power with promises of such a
program.
   By the time Sen. Russell B. Long, D-La., retired as chairman of
the Finance Committee in 1986, giving Bentsen a chance to push his
own ideas, Reagan's plan had been written into law.
   Bentsen often is described as a centrist. In 1986, a
conservative rating group gave him a 50 for his Senate votes; a
liberal group rated him at 45. He supported Democratic party-line
votes 46 percent of the time and opposed them 50 percent of the
time.
   As chairman of the Finance Committee, Bentsen is well-placed to
put his mark on legislation dealing with taxes, trade, welfare,
health insurance and Social Security. As chairman, he seems to push
for the middle ground as often as he was pulled toward a consensus
in earlier days on the committee.
   Thus, in an effort to get a trade bill that President Reagan
would sign, Bentsen accepted several House provisions, especially
those aimed at protecting U.S. workers and at retaliating against
unfair trade practices, that were less than he wanted.
   Republicans controlled the Finance Committee when the massive
1986 tax overhaul was enacted, and Bentsen faced the prospect of
voting to repeal major provisions _ including the investment credit
and capital-gains preferences _ that he had supported. In the end,
he voted for repeal in order to pay for a significant rate
reduction for most individuals and corporations, but he was never
enthusiastic about the package.
   The Texan has fought feverishly to retain special tax treatment
for the oil industry, especially the independent companies not
affiliated with the giant major firms. His biggest battle over the
1986 bill was a losing effort to soften the bite on real estate
developers, although he had called for some change on grounds the
old law was far too generous.
   Under Bentsen's leadership, the Finance Committee this year has
cranked out landmark bills overhauling the welfare system and
expanding Medicare to cover some costs of catastrophic illness.
   Bentsen, who served briefly as a county judge, used his family's
considerable wealth to win election to the House for the first time
in 1948. He retired after three terms to run his own lucrative
insurance and financial services business.
   He won election to the Senate in 1970 by unseating liberal Sen.
Ralph Yarborough in the Democratic primary. He defeated Bush in
November with 54 percent of the votes and was re-elected in 1976
with 57 percent and in 1982 with 59 percent.
   Bentsen has been married for 44 years to Beryl Ann Bentsen _
known as B.A. _ a former fashion model. They have three grown
children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
