<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Math-Minorities     07-13 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Math-Minorities,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Minority Kids Fall Behind Early in Math</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-year study found that minority
children often fall behind in math skills as early as the third
grade.
   The $125,000 study, described as one of the nation's most
extensive examination of math education, looked at 28,000 students
from kindergarten through the 12th grade in Montgomery County
outside Washington.
   It consisted of anaylses of various tests and interviews with
students, parents, principals and counselors.
   According to the study, funded by the National Science
Foundation, about 8 percent of the Asians and whites in the third
grade performed below grade level, compared to 15 percent for
Hispanics and 20 percent for blacks.
   When the students reached sixth grade, the percentage of
students working below grade level climbed to 16 percent for
Asians, 22 percent for whites, 39 percent for Hispanics and 51
percent for blacks, the study found.
   The study also uncovered subtle differences in the math
accomplishments of boys and girls.
   Until the last years of high school, girls take as many math
courses as boys and do as well or better. However, by the junior
and senior years, boys take more sophisticated math courses, such
as advanced algebra and calculus.
   Boys also tend to do better that girls on the math portion of
college entrance exams, the study found.
   Educators speculated that the reasons for the disparities could
include lower expectations of black and Hispanic students, less
preparation among minorities before they begin school, and
different views among female and minority students of their own
abilities and future careers.
   ``The demographic data is quite clear,'' Bassam Shakhasheri,
assistant director for science and engineering education at the
foundation, said at a news conference Tuesday.
   ``Before very long, around the year 2000, 85 percent of those
entering the work force will be minorities and women. The nation
requires both a good cadre of scientists and engineers and a
citizenry that understands the benefits of science and the
potential risks ... of technological advances.''
   ``That is a fairly typical finding all the way through,'' said
Elizabeth Fennema, professor of curriculum and instruction at the
University of Wisconsin at Madison.
   She noted that the racial disparities were similar to those
detected in the recent National Assessment of Educational Progress
and that several studies have found that girls do less well than
boys in ``high-order'' math skills.
</TEXT>
