<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CollapseProbe     07-13 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Collapse Probe,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineers: Many Records Missing In Texas Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engineer investigating the collapse
of a Texas department store that killed 14 people said today that
important building records are missing.
   Gary G. Nichols and Glenn J. Winslow, civil engineers with
Birmingham-based Southern Building Code Congress International
Inc., are the primary investigators of the collapse last week of
the Amigo Store in Brownsville.
   ``We've been told that the building department has moved two or
three times over the period of time when the building was built and
some of the records may have been involved in a flood,'' Nichols
said Wednesday.
   He said the city is still going through its records, which were
stored in several different places, in search of construction plans
for the building.
   The engineers said their investigation has been hampered by
sketchy information from witnesses and the absence of records,
including specifications.
   The two were in Brownsville Saturday through Monday searching
for clues to the July 7 collapse of the three-story building during
a heavy rainstorm.
   ``Right now we don't know why it happened,'' Winslow said
Tuesday. ``We may not ever know what caused it.''
   A preliminary report on the collapse should be complete late
this week, he said, adding that a complete report will take months
to complete.
   Nichols said he and Winslow are looking into the possibility
that the rain may have caused the collapse. If the building's drain
pipes were clogged, water could have backed up and its weight
triggered the fall, he said.
   Nichols and Winslow work for a non-profit agency that writes
building codes for governments.
   Its engineers examine building materials and write
recommendations on how they should be used in construction and
examine structures that have fallen.
   Nearly 2,000 city, county and state building departments are
served by the organization.
</TEXT>
