<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FBI-Libraries     07-13 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Libraries,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Official Defends Library Visits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI official testified Wednesday that
criticism of the bureau's Library Awareness Program has been
``overblown,'' and that agents making official visits to libraries
are interested solely in the activities of Soviet spies.
   James H. Geer, assistant director-intelligence division, told a
House panel that the program is narrowly focused, principally on
scientific and technical libraries in the New York City area.
   Geer said the FBI made 21 contacts with Greater New York
libraries between late 1985 and 1987. Most visits simply alerted
librarians to use of their facilities by Soviet agents engaged in
recruiting and information-gathering, he said.
   Visits to libraries outside New York were not part of any
program, but resulted from leads in specific counter-intelligence
cases, Geer told the House Judiciary subcommittee on civil rights.
   Organizations of librarians and civil liberties groups have
asserted there is a pattern of FBI interest in libraries across the
country, and have accused the bureau of intimidating library
employees.
   They said the bureau was trying to to enlist library personnel
as spies, to identify patrons who might be gathering information
for foreign powers. Librarians, they said, were given broad
requests to monitor patrons with Russian or Eastern-European
sounding names.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of the subcommittee, said
some of the nation's most respected librarians are ``scared to
death'' of the program.
   Geer tried to assure Edwards that ``This isn't any kind of a
massive program. I don't expect any great return.'' Edwards replied
that there has been ``a massive public reaction'' against the
program.
   The FBI official testified, ``Our library contacts seek to
inform selected librarians that they and their libraries are, and
have historically been, significant SIS (Soviet Intelligence
Services) targets for intelligence activities and recruitment.''
   ``Suitable scenarios have been developed by the SIS to approach
students, librarians, scientists and engineers to secure their
cooperation. Payments or other inducements have been offered,'' he
said.
   Geer said lists of patrons with foreign-sounding names or
accents ``are not of interest or concern to the bureau.''
   He also denied that the FBI has used physical or electronic
surveillance in libraries contacted under the awareness program.
Nor has it asked employees to circumvent confidentiality rules or
laws, he said.
</TEXT>
