<2ND_LINE>PM-Alien Trial,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Trial of Journalist, Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began today in the trial
of a free-lance journalist and a Lutheran minister accused of
smuggling two pregnant Salvadoran women into the United States in
1986.
   Demetria Martinez and the Rev. Glen Remer-Thamert, both of
Albuquerque, were indicted Dec. 10.
   The case has been embraced by the sanctuary movement of clergy
and lay people who have been aiding refugees from Central America
since the early 1980s.
   However, U.S. Attorney William Lutz has charged in court papers
that Remer-Thamert was selling Salvadoran babies for adoption, not
helping political refugees.
   U.S. District Judge John Conway today asked prospective jurors
if they were familiar with the sanctuary movement, which contends
religious beliefs outweigh the law when helping Central Americans
flee their wartorn countries.
   Remer-Thamert, 44, was charged with conspiracy, transporting and
harboring illegal aliens and mail fraud. Ms. Martinez, 28, was
charged with transporting and inducing illegal aliens.
   The indictment also accused the minister of submitting false
expense documents to an adoption agency and of receiving $2,900.
   Remer-Thamert has said he acted out of humanitarian concerns and
was charged because of his criticism of the Reagan administration's
Central American policies.
   Ms. Martinez contends she was along on the trip from El Paso,
Texas, to Albuquerque in her capacity as a journalist.
</TEXT>
