<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Convention-Costs     07-13 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention-Costs,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Cities Take Different Approach to Handle Costs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SALADINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic National Convention next week is
expected to cost the city of Atlanta about $15 million with the
Georgia legislature and a few local banks already taking care of
much of the fund-raising.
   In New Orleans, site of the Republican Convention on Aug. 15-18,
the city has struggled to come up with the funds to pay for
security measures, 5,000 upholstered chairs and the lighting and
sound systems for the Superdome.
   The two host cities, faced with expensive convention pricetags,
have taken different paths toward raising the money to pay the
bills.
   In Atlanta, the total cost for the four-day convention is $24
million with the Democratic Party picking up $9 million of the tab.
The remaining cost will be raised from a 2-cent hotel-motel tax in
effect in the city and Fulton County through July 1990.
   Last year, the state legislature passed a bill increasing the
tax and earmarking the money for the Atlanta '88 Committee Inc., a
non-profit corporation created by the city, county and state to
plan and stage the convention.
   ``We have a nice cushion built in, in what we need to borrow and
what our interest revenues are going to be,'' said Atlanta '88
president Bobby Kahn. ``There would have to be a virtual depression
in the convention industry for our revenue projections not to be
met.''
   Two Atlanta banks also agreed in late May to provide a loan of
up to $9 million to help cover the costs until Atlanta '88 receives
those revenues.
   In New Orleans, early fund-raising was slow and complaints by
the Greater New Orleans Convention Fund that big companies were
failing to contribute forced Mayor Sidney Barthelemy to appoint
another committee.
   The second committee, formed on May 12, immediately launched an
intensified campaign that came up with cash and commitments of more
than $250,000.
   Hotels have pledged 10 percent of the money they receive from
rooms in use during the convention _ an estimated $1.5 million.
   ``I think we're going to be on target,'' said Ron Jones, who is
heading the New Orleans fund-raising effort. ``This has always been
a town that gets its big hits late.''
   Jones, president of Louisiana Coca-Cola Bottling Co. and
chairman of the Business Council of New Orleans, said that in an
effort to raise money, special perks will be added for people who
give $1,000 or more, including tickets to the convention, admission
to parks and museums and invitations to receptions with the mayor
and governor.
   Atlanta '88, which was organized immediately after Atlanta was
awarded the Democratic Convention in February 1987, has not faced
the same financial problems although it must pay some high costs.
   Among the expenses are $1.3 million for rental of the Omni
Coliseum, which began May 28; $875,000 for rental of the Georgia
World Congress Center and parking, which began July 1, and $2
million for construction of among other things, lighting grids, a
sound system, seat removal and podium construction, said Ruth
Berry, press secretary for the Democratic National Convention
Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
