<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-House-Ethics     07-13 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House-Ethics,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Ask Fazio To Recuse Himself In Wright Ethics Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans called Wednesday for Rep.
Vic Fazio, D-Calif., to step aside from the ethics committee's
conflict-of-interest case against Speaker Jim Wright because he
enlisted Wright's help for a California political fund-raiser.
   The action came in a resolution unanimously approved in a
closed-door session of the House Republican Conference, the
organization of all GOP House members, said Johanna Schneider,
spokeswoman for Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill.
   The resolution also included a call for the ethics panel,
formally known as the Committee on Standards of Official Conduct,
to appoint an independent counsel to aid in the Wright
investigation. That matter is still under consideration by the
panel, which opened its probe June 9.
   The resolution came just four days before the Democrats open
their national convention, with Wright as chairman, in Atlanta.
   Wright has been accused by Republicans of improperly intervening
with federal regulators on behalf of Texas businesses, and of
collecting unduly high royalties on a book he wrote which was
published by a Wright campaign contractor. Copies of the book were
sold to special-interest groups, and an aide on Wright's
congressional payroll helped prepare it.
   The speaker contends the charges are politically motivated.
   Fazio, a member of the ethics panel, helped arrange for Wright
to be the featured speaker at a $500-a-plate political luncheon in
Sacramento in June, less than two weeks after the committee opened
its Wright probe.
   Republicans maintain Fazio cannot appear to be a fair judge in
the Wright case if the speaker agrees to help him raise money for
party causes. Fazio said there was nothing wrong with the
arrangement, and that political fund raising by the House speaker
is a routine matter.
   Neither Fazio nor Wright directly benefited from the luncheon,
which was to raise money to help elect Democrats to the House and
for a program called Impact 2000, aimed at helping elect Democrats
to state legislative seats to help increase the party's influence
over redistricting.
   The resolution stated that to maintain the ethics panel's
integrity, any member faced with a situation that might appear to
be a conflict ``should voluntarily excuse him or herself from those
deliberations ...'' A temporary replacement could then be named to
maintain the 6-to-6 party balance on the committee, it said.
   The document, which has no binding force but is simply an
expression of opinion by the conference, did not mention Fazio by
name. Earlier versions had included his name, but the language was
toned down at the urging of GOP members of the ethics committee,
said Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., chairman of the Republican Policy
Committee.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., said the resolution
was part of ``an obvious attempt to politicize this (Wright
investigation) and it's most unfortunate.'' He said Fazio's ability
to be an impartial member of the panel had not been affected by the
fund-raiser.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
