<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     07-13 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomat Says U.S. May Be Soft-Pedaling Latest Incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Iran, Bjt and AM-Airliner-Pentagon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. diplomat said Wednesday the United
States may be trying to play down the latest U.S.-Iran skirmish in
the Persian Gulf out of sensitivity over the Navy's destruction of
an Iranian jetliner.
   There was virtually no new information released about a clash
Tuesday night between three U.S. helicopters and several Iranian
boats in the northern gulf.
   U.S. military officials said they had no further information
about whether an Iranian speedboat was damaged in the encounter.
They said they couldn't say if the Navy had conducted a search for
debris or survivors.
   Such searches have been routine after previous clashes involving
Iran's small armed boats and U.S. helicopters.
   One U.S. officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a
search would depend in part on the risk involved.
   A U.S. diplomat, who is knowledgeable about official U.S. policy
in the gulf, said U.S. authorities were providing very little
information, possibly because of the downing of the jetliner.
   ``We just don't want to be killing any more Iranians,'' he said.
``On the other hand, we don't want our people to be killed either.''
   The diplomat was referring to the shooting down of an Iran Air
A300 Airbus by the U.S. missile cruiser Vincennes on July 3. All
290 aboard died when the warship destroyed the jetliner. Navy
officials said the Vincennes crew mistook the jet for an F-14
fighter.
   Officials said Tuesday's skirmish occurred about dusk after the
U.S. missile frigate Nicholas, off the Saudi Arabian coast, heard a
Mayday message from the Universal Monarch, a Panamanian-flag tanker.
   The tanker reported it was under attack by small armed boats 15
miles west of Farsi island, a military base long used by Iran's
Revolutionary Guards for attacks on shipping.
   The Pentagon said the Nicholas' SH-60B Seahawk helicopter and
two attack helicopters responded to the distress signal and drew
fire from the Iranian boats.
   The attack aircraft retaliated with rockets and rapid-firing
Gatling guns, possibly damaging one of the boats, according to the
pilots, U.S. officials said. They said the helicopters were not hit
and there were no U.S. casualties.
   Maj. Barry Willey, a spokesman at U.S. Central Command
headquarters in Tampa, Fla., said on Wednesday there was ``no
further assessment of damage'' to the Iranian boats beyond the
initial report.
   U.S. officials, who spoke on condtion of anonymity, said the
pilots identified the attackers as ``Boston Whaler-type'' boats,
flat-bottomed, glass fiber-hulled craft powered by outboard motors
and commonly used by the Revolutionary Guards, especially around
Farsi.
   The Universal Monarch, managed by a Hong Kong company, suffered
no casualties in the attack but briefly caught fire and its engine
room was flooded, according to gulf-based shipping executives, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, and Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence
Unit in London.
   The ship was towed to Bahrain overnight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
