<DOCNO> AP880713-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Inquiry     07-13 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Inquiry,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Investigators Are Silent and Secret</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Airliner-ICAO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asssociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a region where concern about terrorism
is high and the profile of American military personnel low, U.S.
experts investigating the shooting down of an Iranian airliner are
silent and nearly invisible.
   Their daily travels between a Manama hotel and two U.S. warships
anchored off Bahrain are quick and discreet. They wear civilian
clothes while ashore, as do other U.S. military personnel in the
security-conscious Arab countries of the Persian Gulf.
   The six-man team arrived July 5 on a special U.S. military
aircraft, two days after the Iran Air Airbus A300 was shot down by
the missile cruiser USS Vincennes, which mistook it for an Iranian
F-14 fighter. All 290 people aboard were killed.
   A 15-day period allowed for completion of the report is more
than half gone but officials at U.S. Central Command headquarters
in Tampa, Fla., say it can be extended if Rear Adm. William M.
Fogarty, the team leader, decides more time is needed.
   The investigators received an analysis of the Vincennes computer
tapes Tuesday, but U.S. officials would not say what the analysis
revealed about the performance of the billion-dollar cruiser's
Aegis air-defense system.
   Britain said Wednesday its tapes of distress frequencies were
being provided. The Americans were understood to have requested
similar data from the Italians, who like the British had a warship
in the area, and from air traffic control in Dubai, the destination
of Iran Air flight 655.
   One U.S. official said the team is trying to collect ``anything
and everything'' that might help reconstruct the incident,
beginning with a skirmish between the Vincennes and Iranian
speedboats less than an hour earlier.
   Fogarty, 52, is a former battleship commander who now is
director of plans and policy at Central Command, the administrative
headquarters for U.S. military activities in the Middle East and
the gulf region.
   Navy spokesmen have refused to identify the others, citing
security considerations, except to say one is a lawyer and the rest
are technical experts. They are seen only rarely and ignore all
questions.
   One member of the team, Capt. John J. Kieley III, even refused
at first to acknowledge two journalists he knew months ago while
serving a tour in the gulf as skipper of the missile frigate Reuben
James.
   He exchanged brief pleasantries with the two a day later, but
said nothing about the investigation. He now is a Pentagon staff
officer.
   Navy spokesmen will say only that the investigation ``is
continuing.''
   The team's first action was to take depositions from Capt. Will
C. Rogers III, commander of the Vincennes, and other officers of
the three U.S. warships that were in the area when the Iranian
plane was shot down.
   One U.S. military official said the actions of ships' officers
at the scene might be easily explained and the mystery of the
destruction of Iran Air flight 655 probably lies mainly in the
technical data, including the ``black box'' fight recorder. Iran
says it has not been found.
   U.S. officials in Washington said the combat information center
on the Vincennes received a confusing mixture of identification
signals, on both military and civilian channels, indicating the
Airbus was an Iranian F-14 fighter.
   They say Rogers fired his missiles at virtually the last
possible moment, after failing repeatedly to establish radio
contact with the aircraft on both military and civilian frequencies.
   Most of the investigation has been conducted on the Navy's gulf
flagship, the Coronado, and on the Vincennes. The 9,600-ton missile
cruiser has been anchored off Bahrain for a week, barely visible
from shore in the haze.
   An American who visited the Vincennes last week said ``nobody
talks about'' the Airbus, at least when outsiders are aboard.
   The other two ships in the area at the time, the frigate Elmer
Montgomery and the missile frigate John H. Sides, were in port in
Manama for the first few days of the investigation but have
returned to duty.
   Both ships are said to have evidence indicating the jetliner was
at about 12,000 feet and possibly climbing, rather than descending
from 9,000 to 7,800 feet as the Vincennes believed.
   Officials refused to say Wednesday whether there had been
contact between the United States and Iran in connection with the
investigation. ``If that was deemed appropriate, it would be done
through appropriate channels,'' a Central Command spokesman said.
</TEXT>
