<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Space     07-13 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Space,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Satellite Mission Fails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 40-ton rocket carrying a research
satellite plunged into the sea minutes after takeoff Wednesday,
scientists said. It was India's second launch failure in 15 months.
   The rocket's first-stage motor apparently malfuctioned shortly
after the rocket, the Augmented Satellite Launch Vehicle (ASLV),
blasted off at 2:28 p.m. from Sriharikota Island, 1,100 miles
southeast of New Delhi, according to a scientist at the launch site.
   The scientist, who spoke on condition of anomymity, said contact
with the rocket was lost 1 minute and 15 seconds after takeoff. The
United News of India news agency said the rocket crashed into the
Indian Ocean 4 minutes and 10 seconds after the launch.
   The chairman of the Indian Space Research Organization in New
Delhi, U.R. Rao, was quoted as saying the exact cause of the launch
failure had not been determined.
   It was the second failed Indian space mission since another
rocket from the same ASLV series plunged into the Bay of Bengal in
March 1987, when its first-stage motor failed to ignite minutes
after launching.
   The scientist at the launch site said the first-stage motor in
Wednesday's launch ignited, but ``something went wrong after that.''
   The rocket carried a 330-pound satellite designed to take
three-dimensional photographs of Earth and conduct experiments on
the origins of gamma rays. The satellite was to enter an orbit 240
miles above Earth, scientists said.
   The failure of the mission comes amid reports that India could
develop the ASLV rocket as a launch vehicle for nuclear weapons.
   According to Anthony H. Cordesman, a U.S. military analyst, the
rocket, with the addition of a heat shield and a guidance system,
could deploy intermediate-range ballistic missiles or IRBM.
   ``The Indians themselves have estimated that they could have an
operational, nuclear-armed IRBM by 1989,'' Cordesman said in a
published report.
   India exploded an atomic device in 1974, but the government says
its nuclear program is for peaceful purposes.
   India last successfully launched a satellite on April 17, 1983.
   Since 1980, it has launched two other satellites, while three
other missions failed, including the first ASLV launch.
   Six Indian-made satellites have been sent into orbit by space
agencies in the Soviet Union, United States and Europe.
   On Tuesday, the Soviet Union successfully launched the second of
two space probes to explore Mars and help prepare for a manned
flight to the red planet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
