<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1519EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-BrountasProfile     07-13 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brountas Profile,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paul Brountas: Dukakis' Friend and Adviser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Brountas _ confidant and adviser to
Democratic nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis _ likes to tell a story
about his three brothers, all of them one-time mayors of Bangor,
Maine.
   The local newspaper once photographed the three Mayors Brountas
and ran this caption beneath: ``They also have a brother Paul.''
   Paul P. Brountas has gained a little stature of his own since
then.
   The prominent Boston lawyer led Dukakis' search for a vice
presidential running mate, and Dukakis thanked him publicly on
Tuesday and recalled their days in law school with Paul Sarbanes,
now a U.S. senator from Maryland.
   ``Little could the Greek troika in the class of 1960 at Harvard
Law School possibly imagine that Dukakis would be the Democratic
nominee for president, Sarbanes would be a Democrat from Maryland
in the U.S. Senate, and our counselor and adviser and friend would
not only be the chairman of our cmapaign committee but the person
who managed this wonderful process which has brought us Lloyd
Bentsen,'' Dukakis told a news conference in Boston.
   Brountas, 56, is confidant and gray eminence aboard Dukakis'
campaign plane _ and, many believe, the most likely candidate for
attorney general or White House counselor should Dukakis win in
November.
   ``I really haven't allowed myself to think about it,'' Brountas
says of that talk. ``There's a lot of attraction to it, but there's
also a lot of attraction to what I have been doing.
   ``I haven't even thought about it _ that's the most dangerous
thing you can do.''
   It was Brountas who conducted final interviews with Jesse
Jackson and other potential vice presidential candidates and
presented background findings to Dukakis. In a late-night meeting
Monday at Dukakis' home, Brountas recommended the selection of
Bentsen _ and Dukakis agreed.
   Brountas, 56, a partner in the large and successful law firm of
Hale and Dorr, is like Dukakis in many ways, not the least of which
is his careful, close-to-the-vest demeanor.
   Like the Massachusetts governor, Brountas is the son of Greek
immigrants. He grew up in Bangor, Maine, where his father ran a
small restaurant. He graduated from Bowdoin College and attended
Oxford as a Marshall Scholar before entering Harvard.
   ``I was kind of a hick from Maine,'' Brountas said. ``I hadn't
been out of the state much.''
   But Brountas has pursued politics in his own quiet and
successful way.
   Comfortable in his law practice, Brountas watched the chaotic
1968 Democratic National Convention that nominated Hubert Humphrey
for president and Maine Sen. Edmund Muskie as vice president. On a
whim, Brountas wrote a letter to Muskie volunteering his help.
   ``I did something fairly impulsive for me and said, if nobody
else is going to help, I would,'' Brountas recalled in a recent
interview. ``I never expected to hear from him.''
   But he did. Muskie invited him on a campaign trip, and soon he
was a senior adviser to the vice presidential nominee. Four years
later he was an adviser for Muskie's ill-fated presidential
campaign.
   Brountas has been involved in all of Dukakis' major campaigns,
usually as chairman, including the 1978 Democratic primary when
Dukakis lost to Ed King _ a setback that Brountas says helped
Dukakis in the long-run by teaching him to listen.
   The two became friends at Harvard. After graduating and taking
their bar exams, the two loaded up Brountas' Volkswagen Karmann
Ghia and headed to Los Angeles, where John F. Kennedy was nominated
for the presidency.
   ``We were fairly straight guys, but we would look for the
attractive young ladies to have drinks with,'' Brountas said.
   They stopped in Las Vegas, where they slept in a park, and
Dukakis reluctantly played the slot machines. He won a $30 jackpot
on his first try, then quit. They went to San Francisco and Mexico,
as well.
   ``We talked a lot about what we were going to do,'' Brountas
recalled. ``I was going to go to Maine and run for governor.''
   But Brountas' plans changed. He found he liked practicing law,
and it occurred to him that predominantly Republican Maine might
not elect him.
   ``I thought, I can get involved at a different level,'' he said.
   In Boston, Brountas developed a practice specializing in the
emerging high-technology and computer companies that have led the
region's economic boom. He provides business as well as legal
advice, sometimes representing companies and sometimes the venture
capitalists, and has guided them through rapid growth, mergers,
acquisitions and the sometimes hugely profitable initial public
stock offerings.
   ``It's very satisfying because you grow with the companies,''
Brountas said.
   He has also been an important link for Dukakis to business
leaders in the state.
   Brountas is fond of saying he has quit practicing law, now that
his time is fully occupied by Dukakis' presidential bid.
   It was Brountas who quided the selection of Susan Estrich as
campaign manager when Dukakis' trusted aide John Sasso was forced
to resign in controversy over the seeming sabatoge of rival Joseph
Biden's campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
