<DOCNO> AP880713-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Women-Discrimination     07-13 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Discrimination,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. To Scrutinize Hiring of Women in Construction, Aerospace Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal task force will study why such a low
percentage of women hold jobs in the construction and aerospace
industries, U.S. Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin said Wednesday.
   ``The problems women may have in securing jobs traditionally
held by men is an issue of great interest to me,'' Ms. McLaughlin
said at a news conference.
   The task force is to begin its review by the end of the month
and complete it within a few months, she said. The panel will
determine female representation in the two industries and whether
there are overt or subtle pressures against hiring or promoting
women, Ms. McLaughlin said.
   Women filled about 1.2 percent of construction jobs in 1980,
according to census figures that year, when government and industry
set goals to increase the proportion to 6.9 percent over the next
few years, said Labor Department aide Jerry Blakemore. So far, he
said, women's representation in contruction jobs has improved only
to about 2 percent.
   The female proportion of aerospace workers has been higher _
about 19 percent to 26 percent, he said, but labor officials
consider it still too low.
   According to Ms. McLaughlin, ``If we find there are problems, we
will enforce the prohibition against sex discrimination by
government contractors and the requirements that they take
affirmative action.
   ``In addition, we will see whether we can improve the Labor
Department's compliance and review procedures. And we will develop
recommendations on how to increase opportunities for women in these
non-traditional jobs,'' she said.
   Ms. McLaughlin was in Chicago to attend a briefing with business
and government leaders concerned about affordable child care for
working mothers.
   Serving on the task force will be representatives of the
solicitor's office of the Labor Department, the Office of Federal
Contract Compliance, which administers federal anti-discrimination
guidelines for government contractors, and the federal Bureau of
Apprenticeship and Training, Ms. McLaughlin said.
</TEXT>
