<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Mideast     07-13 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwaiti Sqy{0Shultz Wivyurn To Mideast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Prime Minister of Kuwait said Wednesday
that Secretary of State George P. Shultz will make a fifth trip to
the Middle East this year to push his plan for Arab-Israeli
negotiations.
   Sheik Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah wished Shultz well and joined
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak as the only Arab leaders to openly
endorse the plan.
   However, the prime minister called also for establishment of a
Palestinian state and for participation of the Palestine Liberation
Organization in the negotiations.
   Sheik Saad, who is also crown prince of the Persian Gulf
country, said the continued ``uprising'' of Palestinian Arabs on
the Israeli-held West Bank and in Gaza was ``a strong exhibition of
the determination of the Palestinians to regain their freedom.''
   About 200 Palestinians and four Israelis have been killed in
clashes since last December.
   Shultz's plan does not call for a Palestinian state, nor for PLO
participation in the talks unless it recognizes Israel's right to
exist and disavows terrorism.
   He has made four trips to the Middle East this year to try to
promote negotiations between Israel and a mixed delegation of
Jordanians and Palestinians and run into resistance from Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, King Hussein of Jordan and the PLO.
   Shamir refused to participate in a peace conference held partly
under Soviet auspices, Hussein wanted a guarantee that Israel would
relinquish the West Bank and Gaza, and the PLO barred Palestinians
from meeting with Shultz.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said she knew of
``no plans'' for Shultz to return to the region. And yet, she
recalled ``the secretary has always said that he would be available
to return to the Middle East if it would be useful in pursuit of
the peace initiative.''
   Sheik Saad, on a week-long visit here, met on Tuesday with
President Reagan and on Monday with Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci and Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead.
   Shultz is o a trip to the Far East. He plans to go to Central
America and South America in early August, attend the Republican
national convention in mid-month and take a vacation before Labor
Day. He would then have until January to try to his hand at
``shuttle diplomacy'' again.
   Sheik Saad, in a speech and a press conference, renewed Kuwait's
request for U.S. air-to-ground Maverick missiles as part of a $1.8
billion arms purchase from the United States that would include 40
F-18 jet fighter planes.
   The Senate has voted to block the Mavericks, viewing them as a
potential threat to Israel's security. Sheik Saad said Kuwait was
``a peace-loving country'' and wanted the arms for self-defense.
   ``It doesn't mean we intend to invade any other country,'' the
Arab leader said.
   Over the weekend, Kuwait annouced an arms deal with the Soviet
Union. ``So,'' Sheik Saad said, ``don't be surprised when you read
tomorrow or next week or next month that Kuwait also has bought
military equipment from Moscow, or Britain or France.''
   He scheduled meetings with members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee to try to reverse the opposition to the
Mavericks.
</TEXT>
