<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FerryCapsize     07-13 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ferry Capsize,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Capsizes, 27 Hurled Into Colorado River</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VG1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUGHLIN, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ferry boat hit another vessel and
capsized in the dark, spilling 27 gamblers and casino workers into
the chilly, swift-flowing Colorado River, authorities said.
   The victims were pulled safely from the river by onlookers and
boaters while others combed the river's edge with flashlights. One
rescuer described Tuesday night's ordeal as ``a lot of screaming
and yelling.''
   The 27 victims were treated for minor injuries, shock and
hypothermia, said Joe Harrington, spokesman for Community Hospital
in Bullhead City, Ariz., across the river from this gaming resort.
Two people remained hospitalized Wednesday.
   The 25-foot pontoon ferry boat lost power while pulling away
from the Nevada side of the river about 9:30 p.m. It crashed into
an unoccupied 60-foot pleasure boat that was docked at the
Edgewater Hotel, according to Las Vegas Metropolitan Police.
   The ferry is one of many that carries gamblers and casino
workers between Bullhead City on the river's eastern shore and
Laughlin, 100 yards away on the western shore. Laughlin is 90 miles
southwest of Las Vegas.
   The 27 people were dumped into about 15 feet of 52-degree water.
Two men and two women were pulled from the river some distance away
by three people who had spent the evening fishing downstream.
   ``There was a lot of screaming and yelling and a lot of people
hanging off the boat,'' said Laughlin resident Frank Marini, who
had just finished a night of fishing with two friends. ``My stomach
was in knots. I didn't want to pull up any dead bodies.''
   Emergency helicopters from Las Vegas and Arizona and personnel
from the Metro search and rescue unit joined U.S. Bureau of
Reclamation and state Department of Wildlife and Fish and Game
personnel in searching for the passengers.
   Authorities initially reported that two people had died and 10
were missing. They later revised the figures, saying those reported
missing were determined to have walked away from the accident, and
that there were no deaths.
   The ferry is one of several owned by the Colorado Belle and
Edgewater hotel-casinos, according to Scott Menke, assistant
manager of the Edgewater. The boats make about 12 runs an hour.
</TEXT>
