<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--No-SmokingOrdinance     07-13 0123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--No-Smoking Ordinance,0125</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tobacco-Growing County Endorsed Smoking Restrictions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County Council members in a prime
tobacco-growing region have given initial approval to an ordinance
that would ban smoking in county-owned buildings.
   Under the plan proposed by Councilman Hughey Walker, who calls
it a Clean Indoor Air Ordinance, all cigarette, pipe and cigar
smoking would be banned in county-owned buildings, except in
designated smoking areas.
   County Council voted 6-1 Tuesday night to approve the ordinance
on first reading. The ordinance, which calls for violators to be
fined up to $200, must pass second and third readings before it
becomes law.
   Councilman H.E. Hemingway, a tobacco warehouse owner and the
dissenting vote, puffed on a cigarette while the ordinance was
considered.
