<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Gulf     07-13 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Gulf,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Pentagon Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush To Carry U.S. Case On Airliner Downing to U.N.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, promising to
defend ``the honor of the United States,'' will present the U.S.
case when the U.N. Security Council meets Thursday to debate the
American destruction of an Iranian airliner carrying 290 people.
   The White House said Wednesday that President Reagan's selection
of Bush ``reflects the importance of the issues at stake.''
   It also guarantees a high-profile platform for Bush, who is
certain to be the Republican presidential nominee, at a time when
the Democrats are preparing to install Michael Dukakis as their
presidential candidate.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater insisted that political
factors were not involved in the choice of Bush.
   Iran, which has boycotted the Security Council since the
Iran-Iraq war began in 1980, is coming back to the world
organization to seek a resolution that would condemn, or at least
deplore, the downing of the Iranian civilian airliner over the
Persian Gulf by the U.S. cruiser Vincennes.
   The vice president, at a political appearance before a farm
group, said, ``I can't wait to get up there to defend the policy of
the United States government.''
   Bush was U.S. ambassador to the United Nations from 1971 to
1973, and this is believed to be his first U.N. speech since then.
U.N. officials said that no U.S. vice president had addressed the
council in recent memory.
   Previewing his remarks, Bush said, ``It's the free world's case.
And the efforts to second-guess the captain of that ship will be
rebuffed. And what I'm going to say is a matter that concerns all
Americans, whatever line of work you engage in.
   ``The honor of the United States,'' Bush continued. ``To see
this second-guessing going on, to suggest that the United States
was wrong, that this captain was wrong _ his ship under fire, seven
warnings and him trying to protect the lives of these American
kids.''
   The U.S. ship, under attack by Iranian speedboats at the time,,
claimed it mistook the airliner for an Iranian F-14 fighter.
   Discussing Bush's role, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said the vice president ``will demonstrate to the Security Council
and the world the U.S. concern on this matter, the seriousness with
which we take it and our dedication to steps to try to end the
Iran-Iraq war.
   ``That is our motivation.''
   Denying any political motivation in Bush's assignment, Fitzwater
said, ``Let's deal with the real question here. The issue is that
we believe that this is a matter of the highest importance to the
United States and to the world.''
   ``That is our motivation in the sense that the vice president
can make these points forcefully and dramatically,'' he said. ``The
vice president does not normally appear before the United Nations
Security Council and in this way we can again highlight our
previously stated position.''
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali-Akbar Velayati will be the first
speaker before the Security Council, and Bush is expected to be the
second.
   Diplomatic observers at the U.N. said Bush's appearance would be
a major political gesture of goodwill and sincerity. They said his
presence and his statements also could signal to Iran that the
United States is receptive to a dialogue between the two
governments, which have no diplomatic ties.
   The council meeting, originally set for Tuesday, was postponed
until Thursday because Iran was unable to get a majority on the
15-member council to condemn the United States and demand its
withdrawal from the Persian Gulf.
   But diplomatic sources also said the U.S. announcement of
compensation and its expression of regret had pre-empted Iran,
which had sought to use the forum to denounce the United States.
   The United States was expected to veto any resolution condemning
the U.S. Navy in the Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
