<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GreenRiver     07-13 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Green River,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force Probing Green River Serial Murders Won't Be Reduced For
Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of officers investigating the case of
the Green River killer, who is blamed for the deaths of up to 48
women, will be reduced if no new developments arise within the next
year, an official said Wednesday.
   King County Executive Tim Hill said the 19 officers on the Green
River Task Force will remain at least until the current fiscal year
ends in June 1989.
   ``There is not going to be a reduction this year,'' Hill said.
   The serial killer is officially blamed for the deaths of as many
as 48 young women, many of them prostitutes, between the summer of
1982 and early 1984. Four victims were found in Oregon, but the
killer has operated primarily in the Puget Sound area.
   Forty are known dead and the task force had blamed the killer
for the disappearances of eight missing women.
   Sheriff James Montgomery said $13 million has been spent since
the task force was formed after the first bodies were found. The
budget for the current fiscal year for the officers and four staff
members is about $1 million.
   The force at one time numbered nearly 60.
   Montgomery also said police are investigating similarities
between the Green River deaths and a case in San Diego, Calif., in
which 32 young women have been killed. Those killings started
shortly after the Seattle-area slayings ended in early 1984.
   In a June 30 memo to Hill, Montgomery said the timing of the
killings in the two cases was ``very significant,'' and called the
slayings in the two states ``almost a mirror image'' of each other.
   He told reporters Wednesday there also were many differences.
   Hill and Montgomery said the King County task force would
cooperate fully with San Diego authorities.
</TEXT>
