<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--WarehouseFire     07-13 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Warehouse Fire,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters: Damages to Safeway Warehouse Could Hit $60 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Damages from a fire that destroyed a
520,000-square-foot supermarket chain warehouse could reach $60
million, firefighters said.
   Workers at the Safeway warehouse told firefighters they believe
the building was worth about $30 million and the groceries it
contained were worth $30 million more, said David Howard, the
city's acting fire marshal.
   Company officials said they were still adding up the damage. The
company has not decided whether it will rebuild the warehouse in
the same place, spokesman Louie Gonzalez said.
   The fire could be seen in San Francisco, 15 miles to the
southwest, Monday night and early Tuesday.
   The warehouse was part of a million-square-foot distribution
complex that supplies more than 200 Safeway stores. About 400
people worked there.
   Firefighters said they believe the blaze started when a worker
driving a forklift accidentally ran into an overhanging halogen
light. The impact sent a a shower of sparks down onto a
15-foot-high stack of cardboard boxes filled with toilet paper,
Howard said.
