<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Writers-Networks     07-13 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers-Networks,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Network Bosses Say Writers Strike Seriously Hurting Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 19-week scriptwriters' strike is severely
damaging the major networks, but producers must hold the line
against rising costs, the top ABC and NBC bosses said.
   ``The absence of new fall programs is extremely negative to us
at a time when cable is gaining,'' said NBC President Robert C.
Wright.
   ``Even our own ESPN is competing with us,'' said Capital
Cities@ABC Chairman Thomas S. Murphy, referring to the company's
cable sports network.
   Wright and Murphy were responding to a Los Angeles Times request
for their views on the Writers Guild of America strike. CBS
President Laurence A. Tisch did not respond to the inquiry, the
Times reported Wednesday.
   ``The damage is both short-term and long-term,'' said Wright,
noting that his No. 1-rated network has the most to lose.
   He said the network had an unprecedented opportunity to use its
Olympics and World Series coverage to promote its fall lineup.
   The 9,000 film and TV writers went on strike March 7 over
creative control and residuals from reruns and overseas broadcasts.
   The executives are backing the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers position, even refusing to buy new programs
from independent production companies that sign interim contracts
with the union.
   ``It isn't just the increases in program costs that disturb me.
It's the fundamentally high cost of programming. This is very, very
expensive,'' Wright said.
   ``There's no more water in the mop,'' said Murphy.
   The strike cut last season short and suspended all work on this
fall's shows. The networks have announced plans to fill their
prime-time schedules using specials, foreign scripts, movies and
remakes of old series.
   ``For a number of shows that were important to us for the fall,
it's already too late. We already missed them,'' Wright said.
</TEXT>
