<DOCNO> AP880713-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1605EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FedInflation Bjt   07-13 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed Inflation, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Ready to Push Interest Rates Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told
Congress Wednesday that the central bank stands ready to push
interest rates higher to stem inflation.
   And the risks of a new wage-price spiral are ``sufficiently
great'' that the Fed should err on the side of squeezing credit,
rather than stimulating the economy, he said.
   Greenspan, delivering his mid-year report on monetary policy,
noted that the Fed already has made a series of small
credit-tightening steps from late March through late June, allowing
short term interest rates to rise.
   Nevertheless, inflationary pressures _ including tight labor
markets, high factory operating rates and drought-caused increases
in grain prices _ remain and must be curbed now rather than later,
he said.
   ``As the experience of the last two decades has clearly shown,
accelerating wages and prices would have to be countered later by
quite restrictive policies, with unavoidably adverse implications
for production and employment,'' Greenspan told the Senate Banking
Committee. He referred to the double-digit inflation that led to
the 1981-82 recession.
   When Greenspan last reported to Congress in February, the
situation was quite different. Many analysts were still worried
that the shock of the October stock market crash would tumble the
country into a recession. In late January, the central bank had
pushed short-term interest rates down a notch to stimulate economic
activity.
   However, Greenspan said, ``the economy proved remarkable
resilient'' and now, ``the long-run costs of a return to higher
inflation and the risks of this occurring under current
circumstances are sufficiently great that Federal Reserve policy at
this juncture might be well advised to err more on the side of
restrictiveness rather than of stimulus.''
   He said a leveling in the unemployment rate, which hit a 14-year
low of 5.3 percent last month, and in factory operating rates,
which are at eight-year highs, is ``essential if more intense
inflationary pressures are to be avoided in the period ahead.''
   The committee briefly interrupted Greenspan's testimony to
recommend by unanimous voice vote that the full Senate confirm
Boston banker John P. LaWare's appointment to a vacant seat on the
seven-member Federal Reserve Board.
   On another subject, Greenspan said the Federal Reserve and other
central banks would continue to work for stable international
exchange rates. He said he saw no evidence the growth of U.S.
exports has been affected by the appreciation of the dollar from
three-year lows at the end of last year.
   Credit markets rallied briefly in response to the testimony,
with bond prices edging up and interest rates falling slightly.
   Greenspan's anti-inflation message, which analysts found a bit
tougher than expected, spurred Sens. James Sasser, D-Ten., and Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, to plead with the central bank chairman not to
overreact.
   ``I would come down on the side of avoiding a recession almost
at all costs,'' Sasser said. ``I do hope the Fed would not be
hypersensitive to signs, real or imagined, of inflation.''
   David Wyss, chief financial economist of Data Resources Inc., a
forecasting firm in Lexington, Mass., said, ``I think Greenspan's
attitude can best be expressed by saying, `I don't think we need a
recession, but we're not going to fight so hard against a recession
that we risk inflation.' In other words, `We'll take a little
recession in order to avoid inflation.' ''
   Despite Greenspan's relatively tough rhetoric, Wyss said the
Federal Reserve would ``keep its head low during the election
campaign'' and will avoid its strongest tightening move, an
increase in the discount rate it charges on the money it loans to
member banks.
   The central bank has nudged the federal funds rate _ the amount
banks charge each other for overnight loans _ up by about a
percentage point so far this year to 7.5 percent, but it has not
raised the discount rate since September, when it was set at 6
percent.
   Greenspan acknowledged that the spread between the two rates has
widened, but said it is the judgment of Fed policymakers to date
that ``current relationships are satisfactory.''
   In the mid-year report, Greenspan said the Fed was boosting
slightly its forecast for economic growth this year. He said it was
looking for the gross national product to expand at an annual rate
of between 2.75 percent to 3 percent. In February, the Fed had a
lower GNP growth forecast of between 2 percent and 2.5 percent.
   Greenspan also warned that it is essential that Congress make
more progress in reducing the huge federal budget deficits. He said
such a cut would be the single most important thing government
could do to reduce the country's huge foreign borrowing needs. He
urged Congress to aim ultimately for budget surpluses sometime in
the 1990s.
</TEXT>
