<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--MotorcycleGlitch     07-13 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Motorcycle Glitch,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Law Leaves Hole In Motorcycle Training</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 5{ months, young people who want a
motorcycle license in Florida will be able to get one without
training, thanks to a glitch in a new law meant to toughen
instruction requirements.
   ``I guess if I were a young rider, I'd try to get my license
before January,'' said state Rep. Everett A. Kelly, who helped
draft the law.
   On Jan. 1, every motorcyclist 21 or younger will have to enroll
in at least six hours of on-cycle training and six hours of
classroom training to get a license.
   Since October, a four-hour training course had been required.
But when the new law took effect Friday, it repealed last year's
law without making any provision for the interim.
   ``We spent hours and hours drafting this legislation, and
apparently it got by our attorneys, our staff people and everyone
else,'' said Kelly. ``Sometimes these things get through.''
   Motorcyclists still must pass the written, driving and eye exams.
</TEXT>
