<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Trains     07-13 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Trains,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks and Whites Ride Together On Commuter Trains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks and whites on many
commuter trains rode together Wednesday for the first time, and a
Parliament member urged the government to extend integration to
buses and inter-city trains.
   The ``Whites Only'' signs on first-class train coaches started
coming down Tuesday in the Johannesburg and Durban metropolitan
areas, but many riders did not learn of the change until Wednesday.
   Commuter trains in the Cape Town area were desegregated last
month.
   ``From now on segregation will be based only on economic
principles,'' said J.C. van der Merwe, railroad manager in
Transvaal province for the state-run South African Transport
Services.
   Some blacks who rode the newly integrated first-class cars
Wednesday reported some unfriendly looks from white passengers, but
there were no reports of serious incidents.
   One white woman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said a
black man sat beside her during her morning ride into Johannesburg
and asked if she would be back on the train the next day. When she
replied affirmatively, the man inquired: ``Are you going to learn
Xhosa?''
   Xhosa is one of the four main African languages in South Africa.
   The transport service began integrating restrooms, waiting
areas, railroad cafeterias and other amenities at train stations in
1985. Most coaches continued to be segregated according to race,
although a few first-class trains were declared open to all.
   First-class tickets cost about twice as much as third-class
tickets. There is no second-class service.
   Ebrahim Abramjee, a member of the Asian chamber of Parliament,
praised the integration of commuter trains but condemned
authorities for maintaining segregation on long-distance train
routes and on buses in several major cities.
   He said ``whites only'' benches at bus stops in Pretoria were
also an embarrassment.
   ``Nothing can change overnight. We still have partial
segregation on the inter-city trains but it is being looked at...
We have to see what is practical,'' said Leon Els, a spokesman for
Transport Minister Eli Louw, referring to continued segregation on
the 120 inter-city trains.
   Els said one of the factors that has prevented integration of
inter-city trains is the fact that they ``are overnight trains and
people sleep in the compartments. People would be sleeping in a
compartment together.''
   An exception is the luxury, long-distance Blue Train that
travels between Johannesburg and Cape Town, which is designated as
an international service and has always been desegregated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
