<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraArms     07-13 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Arms,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Indicted For Sending Mercenaries to Help Contras</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother of Contra leader Adolfo Calero was
among seven men who allegedly broke U.S. neutrality laws by sending
mercenaries into combat in Nicaragua, according to an indictment
unsealed Wednesday.
   One group of mercenaries tried unsuccessfully to blow up a
bridge in Sinsin, Nicaragua, in 1985, but was forced out of the
country, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Schnapp.
   The long-awaited federal indictment, which at one point was
investigated by Congress on charges that then-Attorney General
Edwin Meese III tried to sidetrack the probe, did not mention any
Reagan administration officials.
   When reporters asked Interim U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen about
claims by some defendants that former National Security Council
aide Oliver North and Robert Owen, his liaison to Contra
operations, approved their operations, Lehtinen referred all
questions to the Iran-Contra independent counsel.
   The special prosecutor's office cannot comment on current
investigations, said Washington spokesman Jim Wiethart.
   Adolfo Calero's brother Mario Calero, of New Orleans, who has
been active in supplying the Contras, is accused of helping to
equip the mercenaries to battle the Sandinistas in Nicaragua.
   ``I shall wear this as one more badge to show that I am proud to
be a Contra,'' Mario Calero said Wednesday when he appeared before
a U.S. magistrate in Fort Lauderdale.
   His brother, one of the Contras' five directors, did not answer
calls to his Miami home Wednesday.
   Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros said Mario Calero was in charge
of the largest rebel group's procurement in New Orleans during the
1984-85 period the indictment covers.
   ``We were very aware of the Neutrality Law,'' said Matamoros.
``I think all these questions will be clarified.'' As for the
others indicted, he said only that ``many people in the past
provided help.''
   Also appearing before the magistrate Wednesday was Thomas Posey,
head of the Alabama-based Civilian Materiel Assistance, which
allegedly hired many of the mercenaries.
   His attorney called the indictment a farce. ``It's phenomenal
that after three years this is all they could come up with.
Everybody knew what these people were doing _ Rob Owen, the
National Security Council,'' Doug Jones said.
   The others indicted were Maco Stewart, a wealthy former
assistant state attorney general and a 1960-1963 state
representative in Texas; Jack Terrell, a former mercenary who
turned against U.S. Contra policy and has cooperated with the FBI
and the Congress; Jose Coutin, a gun store owner currently at a
halfway house on unrelated charges and a former Civilian Materiel
Assistance liaison; Alex Martinez, a conservative Miami
stockbroker, and Joe Adams, a former bodyguard to Adolfo Calero.
   Stewart, who now lives in France, was ordered released on a $5
million personal bond and allowed to return to Europe. The rest
received $25,000 bonds except for Adams, who was to surrender
later. Of the six who appeared Wednesday, all pleaded innocent
except Martinez and Terrell, who lacked permanent counsel.
   The indictment accuses the seven of violating the U.S.
Neutrality Act, which prohibits mounting operations against foreign
governments from U.S. soil. Adams and Terrell are also accused of
buying a Manlicher bolt-action .308 caliber rifle to be used as a
sniper weapon in Nicaragua. They could face up to 33 years in
prison. Coutin faces 13 years because he allegedly gave his
passport to a mercenary, while the rest face a maxmimum of eight
years on the two Neutrality Act violations.
   Critics of the investigation ridiculed the indictment, saying it
caught only the small fishes.
   ``Where are the policy-makers that put together this network?''
said John Mattes, a federal public defender whose investigation of
a client's case led to accusations that the U.S. attorney's office
tried to sidetrack the probe.
   He said it was ``a joke'' that with all the illegal Contra aid
shipped to the Contras, the only weapon mentioned was a bolt-action
rifle.
   ``This is the reward you get for bucking administration
policy,'' a bitter Terrell said Wednesday. ``It doesn't pay to be a
whistleblower in the United States.''
   The two-year investigation was the subject of charges a year ago
that Meese attempted to delay the probe to keep the
administration's illegal Contra supply operations from being
exposed. Congress investigated but issued an inconclusive report.
</TEXT>
