<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Greece-USBases     07-13 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-US Bases,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece Issues Formal Shut-Down Notice For U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday issued a
formal shut-down notice for the four United States military bases
operating in Greece.
   The notice is a legal formality that is not expected to result
in any of the bases being closed.
   Greek and American officials currently are negotiating a new
agreement on the bases to replace the existing accord, which
expires Dec. 31. The next round of talks will take place in Athens
later this month.
   ``The foreign ministry verbally informed the United States
Embassy of the Greek government's decision to terminate the Defense
and Economic Cooperation Agreement,'' government spokesman Sotiris
Kostopoulos said in a statement.
   According to the Greek interpretation of the current five-year
accord _ signed in 1983 by the United States and the socialist
government of Premier Andreas Papandreou _ Greece is obliged to
issue a notice terminating the agreement five months before it runs
out.
   Papandreou has said he is willing to sign a new agreement, but
insists it must be approved in a referendum.
   Greek officials say negotiations that started in November 1987
have made little progress.
   The four U.S. bases in Greece _ two near Athens and two on the
southern island of Crete _ have been operating since the early
1950s.
</TEXT>
