<DOCNO> AP880713-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0726 07-13 1148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,1100</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Dukakis Bids For Jackson Support; new material from news
conference with Bentsen and Bush material on veep search. Picks up
9th graf pvs ... ``I resented.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis mended fences with black leaders on Wednesday
and said he and his newly minted running mate, Lloyd Bentsen,
``hope and expect'' that Jesse Jackson will support the Democratic
ticket this fall.
   An angry Jackson broke off negotiations on the platform and
other convention issues, and aides said he was ``flabbergasted''
over a perceived snub in Dukakis' handling of his vice presidential
selection. ``It is now up to Michael Dukakis to make it a unity
convention,'' said Ron Brown, Jackson's convention manager.
   George Bush's search for a running mate was getting under way in
earnest. Campaign sources said the vice president likely will make
use of private polling to guage the vote-drawing appeal of various
potential ticket combinations, and a spokeswoman said Bush has no
intentions of ``parading people around'' for auditions.
   Meanwhile, the White House announced that Bush would travel to
the United Nations on Thursday to present the U.S. explanation on
destruction of an Iranian airliner. Bush said he ``can't wait'' to
argue ``the free world's case'' before the Security Council.
   With the Democratic convention just five days off, Dukakis and
Bentsen made their campaign rounds in Washington and at an
afternoon news conference Dukakis was peppered with questions about
``Jackson.''
   At first he tried to make light of the issue, saying, ``I
haven't talked to Michael Jackson in months.'' He went on to say,
``I want Jesse Jackson to be deeply involved in this campaign as a
party leader.''
   ``We want his support,'' the Massachusetts governor said. ``We
hope and expect he will be very much involved with us in the
campaign and afterwards.''
   Some black leaders urged reconciliation, including the chairman
of the Congressional Black Caucus. ``Lots of fences have been
mended,'' Rep. Mervyn Dymally of California said after a closed
door session with Dukakis and Bentsen.
   Rep. Bill Gray, D-Pa., a senior black House member, said he had
been disappointed that Jackson was not the choice for No. 2. ``But
it's been made, and I plan to support the ticket,'' Gray said.
   But not all of Jackson's backers were persuaded. Atlanta City
councilman Hosea Williams, a nationally known civil rights activist
but not always an ally of Jackson, announced plans for a protest
march to the convention next Monday. ``It's not that they turned
Jesse Jackson down, it's how they did it,'' he said.
   Two Democratic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Jackson was told privately Monday afternoon that he would not be
picked. One source said Dukakis emissary Paul Brountas told Jackson
``he would bring the ticket down'' if nominated for vice president.
   Jackson didn't learn of Bentsen's selection until reporters
asked him for a comment Tuesday morning, and the perceived snub had
Jackson and his followers still seething on Wednesday.
   At his news conferencein Washington, Dukakis said he had tried
to notify Jackson by telephone of his selection of Bentsen, but
failed to reach him before word leaked out. When the two men
finally spoke, Dukakis said, ``I said I was sorry that I missed him
on the first call.''
   Bentsen said he had spoken with Jackson by phone earlier in the
day. ``Jesse Jackson is a friend of mine and he is a very able
gentleman,'' said the Texan.
   But not all of Jackson's supporters sounded ready for
reconciliation.
   ``I resented being talked to by the runt of the Democratic
political litter who did not have the courtesy to consult Jackson,
to let him know prior to the time the public knew,'' said Vera
Baugh, a delegate to the NAACP convention where Dukakis and Bentsen
spoke.
   ``To me that was a slap in my face and I am going to write in
Jesse's name. I will not vote for Dukakis,'' she said. Jackson, for
his part, had said he planned to support the ticket but would have
his name placed in nomination for president.
   Dukakis sought throughout the day to soothe any hurt feelings,
with only occasional success.
   He linked arms with members of the NAACP and sang ``We Shall
Overcome,'' and told the organization's convention in Washington
that the Democratic Party had ``opened up the door of opportunity
to a couple of guys named Dukakis and Jackson, the top two
candidates for the presidency.''
   When NAACP president Benjanim Hooks told the Democratic
nominee-in-waiting that ``knowing Jesse has been good for you,''
the Massachusetts governor replied, ``I've learned a lot from Jesse
and I've learned a lot from you.''
   Dukakis said Bentsen had been a civil rights advocate since
``way back in the 40s,'' but some in the audience booed when the
Texas senator took the microphone to speak.
   Hooks appealed for a warmer welcome, then turned the jeers to
laughter in saying, ``I empathize with you. ... I've been preaching
when they wanted somebody else to preach. One said, `We ain't going
to say Amen one time.' They didn't.''
   ``... Many of our delegates, as you know, wanted to see Jesse in
this position,'' he said. At that mention of Jackson's name, the
audience erupted in cheers and applause.
   The Democratic convention city was beginning to fill up with the
advance wave of party officials and journalists. Construction
continued inside the smallish Omni hall _ where some seats afforded
no view of the proceedings on the floor _ but party officials said
all would be ready by the time the opening gavel fell next Monday.
   Ready, perhaps, but not necessarily peaceful.
   Dukakis and Bentsen received a rousing reception from House
Democrats when they met early in the day. ``He sent one single
message,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. ``He wants to work with us
and reach out to us. That's what the Congress wants to hear.''
   Others were finding their disappointment harder to overcome.
   Jackson said nothing publicly during the day about Dukakis'
choice of the 67-year-old Bentsen to be his vice presidential
candidate.
   But campaign aide Brown spread the word that the runner-up in
the primary campaign was incredulous that Dukakis had not consulted
him over the choice of Bentsen, and had not informed him before the
word was made public.
   ``It seems like too big a mistake that politically astute people
would make,'' said Brown.
   He said negotiations over platform disagreements have been
suspended, at least temporarily.
   Privately, some were urging Jackson not to overreact to the
perceived snub. ``I don't think it's in Jesse's interest to get
into a fight about protocol, and have his constituents talking
about no respect, no respect,'' said one influential black
politician.
   ``What if Dukakis loses and people can point to this episode as
one of the reasons. Then Jesse has just kicked over his pail of
milk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
