<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-Nicaragua-Chronology     07-13 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nicaragua-Chronology,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chronology of US-Nicaragua Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of recent U.S.-Nicaraguan relations:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1979</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JULY 17 _ Anastasio Somoza, Nicaraguan president, resigns and
ends more than four decades of rightist, pro-American rule by his
family. Two days later, leftist Sandinista rebels enter Managua.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1982-1983</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reports emerge alleging covert U.S. aid to anti-Sandinista rebel
Contras. Nicaragua claims violations of its territory by U.S. spy
planes and warships.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1984</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   APRIL _ Congressional sources say CIA is involved in military
action against Sandinista government by supervising mining of
Nicaraguan ports. Nicaragua files complaint at World Court against
United States, charging U.S. efforts ``to coerce and intimidate''
Nicaragua through support of Contra forces.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1985</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   MAY 1 _ President Reagan announces trade embargo against
Nicaragua.
   AUGUST _ Enactment of foreign-aid bill resuming direct aid to
Contras, $27 million in ``non-lethal'' assistance.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1986</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 25 _ After intensive lobbying by Reagan, House approves
$100 million in military and humanitarian aid to Contras. Senate
approves package two months later.
   JUNE 27 _ World Court denounces U.S.-sponsored military actions
against Nicaragua and U.S. support for Contras as violation of U.N.
Charter's ban on use of force.
   OCT. 5 _ Military cargo plane is shot down in Nicaragua, killing
two Americans. Surviving crew member Eugene Hasenfus is captured
and implicates CIA in Contra-supply operation. Hasenfus released
two months later.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   FEB. 18 _ Senate Foreign Relations Committee votes narrowly to
halt U.S. aid to Contras.
   AUG. 7 _ Five Central American presidents sign peace plan
calling for cease-fires and additional steps toward democratization
in effort to end guerrilla wars in Nicaragua and elsewhere in
region.
   DEC. 3 _ Indirect talks between Sandinista government and
Contras begin.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JANUARY _ Responding to pressure from other Central American
nations, Sandinistas agree to direct talks with Contras. Nicaragua
lifts 6-year-old state of emergency and begins face-to-face
negotiations with Contras.
   MAR. 17 _ U.S. troops arrive in Honduras as show of force
against Nicaragua, whose forces reportedly have crossed Honduran
border in offensive against Contra rebels.
   MAR. 23 _ Sandinista leaders and Contra representatives announce
cease-fire plan that would end war by May 31.
   MAY 31 _ After several runds of talks that fail to produce any
agreement, the truce ends. Cease-Fire extensions are announced.
   JUNE 9 _ In the latest break-off of negotiations, Contras reject
a Sandinista plan. Both sides report numerous violations of
cease-fire in following weeks.
   JULY 11 _ Nicaragua orders expulsion of U.S. ambassador and
seven other diplomats one day after police clash with thousands of
demonstraters at anti-Sandinista rally. Government closes down
opposition newspaper La Prensa and Catholic radio station.
   JULY 12 _ U.S. retaliates, ordering Nicaraguan ambassador and
seven others out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
