<DOCNO> AP880713-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0724 07-13 0970</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0724,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Greeted With Praise from Congress, Cool Reaction from
NAACP</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Dukakis news conference;
pick up 2nd graf pvs, There were; edits to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, a week away from receiving
the Democratic presidential nomination, brushed aside Wednesday
complaints that he was tardy notifying Jesse Jackson of his vice
presidential selection and said he wanted Jackson to be ``deeply
involved in this campaign as a party leader.''
   With his designated running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas,
at his side, Dukakis told a news conference on Capitol Hill that he
was unable to reach Jackson by telephone Tuesday morning to notify
him of his vice presidential decision.
   As a result, Jackson did not learn of the choice until asked
about it by reporters when he arrived at Washington's National
Airport.
   In Atlanta where Democrats were making final preparations for
the opening of the party's national convention on Monday, Jackson
convention manager Ron Brown said he was ``flabbergasted'' by the
failure to notify Jackson and said he had broken off negotiations
aimed at settling differences over platform issues.
   ``That's okay,'' said Dukakis when asked about the halt in
negotiations. ``If people want to debate certain issues, they have
a perfect right to.''
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis and Bentsen received a cool
reception from delegates to the annual convention of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   ``I thought it was terrific,'' said the Massachusetts governor.
``I understand many of the people in the room were actively
involved in the Jesse Jackson campaign and they were disappointed.''
   He said Jackson would have received a similar response had he
gone before a Greek-American group after defeating Dukakis in a
fight for the presidential nomination.
   ``I want Jesse Jackson to be actively involved in this campaign
as a party leader,'' said Dukakis. ``I hope and expect he will be.''
   Bentsen said he had talked to Jackson by telephone Wednesday
morning ``to establish communications.'' He gave no further details
of the conversation.
   There were scattered boos when Dukakis introduced Bentsen to the
NAACP convention. And many delegates sat silently when Dukakis
first entered the room and was introduced by NAACP executive
director Benjamin Hooks.
   A little more than 12 hours earlier, the same hotel ballroom was
packed with delegates who leapt to their feet repeatedly to cheer
and applaud Jackson.
   The Massachusetts governor flew to the capital with Bentsen for
a day of joint appearances before members of Congress as well as
the speech to the NAACP.
   The pair met for abou 45 minutes with members of the
Congressional Black Caucus. ``It went well,'' Bentsen said as he
emerged, and the comments of black House members generally
reflected that assessment.
   ``Lots of fences have been mended,'' said caucus chairman Rep.
Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif. ``We had a very fruitful discussion about
the convention, the campaign and the presidency.''
   ``It's a strong ticket. It's a winning ticket,'' said Rep. John
Lewis, D-Ga., adding: ``It was very friendly in the room.''
   Dymally said Dukakis offered an explanation for why Jackson was
not notified of his selection of Bentsen as vice presidential
running mate before it was made public on Tuesday, saying he sought
to call Jackson first but was unable to reach him because Jackson
had left his hotel.
   But for some members, it wasn't enough.
   ``I was disappointed,'' said Rep. Major Owens, D-N.Y., who said
he had hoped for some specific commitment to at least symbolically
show that Jackson would be a special third member of the ticket.
   The way Jackson learned of the No. 2 choice was ``a
demonstration of disrespect,'' Owens said, and Dukakis' account
``was a lame explanation.''
   After the designated Democratic ticket met with House Democrats,
Speaker Jim Wright of Texas said the session evoked ``real
enthusiasm.''
   ``I think Dukakis and Bentsen together can deliver Texas,'' said
Wright.
   The session was closed as were later meetings with Senate
Democrats and the Congressional Black Caucus.
   Dukakis was returning to Boston Wednesday night where he still
was looking for about $100 million in spending cuts to bring his
state budget into balance.
   Current plans called for the Massachusetts governor to fly to
Houston, Texas, on Sunday for a rally with Bentsen after which the
two would fly together to Atlanta where the Democratic National
Convention will nominate them for president and vice president.
   The roll call for the presidential nomination, with Dukakis and
Jackson as the only names before the convention, will take place
Wednesday night. The following night the convention will be asked
to ratify Dukakis' choice of Bentsen as the vice presidential
nominee.
   Many delegates at the NAACP convention said they were angry over
the fact Dukakis did not notify Jackson of his decision on the vice
presidency before it was made public.
   Beulah C. Wright of Main Line, Pa., said Dukakis had been ``very
rude'' to Jackson. Asked if she would vote for the Dukakis-Bentsen
ticket, she replied, ``I'm going to have to think about that. When
you put him against Bush, I probably will.''
   ``To me that was a slap in the face,'' said Vera Baugh of
Pasadena, Calif. ``I am going to write in Jesse's name. I will not
vote for Dukakis.''
   In Atlanta, Jackson convention manager Ron Brown said, ``We were
flabbergasted by the way this was handled.'' He said, ``It is now
up to Michael Dukakis to make this a unity convention.''
   After Dukakis entered the room to subdued applause, the first
burst of enthusiasm came when Hooks turned to the governor and
said, ``You know, knowing Jesse has been good for you.''
   ``I've learned a lot from Jesse,'' said Dukakis. ``And I've
learned a lot from you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Text 1stAdd   07-13 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Text, 1st Add,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: your guest.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Four weeks ago, I, too, had the privilege of addressing an
audience of mostly young people, although it was a much smaller one
than Dr. King spoke to in 1959. It included the members of the
first graduating class at the new campus of the Roxbury Community
College in the City of Boston. A sumbol to all of us in my state of
educational opportunity, of economic opportunity of the future for
young people in our city and in our state. And there, I felt not
only the sense of pride and accomplishment of those young
graduates, I felt the pride of an entire community, and I was very
proud to have been a part of building that campus and making that
opportunity available to those young people and to their community.
I felt the pride of mothers and fathers who had worked so hard for
years so that children would have a chance to wear a cap and gown.
I saw the pride of youngsters who would now have to look no further
than to their older brothers and sisters for the inspiration to
work hard and to stay in school. I could feel the pride of teachers
who had helped to unlock the door of opportunity for a generation
of their community's young. I could sense all around me pride of
the people of Roxbury about that beautiful new college campus it
could call its own. And I thought to myself that morning, this is
what it's all about. This is what public service is all about. This
is what leadership is all about. This is what all of us are all
about. Expanding the circle of opportunity, deepening the sense of
community, building pride, making a real difference in the lives of
real people. This is how you create a new world, and this is how
we're going to make the American dream come true for every single
citizen in this country, no matter who they are or where they come
from or what the color of their skin. And this, my friends, is what
the election of 1988 is all about.
   Over the past 16 months, I've campaigned from one end of this
country to another, campaigned with many of you. I've met you, I've
sat down with you. We've talked together. And I know, and you know
that some neighborhoods and some communities in this country of
ours are doing very, very well. But opportunity for some isn't the
goal we set for America. And maintaining the status quo, running in
place, standing still, isn't the kind of future we want for our
country. We want to grow, we want to keep growing, and we want to
grow together. We want to grow together as one nation, one
community, one family.
   This fall, the American people will be asked to choose between
two very different styles of leadership, between two very different
records of public achievement, between two very different ideas of
how to build the best America. My friends, some people say we need
Star Wars. I say we need star schools. That's what we need for the
youngsters of this country. Some people want to overthrow
governments in Central America. I want to create jobs in middle
America. That's what this election is all about.
   Some candidates are worried about where we went to college. I
care about whether our children will have the chance to go to
college and can afford the tuition. Some people say we can't create
opportunity for all Americans and build a strong national economy
at the same time. I say nonsense to that. Opportunity for all and a
healthy and growing economy go hand in hand.
   I've been my state's chief executive for 10 years. I've been in
public service for a quarter of a century, and let me say I'm proud
of it. I'm proud of the fact that my vocation is public service,
and I hope I can encourage thousands and thousands of young people
in this country to go into public service as president of the
United States.
</TEXT>
