<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Hay     07-13 0118</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Hay,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Approves Emergency Hay Harvesting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers in counties not hit by drought may
harvest hay under various government acreage and conservation
programs if they donate it to those in drought-stricken areas,
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng announced Wednesday.
   Previously, hay could be taken only from idled program land in
counties approved for emergency haying or grazing due to drought.
There are nearly 2,000 of those designated counties in 37 states.
   A producer who wishes to donate hay should contact the local
office of the department's Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service for harvesting permission, Lyng said.
   The farmer than must donate the hay through a designated state
agency engaged in drought relief efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
