   And I know that if we're going to take on and beat our foreign
competition, if we're going to make the label ``Made in America''
once again the hallmark of quality and value and durability, if
we're going to be the No. 1 and stay No. 1, we're going to need all
of our people.
   That means that the children who enter school in this fall in
Philadelphia, in Birmingham and Detroit, and in towns and cities
all over America, must be the best prepared, the best skilled, and
the best educated in the world. It means that we've got to give
those citizens of ours who happen to be on public assistance real
training for real jobs and quality day care for their children, if
we're going to help them to lift themselves out of poverty and to
become independent and self-sufficient, and Senator Bentsen is one
of the leaders in the Congress that is right now attempting to do
that.
   It means we've got to do for the nation what I'm proud to say we
have already done in my state. Last April, I became the first
governor in the history of this country to sign legislation that
will guarantee basic health insurance to every single citizen in my
state. And if one state can do it, ladies and gentlement, we should
be able to do it for the entire United States of America. We have
40 million Americans, most of them members of working families who
don't have a dime of health insurance, 40 years after Harry Truman,
in this city, said that basic health insurance and basic heath
security should be the birthright of every American. And we're
going to work hard, beginning in January of 1989, with you and with
the Congress of the United States, to make good on that commitment
that President Truman made some 40 years ago.
