<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     07-13 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamadi Admits Smuggling Explosives And Being Amal Fighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese man on trial for the
1985 hijacking of a TWA airliner to Beirut testified Wednesday that
he fought with a Moslem militia in Lebanon and smuggled explosives
into West Germany.
   In his first statement to a Frankfurt court, Mohammed Ali Hamadi
said he fought for two years with the Shiite Amal militia in Beirut.
   But he denied belonging to the radical pro-Iranian Moslem group
Hezbollah, or Party of God, which is believed to be the umbrella
group for kidnappers holding Western hostages in Lebanon.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite, is charged with murder and air piracy
in the June 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner on an Athens-to-Rome
flight.
   U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem of Waldorf, Md., was shot and
killed after the hijackers forced the plane to land in Beirut.
Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage during the 17-day ordeal.
   One of Hamadi's brothers, Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, is chief of
security for Hezbollah in Beirut. Another brother, Abbas Ali
Hamadi, was convicted in April of kidnapping two West Germans in
Lebanon in an attempt to win freedom for Mohammed Hamadi. He was
sentenced to 13 years in prison by a Duesseldort court.
   During Wednesday's session, Mohammed Hamadi refused to answer
questions relating to the hijacking or to his brother Abdul-Hadi.
   ``I am not a member of the Hezbollah,'' Hamadi said in Arabic.
His comments were translated into German by a court-appointed
interpreter.
   Hamadi told the court he had smuggled liquid explosives into
West Germany twice, contradicting a statement he made to police
after his January 1987 arrest at Frankfurt airport. At the time,
Hamadi told police he thought the bottles were filled with alcohol
and denied knowing they contained explosives.
   He insisted he was not told why the explosives were being
smuggled into West Germany. ``A certain person asked me to smuggle
them in and hide them,'' Hamadi said. ``I did it twice. The second
time I was arrested.''
   ``I don't know the reason why the explosives were brought in,''
he said. ``I was not told.''
   Hamadi said his statements to police after his arrest were made
under duress. He alleged that West German interrogators threatened
him with extradition to the United States if he did not cooperate.
   West Germany's refusal to extradite Hamadi later led to
temporarily strained relations between Bonn and Washington.
   Hamadi also contended he was one or two years younger than
official documents indicate.
   The court is trying to determine Hamadi's age at the time the
hijacking was being planned to determine whether he will be tried
as a juvenile, a young adult or an adult. Depending on the
classification, he could receive from 15 years to life in prison if
convicted.
   ``The passport which I had when I came to West Germany in 1982
listed the year of my birth as 1964,'' Hamadi told the court. ``But
that date is false. I am one or two years younger, but I can't give
an exact date.''
   He said he believed his father had altered his birth date to get
additional child support from the Lebanese goverment.
   Hamadi said he was an Amal militiaman between 1980 and 1982, but
left after becoming disillusioned with the group's leadership.
   Hamadi's testimony about his past with Amal would make him a
teen-age street fighter in war-torn Beirut. According to Hamadi, he
would have been 14 or 15 when he joined Amal. Official court
documents have him as 16.
   ``I was forced (by cirumstances) to carry weapons,'' Hamadi
said. ``I wanted to fight against Israel.'' He said he did not know
if he killed anyone.
   Hamadi is being tried under heavy security in a specially
constructed prison courtroom. Officials have scheduled court days
into December and say more could be added.
   One of the hostages Hamadi's brother was convicted of
kidnapping, engineer Alfred Schmidt, was released in September
1987. The second, Rudolf Cordes, a businessman, is still being held
in Beirut.
   The longest-held foreign hostage in Lebanon is Terry Anderson,
chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
