<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-13 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLAND, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A horse is a horse, of course, of
course. Unless it's a mule. And that's what Jezebel is even though
he's winning top honors in the Nebraska State 4-H Horse Show.
   The 3-year-old mule earned a red ribbon Wednesday in the pony
pleasure competition on Wednesday. A mule is the offspring of a
donkey and a horse.
   Jezebel, owned by Gene Daniel of Stanton, won blue ribbons in
pony pleasure and western horsemanship at district competition to
qualify for the state show.
   R.B. Warren, extension 4-H horse specialist at the University of
Nebraska-Lincoln, said Jezebel is the first mule to show at
district shows or to qualify for the state show in its 25-year
history.
   Mules have a reputation for stubborness, but Daniel said Jezebel
isn't necessarily stubborn.
   ``Once you get something through to her, she remembers it a lot
longer (than a horse),'' Daniel said. ``But it takes twice as long.
Once it's done, they'll never forget.''
   Daniel, 19, said he gets some curious looks when he rides the
mule, and horses look at Jezebel funny when she starts to bray.
   Daniel said he grew up with horses but said mules have won him
over.
   ``I won't buy another horse for quite awhile,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KEARNEY, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   'Tis the season to be hot and sweaty _
except at interstate rest stops where 'tis the season to celebrate
Christmas in July.
   ``It's been so hot,'' vacation guide Dawn Wisdom said Tuesday.
``We are just reminding them it will be cold again before they know
it.''
   The sign in her information booth at the Interstate 80 stop near
Kearney in central Nebraska says there are only 166 shopping days
until Christmas.
   There is a tiny Christmas tree with blinking lights, silver
garland and two bright red reindeer. Christmas stockings have been
hung by the railing with care and Wisdom is passing out peppermint
candy.
   ``It's the only Christmas-type candy I could find,'' said Ms.
Wisdom, who was decked out in a red blouse and hat for a lunch-hour
Christmas carol fest.
   Christmas in July is being celebrated at all 24 rest stops along
Nebraska's insterstate system, Wisdom said. But guides at each stop
can determine how they want to celebrate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennis buffs in this exclusive community
might find it hard to practice at night without a partner. That's
because the town has restricted the use of noisy tennis ball
serving machines.
   Town Council gave final approval Tuesday to an ordinance
limiting the use of the electric servers. Town officials had
considered an outright ban.
   ``The council received several complaints from people who found
the noise obnoxious and a nuisance,'' town attorney John Randolph
said Wednesday.
   ``We don't anticipate that this is a great problem in the town
or that it will have to be used very often.''
   Palm Beach was lampooned by Garry Trudeau in ``Doonesbury'' for
a law requiring workers to carry ID cards. That law was declared
unconstitutional. The ordinance prohibiting men from topless
jogging also was struck down.
   The tennis ball machine ordinance limits their use to the same
weekday, daytime hours set aside for heavy construction.
   The regulation will be enforced only if there are complaints,
officials said. The maximum fine is $250.
</TEXT>
