<HEAD>Egypt Refuses To Return Two Egyptians Wanted in Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt has notified the United States it will
not return two military officers wanted for questioning in a
technology smuggling investigation.
   But the State Department said Wednesday it would await the
results of a promised Egyptian investigation before making any
judgment.
   Egypt promised to ``share the results'' with U.S. authorities,
Phyllis Oakley, the department spokeswoman, said.
   Federal officials last month alleged a conspiracy to export the
chemical carbon-carbon, which is used to make missile nose cones
and stealth aircraft less visible to radar.
   Lt. Col. Mohammed Abdella Mohammed, who was assigned to the
Egyptian Embassy in Washington, was arrested in Baltimore and then
released after claiming diplomatic immunity.
   He then went home to Cairo. Another Egyptian military
procurement official, Adm. Abdel Rahim Elgohary, also was called
home in the wake of the charges.
   Although Elgohary was not charged in the case, the Customs
Service mentioned him in an affidavit as having played a role.
</TEXT>
