<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TunnermannProfile     07-13 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tunnermann Profile,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Ambassador Was Not Managua's First Choice</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann, who
is being expelled by the Reagan administration, has served here 3{
years, but he was not the Sandinista government's first choice for
the post.
   Initially, Nicaragua had intended to appoint Deputy Foreign
Minister Nora Astorga as ambassador, but the Reagan administration
refused to accept her because of her role in the 1978 slaying of a
high-ranking officer in the National Guard of deposed President
Anastasio Somoza.
   The Sandinistas then decided send Tunnermann, who was education
minister at the time, to the embassy in Washington. Two previous
Sandinista ambassadors to Washington had defected but Tunnermann,
54, has worked tirelessly in support of his leftist government.
Initially, he was plagued by his limited knowledge of English, but
he has largely overcome that problem.
   He also is Nicaragua's ambassador to the Organization of
American States here.
   Before becoming education minister, Tunnermann was rector of the
University of Nicaragua for two years and an official in Colombia
with the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization.
   He is married and the father of eight children. The family has
lived in a fashionable area of suburban Maryland.
   Short in stature with an amiable manner, Tunnermann pressed hard
for an improvement in U.S.-Nicaraguan relations. But the Reagan
administration insisted that a clear demonstration of Sandinista
interest in democracy must come first. As a result, Tunnermann
seldom has had an opportunity to deal on matters of substance with
administration officials.
   Last December, at a State Department Christmas party, Adolfo
Calero, a leader of the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, extended his hand
in friendship to Tunnermann but the envoy rejected the gesture.
   He urged Calero to take up the Nicaraguan government's offer of
amnesty to the rebels, then walked away.
   Tunnermann has been ordered to leave the United States by Friday
as a result of State Department claims that he engaged in
``abuses'' during his stay here.
   The administration has refused to provide details. Tunnermann
has denied any wrongdoing.
   The decision to oust Tunnermann and seven colleagues came after
the Sandinistas expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton and seven
of his aides from Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1722EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-Analysis Bjt   07-13 0896</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Analysis, Bjt,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Road with Jackson: Where Does It End?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, his 1988 presidential campaign
winding down, takes to the road Thursday en route to the Democratic
National Convention _ while angry supporters search for a signal of
how he will end his remarkable effort.
   The possibilities range from unity to confrontation.
   Jackson's words and actions as he finally acknowledges Michael
Dukakis' victory _ and Lloyd Bentsen spot on the ticket _ will not
only shape the tone of the Democratic National Convention here
starting Monday. They will also mold the enthusiasm that his
supporters give to the Democratic ticket in the fall.
   Will Jackson push floor fights on the platform on Tuesday night
at the convention? Will he push on to the presidential nomination
roll-call on Wednesday? Or will he condone supporters' suggestions
that his name be on the vice presidential roll-call as well?
   ``I'm not suggesting that I will compete for a place on the
ticket but the floor is wide open on Thursday night when the (vice
presidential) recommendation is made,'' Jackson said in Chicago on
Wednesday.
   That's as much of a sign as Jackson has delivered in the 24
hours after Jackson was embarrassed by Dukakis' failure to reach
him before word circulated of the selection of Lloyd Bentsen as the
vice presidential nominee.
   Jackson learned of the Bentsen selection from a reporter Tuesday
morning. Publicly, his aides have said they were flabbergasted by
the ``major miscalculation,'' and on Wednesday they spread the word
to suspend all convention negotiations between the Dukakis and
Jackson campaigns.
   ``You can assume we have the wherewithal to make our presence
felt on everything that happens at the convention,'' said Jackson
convention manager Ron Brown.
   It is clear that it is not clear what Jackson will do.
   It is clear his supporters are upset.
   ``They still expect him to be a good old boy and get out the
vote. Well, respect that good old boy,'' said Melinease Hutchinson
of Norfolk, Va. ``Dukakis should have given Jesse the respect of
making certain he personally informed him.''
   ``It's not that they turned Jesse Jackson down, it's how they
did it,'' said Atlanta City Councilman Hosea Williams said,
accusing Dukakis of an ``un-American racial injustice ...
perpetrated upon millions of American voters'' who voted for
Jackson for president.
   Williams plans a march Monday outside the convention hall to
protest.
   Jackson himself has put up only veiled cues as to his plans.
   In an emotional speech to the annual meeting of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People in Washington on
Tuesday, Jackson reached a peak of intensity by declaring over and
over again his effort will culminate in the presidential roll call.
   ``When my name goes in nomination, our struggle is being
vindicated,'' he said. ``We go to Atlanta not to smile and style
and profile, but to deliberate and debate our nation's priorities.''
   But one Jackson aide warned against reading too much into any
general Jackson rhetoric.
   This aide said that Jackson himself is still deciding on
tactics, decisions he will work through on the three-day bus trip
starting Thursday in Chicago and ending Saturday in Atlanta.
   As Jackson pondered, Dukakis and Bentsen moved Wednesday to try
to minimize the squabble.
   Dukakis, the Democratic nominee-in-waiting, denied Wednesday
that any insult had been intended by the communications foul-up.
And he said he apologized when he did talk to Jackson.
   ``I told him how sorry I was I hadn't been able to get through
to him,'' Dukakis told a Capitol Hill news conference.
   One Jackson aide, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said
there is an emotional reaction within the campaign that the slight
was intentional. But this aide said Jackson believes Dukakis
decided to lump him in with all the other also-rans for the vice
presidency, setting up the current furor.
   It is also true that some of the public anger is public
posturing on the part of shrewd politicians looking for advantage
in the endgame of the Democratic nomination process.
   ``He's probably allowing some of his people to beat up (on the
phone call issue) because he's still negotiating on some other
issues,'' said one Jackson adviser would not be quoted by name.
   The current furor _ however interesting for the political
insiders _ has to be put in the perspective of Jackson's entire
1988 campaign.
   He has run a professional, disciplined effort, aimed at building
his own coalition and the party at the same time. The divisive
rhetoric of his 1984 effort has not been heard in 1988.
   It is unlikely that Jackson would tear down the respect he has
earned from many inside the party with a final angry gesture that
could hurt the Democratic chances in the fall.
   ``We go down to a convention where Democrats get together to put
their ticket together. That's going to be a positive act and Jesse
Jackson's going to be a positive leader,'' said Jackson adviser Ann
Lewis on Wednesday. ``Again, you're going to see a Jesse Jackson
who is forward-looking, who's talking about the fall, who's talking
about the issues. That's what's important and that's what's at
stake.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITORS' NOTE: Evans Witt is a Washington-base political writer
who covered both the 1984 and the 1988 campaigns of Jesse Jackson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
