<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel     07-13 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Die Of Wounds, One Injured In Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinian teen-agers died Wednesday of
bullet wounds suffered in earlier clashes with Israeli troops, and
a Palestinian was wounded by army gunfire in new battles in the
West Bank, hospital officials said.
   In south Lebanon, meanwhile, Israeli paratroopers on a
search-and-destroy mission clashed with Arab guerrillas, and the
army said three guerrillas and one Israeli were killed in the
firefight.
   In newly released figures, the chief military prosecutor said
2,800 Palestinians are being detained for up to six months without
charges, up about 300 from last month, Israel army radio reported.
In addition, about 3,000 Palestinians are being held on charges of
anti-Israeli violence.
   Also Wednesday, the army blew up two homes of Arabs suspected of
throwing firebombs and stones at Israeli targets, and it sealed
four other houses.
   In another development, the army said it has opened an
investigation into reports that soldiers brutally beat Arabs in the
Gaza Strip twice this month.
   In one incident, troops were suspected of throwing the victims
into cactus bushes after beating them, the daily Haaretz reported.
   In the second case, troops allegedly beat four Palestinians,
then took them to military headquarters, where they forced them to
lie on the ground and trampled on their fingers, the newspaper said.
   Troops opened fire Wednesday on Palestinians in the West Bank
city of Nablus to disperse protests started by news that two Arab
youths wounded Monday had died of their injuries, an Arab reporter
said.
   A Palestinian was seriously wounded by a bullet to the stomach
in the clash, said officials at Nablus' Ittihad Hospital.
   Samir Sayah, 16, who also was shot in the stomach in a clash
with troops Monday, died of his wounds Wednesday, the officials
said.
   Amjad Deed Nafea, 18, who was shot in the chest in Monday's
fighting in Nablus, died Wednesday at Jerusalem's Mukassad
Hospital, officials there said.
   The fatalities brought to 222 the number of Palestinians killed
in the 7-month-old uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Four Israelis have died since the violence began.
   In the West Bank villages of Ras Karkar and Janiyeh near
Ramallah, the army blew up two homes belonging to three Arabs
suspected of throwing a firebomb at an army patrol June 9. Two
officers were badly burned in the attack. The Ras Karkar home of a
fourth suspect in the attack was sealed, the army said.
   Troops also sealed three homes in the northern West Bank village
of Atil. The homes belonged to Palestinians suspected of stoning
and torching buses in April, the army said.
   In southern Lebanon, about 60 Israeli soldiers and allied
Lebanese Christian militiamen intercepted a group of pro-Iranian
Shiite Moslems belonging to Hezbollah, or Party of God, who were
planning a cross-border raid against Israel, police said.
   The brief battle occurred near the village of Qillaya, 10 miles
north of the Israeli-Lebanese border, the army and television
reports said.
   The trooper who died was the eighth Israeli soldier killed in
clashes near the Israeli-Lebanese border this year. About 30
Israeli soldiers have been wounded. According to Israeli reports,
more than 110 guerrillas and nine South Lebanon Army militiamen
have been killed this year.
   Israel established a six-to-10 mile security zone north of the
border after it withdrew most of its troops from Lebanon in 1985
following a three-year occupation. The strip has been the target of
frequent attacks by Palestinian and Shiite Moslem guerrillas.
</TEXT>
