<DOCNO> AP880713-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Marcos     07-13 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Marcos,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Seeks Consultations on Marcos Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House has asked to be consulted
before any attempt by the Justice Department to obtain an
indictment of former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos, a
spokesman said Wednesday.
   Marlin Fitzwater said he could not confirm a published report
that U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani recommended a grand jury
indictment of Marcos and his wife Imelda in connection with their
New York real estate holdings.
   Fitzwater did say, however, ``we have told the Justice
Department that before indictments are issued, the White House does
want to review the matter.''
   Fitzwater said there was nothing irregular or unusual about the
practice of giving the White House some consultation before seeking
an indictment which could have foreign policy overtones or
consequences.
   The spokesman acknowledged that the White House doesn't ``have
veto power'' over a Justice Department decision to seek an
indictment.
   ``However, this is a matter that has foreign policy
implications,'' the spokesman said. ``We want to review it for that
reason and we certainly would make our views known to the Justice
Department.''
   Fitzwater would not specify why the White House thought the
indictment of the deposed Philippines president would be sensitive.
   But he did say ``it is a matter that, as you know, the
circumstances in which he left the Philippines, that he has been
given certain assurances by the United States in regard to that
departure.''
   ``And he also still has influence and contacts in that part of
the world,'' Fitzwater added, ``so there are any number of foreign
policy issues that need to be considered.''
   Asked whether Marcos had been assured by U.S. officials that he
would not be indicted in this country when he fled the Philippines
in 1986, the spokesman replied, ``I don't know what assurances he
was given.''
   ``I think this is a routine request and not a specific one,''
Fitzwater said.
   He told a reporter that one reason the White House was seeking
consultations with the Justice Department is that President Reagan
and top officials were blind-sided by the indictments handed up by
federal grand juries in Tampa and Miami, Fla., against Panamanian
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``It's mostly an internal thing,'' the spokesman said. Fitzwater
said that staff members of the National Security Council had been
aware of the plan to indict Noriega, but had not made this known to
superiors.
   ``It was clear that we needed to strengthen the process to make
sure those kinds of things are brought to the full attention of the
NSC,'' which Reagan heads.
   The Village Voice said Wednesday Giuliani recommended that
Marcos and his wife be indicted on fraud and conspiracy charges in
connection with owning prime Manhattan real estate.
   The Justice Department is expected to ask the president to
approve the indictment this week, the weekly newspaper reported,
noting that a five-year statute of limitations on some charges is
due to expire on July 18.
   Giuliani's office declined to comment on the report.
   The Associated Press reported last month that federal
prosecutors were reviewing proposed charges that Marcos and his
wife Imelda conspired to loot the Philippines government over two
decades.
   The charges reportedly sought by Giuliani stem from Marcos'
once-secret ownership of the Crown building, the Herald Center
shopping mall and an office building at 40 Wall Street, among
others.
   Sources told the Voice that the case also will involve charges
that Saudi Arabian arms dealer Adnan Khashoggi assisted in a
fraudulent transaction designed to conceal the fact that Marcos
owned the property.
   If indicted, the Marcoses, now living in Hawaii, would face
criminal charges in U.S. courts for the first time. And if
convicted, they and other defendants could face substantial prison
sentences and large fines.
   Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad said Tuesday evening that Marcos
had not been told of the Village Voice report.
   ``This thing is purely legal and I would like to consult the
president before commenting on it,'' Trinidad said.
   The Marcoses previously have denied any wrongdoing in connection
with the New York properties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Text 3rdAdd   07-13 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Text, 3rd Add,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: years ago.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   It means, my friends, that we've got to end the disgrace and the
shame of homelessness in the United States of America and we're
going to do that. We're going to do that. We know why we have
homeless people in this country today and we didn't have them 10
years ago, because we've cut back by 90 percent on our commitment
of affordable housing for families of low and moderate income. And
nobody's going to tell me that a nation as wealthy as this, a
nation as affluent as this, a nation fundamentally as caring as
this cannot build decent and affordable housing for all of our
citizens.
   It means that we're going to need, beginning in January of 1989,
an attorney general of the United States who is determined to end
racism and sexism and discrimination in America, and I mean end it
once and for all _ an attorney general who believes in enforcing
the Voting Rights Act and the Civil Rights Restoration Act and the
Fair Housing Act amendments of 1988 _ an attorney general that you
and I can be proud of.
   And it means that we've got to elect a president of the United
States who knows how to balance a budget and build a strong economy
and create those good jobs, and has done it; a president knows how
to create jobs and to save jobs, and has done it; a president who
will work with the Congress and the governors and mayors and
community leaders and all of you all across America to build a
future of good jobs and full employment for all of our citizens _
and I mean full employment _ a good job at decent wages for every
adult citizen who's ready and willing to work; a president with the
strength and the vision and the values to get this nation moving
again. And don't let anyone tell you that we can't do it. I've
balanced nine budgets in a row. I'm in the process of balancing a
tenth. My state has one of the hottest economies in the country.
And unemployment for minority citizens in my state has dropped by
50 percent in the past four years. And yes, while I'm proud of the
fact that my state has a minority unemployment rate of 5.5 percent,
my friends, I am not going to be satisfied until there is no
minority unemployment rate in my state and in the United States of
America, none whatsoever.
   Now, we've accomplished this, not only because we've worked hard
and invested, we've accomplished it because we've involved people.
And I'm proud of the way we've made that progress. By doubling
minority representation in state government, by being one of the
few states in the country that has a minority set-aside program
whose goals are not only being met, we're exceeding them, by
establishing a permanent commission on minority business
development; above all _ you may applaud if you would like. Above
all, we've made progress by working together, white and black and
brown, business and labor, educators and public officials, and
community leaders and just plain citizens, sharing responsibility,
sharing progress, building a sense of community and of teamwork and
confidence about the future.
   Isn't it about time we had that kind of partnership in the White
House? I think it is _ I think it is. Isn't it about time we
stopped waiting for opportunity to trickle down from a few
privileged neighborhoods into our urban centers and small towns of
rural America? Isn't it about time we told the sharp operators and
the inside traders and the dishonest contractors that their day in
the sun is over, and that a new day in this country is about to
begin? I think so, and so do you. And isn't it about time that we
restored in this country and in our government decency and
principle respect for the law of the highest offices of our land.
You know, my friends, respect for the law is the most basic, the
most conservative, and the most important principle of our
democratic society, and it must begin at the top in the White
House, in the Defense Department, and in the Justice Department of
the United States of America.
</TEXT>
