<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Horsewash     07-13 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Horsewash,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Horse-Washing Raises Some Nagging Questions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people are complaining that Jennifer
Schaffer is allowed to clean her horses _ despite a water shortage
_ at the Main Street coin-operated car wash.
   But Mayor Charles Hardy says the horse-washing is legal,
provided that Ms. Schaffer pays for the privilege.
   ``In my thinking, as long as they pay to use the meter, they can
wash their dishes there,'' Hardy said. ``I just want them to pick
up any residue the horses may leave behind.''
   Last week, because of the drought, Hardy ordered residents to
stop watering lawns, washing their cars at home and filling pools.
But his mandate allowed the car wash to continue operating in this
southern Ohio village of 1,000, about 50 miles south of Columbus.
   Hardy said those who complained didn't realize that ``it's
perfectly legal for her (Ms. Shaffer) to do this.''
   Ms. Schaffer said she decided to wash the family's prize quarter
horses at the car wash because of convenience. It costs $1.50 to
$2.25 each time she washes a horse.
   ``It's easier. I don't have to drag out the equipment,'' she
said.
   The horse-washing has raised eyebrows among some area residents
in the face of the water use restrictions imposed last week.
   ``Looks like there's a loophole,'' said Neil McCalla, who lives
just outside the village limits. ``Nobody ever said anything about
washing horses.''
   Ginny Allison said the wash should be for cars only.
   ``There's a water shortage. Some people here don't have enough
water. It's a waste,'' she said.
   But Marcine Daughtery, who was washing her clothes at the
village coin-operated laundry, said the idea has its merits.
   ``I just might bring my 200 hogs. I'd herd them through and then
go through myself,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
