<DOCNO> AP880713-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1759EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua Bjt   07-13 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, Bjt,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Moves _ A Sign Of Frustration Or New Wave Of
Repression?</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perhaps it was a case of just not
wanting to take it anymore that caused the Sandinista government to
take its most dramatic diplomatic move against the United States.
   Or maybe, as an opposition group suggests, it was simply the
return to a repressive rule that had eased following the signing of
a regional peace plan.
   Either explanation was possible for the Sandinistas' surprise
move Monday ordering the expulsion of Ambassador Richard Melton and
seven U.S. Embassy diplomats. The Reagan administration responded
in kind.
   The Sandinista order came a day after one of the most massive
anti-government demonstrations in Nicaragua since the Sandinistas
came to power. It ended with security forces beating civilians and
hurling canisters of tear gas. Police said they detained 43
opposition figures.
   The government accused the American diplomats of being behind
the demonstration and of inciting unrest.
   The expulsion order also came after a week of stepped-up rebel
attacks that violate an almost 4-month-old cease-fire.
   The Sandinistas expressed their outrage at the raids by the
U.S.-backed rebels, which killed at least eight civilians and
several dozen soldiers.
   In a clear reversal of recent democratic reforms, the
Sandinistas also shut down the Roman Catholic radio station on
Monday and suspended the only opposition newspaper, La Prensa, for
15 days.
   The Democratic Coordinate, an umbrella group of anti-government
organizations and political parties, claimed security agents were
rounding up dissidents in various Nicaraguan cities.
   The anti-Sandinista group charged the government was
``developing a wave of repression.''
   Relations between Nicaragua and the United States have been
strained at least since 1981, almost two years after the
Sandinistas came to power.
   The Reagan administration has financed the rebels, or Contras,
in the war to overthrow the Sandinistas. The CIA mined Nicaraguan
harbors. American planes fly reconnaisance and rebel resupply
flights in Nicaraguan territory. And the U.S. government ignored a
1986 World Court decision to reimburse Nicaragua for damages.
   The United States cut off aid to Nicaragua in 1981, blocked
loans and enacted a trade embargo in 1985. Bilateral talks to
resolve the problems were last held in 1984 despite repeated
requests for renewal by the Sandinistas.
   Washington claims the Marxist-led Sandinistas represent a threat
to U.S. national security interests by serving as a beachhead for
communism and aiding the Marxist rebels fighting the U.S.-backed
government in El Salvador.
   Nonetheless, the two nations maintain weak diplomatic relations.
The U.S. Embassy in Nicaragua frequently entertains opposition
figures and handles visa applications.
   Almost a year ago, in a move that took Washington off guard, the
nations in the region _ Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras
and Costa Rica _ signed a plan designed to end civil wars and
hostilities among the Central American nations.
   Nicaragua moved quickly to comply, but critics said it had the
furthest to go.
   The Sandinistas also had the most to gain _ a U.S. congressional
refusal to continue funding the Contras.
   The government in Nicaragua authorized the return of three
exiled priests, permitted several media outlets to reopen,
including Radio Catolica and La Prensa. In January the government
lifted the state of emergency that barred many basic freedoms.
   The Sandinista government also backed down on its position to
never hold talks with the Contras. Three days of face-to-face
meetings in March ended with a cease-fire agreement. A series of
talks held amid mutual mistrust broke off June 9, but each side
vowed to maintain the truce.
   The Sandinistas say they want the talks to continue. Almost
seven years of war have claimed more than 26,000 lives and
shattered the economy.
   Opposition groups began holding marches, all with prior
government approval as required, after the state of emergency was
lifted. Most of the demonstrations were against measures to repair
the battered economy.
   None of the earlier demonstrations was quashed with the violence
used Sunday.
   Opposition figures were refused permission to hold a ``Hunger
March'' on Saturday, two days before the Sandinistas mark their
ninth anniversary with a huge celebration in Juigalpa, 85 miles
east of the capital. The government said the opposition march could
take place July 24.
   But by closing the opposition newspaper for 15 days, the
government is preventing La Prensa from covering the July 19
anniversary or the anti-government demonstration.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Bryna Brenna has been based in Nicaragua since
September 1987 and in Central America since January 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
