<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-SovietInspections     07-13 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet Inspections,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Due Thursday for Second Round of INF Inspections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty Soviets were to arrive Thursday for the
next round of inspections to assure compliance with the treaty on
destruction of superpower medium-range nuclear missiles, a U.S.
spokesman said Wednesday.
   Four Soviet teams of 10 people each were to arrive aboard a
special Ilyushin 62 jet shortly after 5 p.m. at Dulles
International Airport near Washington, said Cmdr. Kendall Pease,
spokesman for the On-Site Inpection Agency.
   That agency conducts inspections in the Soviet Union of sites
covered under the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces, or INF, treaty
signed at the Washington summit last December.
   Between four and 48 hours after their arrival, the Soviets were
to notify U.S. authorities which of five locations they intended to
inspect: a Martin Marietta Corp. plant in Baltimore; Cape
Canaveral, Fla.; the Redstone rocket research center at Huntsville,
Ala; Fort Sill, Okla.; or the Longhorn Army Depot at Marshall,
Texas, said Pease.
   Five Soviet teams arrived on the West Coast at the beginning of
this month to inspect INF sites there. A 23-member Soviet team
arrived on July 2 in Magna, Utah, to prepare a permanent inspection
station at the Hercules Plant No. 1, where U.S. missiles were
produced.
   During the same period, 12 U.S. teams under the command of Army
Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie inspected 33 INF sites in the Soviet
Union, Pease said. The U.S. side is to visit 133 sites within a
60-day ``baseline inspection'' period to verify the exact number of
missiles and related components to be destroyed under the treaty.
   The Soviet side is to inspect 26 sites in the same period, the
spokesman said.
</TEXT>
