<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-MIAs     07-13 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-MIAs,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Returns Remains Of 25 U.S. Servicemen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials in Hanoi accepted what
are believed to be the remains of 25 Americans killed in Vietnam
and the caskets were put on a military plane for the trip to the
United States, the U.S. Embassy said.
   It was one of the largest returns of remains. U.S. forces left
Vietnam in 1973 after losing 58,000 soldiers in combat, and the war
ended with a Communist victory in April 1975.
   In the North Vietnamese capital, American officials were to
begin talks Thursday on the possible resettlement in the United
States of thousands of Vietnamese political prisoners who helped
the United States during the war.
   Honor guards loaded the 25 caskets, each topped with a folded
American flag, onto a C-141 transport plane at Noi Bai Airport.
After a 25-minute ceremony the plane left for Honolulu, where Army
experts will try to confirm Vietnam's preliminary identifications,
the embassy said.
   U.S. officials said the Vietnamese provided a list of 25 names,
some of which are on the official list of 1,761 Americans still
listed as missing in action. Vietnam also gave other information
related to the servicemen, many of whom were shot down while
bombing missions.
   Vietnamese officials entrusted the remains to a 23-member team
from the Joint Casualty Resolution Center and the Army Central
Identification Laboratory, both based in Honolulu.
   Retired Gen. John W. Vessey, a special presidential envoy,
negotiated an agreement in August 1987 under which Vietnam pledged
to speed its accounting of the missing Americans.
   The Vietnamese hgave returned more than 150 containers of
remains since the war ended. The largest return was April 6 _ the
remains of what were believed to have been 27 Americans, and those
of three ethnic Asians who might have been missing Americans.
   In exchange for Vietnam's cooperation, Washington has encouraged
private humanitarian agencies to help the former enemy with medical
problems, including rehabilitation of veterans disabled in the war
with the United States.
   Washington has no diplomatic relations with Hanoi.
   Robert L. Funseth, a deputy assistant secretary of state for
refugee programs, went to Hanoi on Wednesday to persuade Vietnam to
allow the emigration of some of the 900,000 former U.S. government
employees or officials of the South Vietnam government who were
interned in ``re-education camps.'' Most of the political prisoners
were detained for their U.S. ties, State Department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley said in Washington.
   Vietnam freed hundreds of former South Vietnamese officials in
mass amnesties in September 1987 and last February. Phan Quang, the
vice minister of information, has said only 150 former officials
still are held and they may be freed soon.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said the former prisoners could
emigrate only with a guarantee that they would not engage in
anti-Vietnam activities. U.S. officials have said this was not
possible because the U.S. government cannot dictate individual
conduct.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FiredFBIAgent     07-13 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fired FBI Agent,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agency Upholds Firing of FBI Agent Who Disobeyed Orders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Merit Systems Protection Board has
upheld the firing of an FBI agent who was dismissed for refusing to
investigate a group opposed to the Reagan administration's foreign
and military policies.
   The merit board on Tuesday ruled without comment in favor of the
FBI in its case against John C. ``Jack'' Ryan.
   ``I guess I wasn't really surprised,'' Ryan said Wednesday. ``I
would have been shocked if the decision had gone the other way.''
   Ryan, 50, was appealing the Feb. 2 decision of Administrative
Judge T. Christopher Heavrin, who rejected his claim that the
firing was unfair and constituted religious discrimination.
   A 21-year FBI veteran, Ryan lost his $50,000-a-year job just 10
months before he was eligible for retirement with full pension
benefits.
   The FBI fired Ryan last September after he refused to
investigate a group suspected of vandalizing 11 military recruiting
offices in the Chicago area in October 1986 in an anti-war protest.
   Ryan, a devout Roman Catholic, says he became a pacifist for
religious reasons in 1985 and now would never carry a firearm or
kill _ even in self defense. He denounces the administration's
policies in Central America as ``immoral activities.''
   His refusal to carry a gun is a key reason the appeal was
rejected, Ryan said.
   The FBI offered to reinstate him in December on the condition he
never speak about the case. He signed an agreement and mailed it to
FBI headquarters but the deal later collapsed.
   FBI spokesman Gregory Jones said the bureau had no comment on
the merit board's decision.
   Ryan said he is considering taking the case to federal court but
legal costs might prevent the move.
   ``I'd like to pursue it because I think it's a winnable case,''
he said. ``It's certainly a major issue.''
</TEXT>
