<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0705 07-13 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Azerbaijan Rejects Secession Move by Disputed Region</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs to include prosecutor comments, report of
arms confiscation; PICKS up 7th `Armenians, most'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Azerbaijan quashed a territory's attempt to secede
and join Armenia, Tass reported Wednesday, creating another
stalemate in an ethnic dispute that has caused months of turmoil in
the two southern republics.
   The official news agency said the Presidium, or executive
committee, of Azerbaijan's parliament met Tuesday night and
declared ``null and void'' the declaration of secession that the
Nagorno-Karabakh legislature passed Tuesday.
   Three-quarters of Nagorno-Karabakh's 160,000 residents are
ethnic Armenians but the enclave was made part of Azerbaijan in
1923. The argument over it became public in February and the two
neighboring Caucasus republics have been disrupted by riots,
strikes and huge demonstrations.
   Tass quoted the Azerbaijan Presidium's resolution as saying the
territory's legislature ``failed to secure strict compliance with
principles of legality'' and ``openly encroached on the
national-state composition of the republic.''
   It said only 101 of the 150 legislators were present when
secession was voted. Reporters for the radio station in the
territorial capital, Stepanakert, said Tuesday the vote was
unanimous except for one abstention.
   Vladimir V. Vaselenko, prosecutor of Nagorno-Karabakh, said in
an interview broadcast by Soviet television Wednesday that the
legislature's action violated the constitutions and laws of
Azerbaijan and the entire nation. He said one deputy who spoke at
Tuesday's session admitted that, but then voted for secession.
   The Soviet evening television news program ``Vremya'' reported
Wednesday that militiamen in Nagorno-Karabakh had confiscated
grenades, pistols, revolvers, sawed-off shotguns and ammunition
from residents in the past month.
   The declaration of secession, challenging central authority all
the way up to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, was the first
such action in the Soviet Union's 70 years.
   Armenians, most of whom are Christians, consider the mountain
enclave part of their ancestral homeland. Azerbaijan is
predominantly Moslem.
   Legislators of Nagorno-Karabakh, which is slightly smaller than
Delaware, said in their declaration Tuesday it was being renamed
the Artsakh Autonomous Region of Armenia.
   It also called for an end to strikes, but Tass said they
persisted Wednesday in Stepanakert.
   ``All industrial enterprises ... remained idle on July 13,
public and city transport did not function, all shops selling
manufactured goods were closed, so were consumer service outlets,''
the agency said.
   A worker at the Stepanakert radio station said in a telephone
interview: ``The food situation has become very critical. We are
producing our own bread and milk, but other foodstuffs are lacking.
Nothing is coming to us from Azerbaijan.''
   He said, speaking on condition of anonymity, that soldiers were
in the city streets and in other parts of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   In Yerevan, capital of Armenia, 120,000 people rallied to demand
the central government in Moscow approve the transfer of
Nagorno-Karabakh to Armenia, a reporter for the republic's official
news agency said. He said a general strike continued and quoted
speakers at a rally as saying: ``We have no other means of protest
than strikes.''
   The dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh has brought it into direct
confrontation with central authorities in Moscow as well as with
Azerbaijan.
   In February, the dispute led to riots in the Sumgait,
Azerbaijan, in which at least 32 people were reported killed, 26 of
them ethnic Armenians.
   The Soviet constitution gives citizens the right of
self-determination, but requires a republic's consent for any
changes in its boundaries.
   On Feb. 20, Nagorno-Karabakh's legislature asked the Azerbaijani
and Armenian governments to approve transfer of the region to
Armenia. The Armenian legislature agreed June 15 but Azerbaijan
said no two days later.
   In Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan, a reporter for the
republic's official news agency said the dispute was being resolved
in accordance with Gorbachev's policies of ``glasnost,'' or
openness.
   ``It's being decided in a democratic way. Some people say one
thing; others say something else,'' the reporter said in a
telephone interview, on condition his name not be used.
   Gorbachev has said more attention should be paid to concerns of
the Soviet Union's more than 100 national groups, but that some are
abusing glasnost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
