<HEAD>Unisys Cooperating in Probe of Work For Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp., one of the defense contractors
enmeshed in the Pentagon bribery probe, is cooperating in a
separate federal criminal investigation of the company's work at
the Army Information Systems Command in Fort Huachuca, Ariz., a
spokesman for the firm said Wednesday.
   Unisys spokesman Peter Hynes acknowledged that the investigation
is under way and sources familiar with it, speaking on condition of
anonymity, say it is being conducted by the U.S. attorney's office
in Tucson, Ariz.
   Hynes said Unisys performs computer software maintenance at the
location in Arizona.
   The systems command is a global telecommunications network for
the Army that employs 40,000 civilians and military personnel and
it is headquartered in Fort Huachuca.
   The Wall Street Journal, which disclosed the investigation in
Wednesday editions, said the probe involves alleged overcharges
that may amount to $10 million on computer work performed for the
Army.
   Unisys, based in Blue Bell, Pa., also is deeply involved in the
massive Pentagon bribery probe, which is a separate investigation
from the Fort Huachuca matter.
   The government in the Pentagon bribery probe is delving into the
activities of former Unisys vice president-turned-consultant
Charles Gardner.
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell declined to comment on
the probe involving the systems command.
