<HEAD>Actor James Garner in Satisfactory Condition After Aneurysm
Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emmy-winning actor James Garner was
recovering from artery surgery on Wednesday, an operation postponed
three months ago after doctors decided he needed an immediate
quintuple heart bypass.
   ``He is doing quite well,'' said Ron Wise, spokesman for
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center. ``He is up, out of his bed, and
walking around in his room.''
   Garner, 60, entered Cedars-Sinai last Thursday. The surgery the
following day was to correct an aneurysm, or weakness, in the
aorta, the main artery carrying blood from the heart.
   The operation routinely requires a lengthy hospital stay, but
Garner has healed rapidly, Wise said.
   ``His recovery is remarkable. He is going to be released
probably by the end of the week, much earlier than previously
expected,'' said Wise.
   Garner also has recovered well from the five hours of heart
bypass surgery on April 21, Wise said.
   Garner starred in television's ``Maverick'' and ``The Rockford
Files,'' winning an Emmy for ``Rockford.'' He recently appeared
with Bruce Willis in the film ``Sunset,'' and received an Oscar
nomination for another of his movies, a role opposite Sally Field
in ``Murphy's Romance.''
