<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru   07-13 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru,0848</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev: Soviet Union Can Learn from Polish Experience</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 18-21 pvs, `A group of Solidarity ... freed, he
said.' with 7 grafs to UPDATE with activist claim that workers were
reinstated, Gorbachev returning to Warsaw. PICKS up 22nd pvs bgng,
Gorbachev's visit...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SCZ51</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SZCZECIN, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said
Wednesday that socialist leaders must share their experiences in
order to avoid making costly political errors as they overhaul
their economic systems.
   ``One must not panic because of single failures,'' Gorbachev
said in a pep talk for ``perestroika,'' his campaign to reform
Soviet economy and society. ``We have started such a great cause.
... He who is persevering will win.''
   The Soviet leader, midway through a six-day visit to Poland,
noted that the Polish government headed by Wojciech Jaruzelski is
embarked on a similar reform campaign known as ``socialist
renewal.''
   ``We find many useful things in your experiences also for
ourselves. We wish ... to display more ability, competence ... and
the ability to avoid errors, specifically political errors, at the
sharp turns of our history.''
   ``It is not one collective, city or province that pays for
political errors. Frequently it is the whole nation, country, that
pays for these errors,'' he told about 3,000 shipyard workers at a
rally in this port city.
   Poland's attempt to restructure its economy was dealt a setback
this year with the failure of a program that was aimed at
overhauling the retail price structure, trimming government
subsidies and bringing prices more in line with actual costs.
   The government raised prices an average of 40 percent, almost
immediately touching off inflation that hit 60 percent and is
expected to go higher.
   Polish leaders have admitted the reform effort was a failure and
needs a new approach.
   ``We are analyzing now the Polish experiences to find out what
elements we could use and to avoid your errors or the things you
consider erroneous,'' the Soviet foreign affairs spokesman, Gennady
Gerasimov, told a Polish reporter after Gorbachev's speech.
   Gorbachev told delegates to the Communist Party national
conference last month that a realistic price structure and
elimination of heavy government subsidies, particularly for many
foods, is vital if the Soviet Union is to eliminate shortages and
produce high-quality goods.
   He has given no indication how the program will be implemented.
   Gorbachev's speech was greeted with polite applause but little
outward enthusiasm by the workers, admitted by invitations they
received at their workplaces. Many came from enterprises elsewhere
in the city. Perhaps a third were among the shipyard's 8,300
employees.
   The shipyard was among the first major factories to go on strike
in August 1980 to support Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first and
only independent trade movement. The shipyard no longer plays a
leading role in the activities of Solidarity, now outlawed.
   Jaruzelski, the military general who came to power after the
labor unrest and imposed martial law, referred to Szczecin's
tumultous past.
   ``In this city eight years ago, the voice of protest rose
against distortions defying the essense of socialism,'' he said.
   But he added that ``everything creative and valuable'' from that
time is being preserved, while the socialist government seeks new
solutions to the nation's continuing economic problem.
   ``Those were stormy times,'' Jaruzelski said. ``It was bringing
along some solidarity and set working people at variance. There
were roads, but pathless tracts too. It has already become
history.''
   Meanwhile, a group of Solidarity members at a steel and defense
plant in southeastern Poland said their one-day strike won job
reinstatement Wednesday for seven fired activists. The seven had
been dismissed for leading a strike at the plant April 29-30.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban in Szczecin said there was an
attempt ``by a small group of people'' to start a strike at the
Stalowa Wola steel mill, but he said they failed.
   The plant 120 miles southeast of Warsaw is off-limits to
reporters, and there was no way to independently verify either
side's statements.
   Late Wednesday, one of the dismissed workers, Liwak Wladyslaw,
said in a telephone call to Warsaw that he and the other six were
promised in writing they would be rehired. He said the agreement
cme after six hours of talks with management.
   ``There was considerable pressure on us,'' Wladyslaw said. ``The
situation in Poland connected with Gorbachev's visit forced a
possibly quick solution here in Stalowa Wola.''
   Gorbachev returned to Warsaw later Wednesday.
   Gorbachev's visit highlighted the Szczecin shipyard's links to
the Soviet Union, which helped build the yard on territory captured
from Germany during World War II. The Soviet Union buys about half
the ships built at the yard. About 200 vessels built in the
Szczecin yard sail under the Soviet flag.
   The official shipyard workers' union presented Gorbachev and his
wife Raisa with a model of a cruise ship they lived aboard during
the 1986 U.S.-Soviet summit at Reykjavik, Iceland.
</TEXT>
