<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FreddieMac     07-13 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freddie Mac,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preferred Stock Ownership Restrictions Lifted; May Help Ailing
S&Ls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of the Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp. voted Wednesday to lift ownership restrictions on its
preferred stock, a move expected to bring a windfall of more than
$1 billion to the savings and loan industry.
   The corporation, known as Freddie Mac, is a congressionally
created corporation that buys home mortgages from savings
institutions and other lenders and packages them into securities
for resale to investors, thus making more money available for home
buyers.
   Freddie Mac voting stock is owned by the Federal Home Loan Bank
System, which, in turn, is owned by the nation's savings
institutions. Its preferred stock, with no voting power, is
currently owned directly by savings institutions.
   The Senate Banking Committee has been considering legislation,
sponsored by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., to allow S&Ls to sell
their preferred stock to public investors, thus creating a wider
market for the stock and driving its price up.
   Analysts estimate the move would bring a profit of between $1
billion and $1.5 billion to savings institutions, which are badly
in need of new capital. The industry posted a post-Depression
record loss of $7.6 billion last year and lost another $3.8 billion
in the first three months of this year.
   However, much of the preferred stock is owned by the healthier
segment of the industry and Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., chairman
of the Senate Banking Committee, was pushing for a measure that,
through a transfer fee on sale of the stock, would have pumped
about $375 million of the windfall into the Federal Savings and
Loan Insurance Corp., the ailing fund that insures S&L deposits up
to $100,000.
   However, Freddie Mac's board, which is the same as the
three-member Federal Home Loan Bank Board, the regulator of
federally insured S&Ls, pre-empted Congress by acting on its own to
remove ownership restrictions.
   The plan, approved by the board in principle, would lift
ownership restrictions on about 15 million shares of stock. Savings
institutions will be permitted until Nov. 30, on payment of a
$7-a-share fee to Freddie Mac, to exchange restricted shares for
shares which public investors will be permitted to buy after Jan.
1. Any preferred shares not exchanged by Nov. 30 will continue to
carry the ownership restrictions.
   That formula, if all the shares were exchanged, would bring
about $105 million to Freddie Mac, rather than the $375 million to
FSLIC as envisioned by Proxmire.
   Kenneth McLean, staff director of the Senate Banking Committee,
said Congress was unlikely to pass any legislation including
Proxmire's proposal because of stiff opposition from the industry
and the bank board.
   The U.S. League of Savings Institutions, the industry's largest
trade group, issued a statement late Wednesday hailing the board's
decision as ``a welcome and sensible move.''
   The Freddie Mac board also voted to lift the limits gradually on
the number of shares a single stockholder may own. The current
limit of 150,000 shares was raised to 300,000 immediately and will
rise to 450,000 effective Oct. 1 and 600,000 effective Jan. 1.
   Ownership restrictions on the 100,000 outstanding shares of
voting stock are unaffected by the plan and remain in place.
   Meanwhile, Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for the bank board, said a
new rule will take effect immediately requiring institutions with
less than the required level of capital to get approval of federal
regulators before selling their stock. The purpose is to allow
regulators to monitor stock sales by ailing institutions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Reform     07-13 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Reform,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Committee Discusses Economic Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders discussed plans
for economic reform Wednesday in the Soviet bloc's first Central
Committee meeting to which a journalist was admitted.
   In a departure from the traditional secrecy of party
proceedings, a correspondent of state radio was allowed to attend
and gave hourly reports from the chamber in which the 108 Central
Committee members conferred.
   Committee Secretary Miklos Nemeth said the economy was in ``a
critical situation'' and further delays in implementing necessary
reforms would erode public confidence in the leadership.
   Nemeth said the economy and society should be open and
authorities should ``demolish the barriers that provide
overprotection for the economy.''
   He said all subsidies to money-losing enterprises should end,
and only those making profits should be granted ``possibilities for
development.''
   True commodity, money, capital and labor markets should be
established and companies freed from unnecessary restrictions,
enabling them to react ``as they see best,'' Nemeth declared.
   The radio broadcast 20 minutes of excerpts from Nemeth's speech
during a news program at noon.
   Past practice has been to give information on such meetings in
communiques, often vague, issued when they were over and rarely
indicating disagreement.
   On Wednesday, however, the radio said 20 Central Committee
members asked to speak after Nemeth's report on measures necessary
to curb the $18 billion debt and stimulate the stagnating economy.
   Premier Karoly Grosz, who also became party chief at the end of
May, has repeatedly sought public support of unpopular but
necessary austerity measures.
   He took over as party leader from Janos Kadar, who now has the
honorary post of party president. Official media said he was on
vacation and did not attend the meeting Wednesday.
   Grosz asked the public in a television interview Tuesday, to
``understand the need'' for reforms, which he said would require
``sacrifices for the sake of the future'' and might need 10-15
years to show results.
   Wednesday's broadcasts could help him soften any potential party
resistance to economic reform by taking debate on them direct to
the public.
   Nemeth said the reform program must be implemented as a package.
``Taking any one of the elements out of its context may inevitably
lead to confusion and failure,'' he said.
   He presented two alternative plans _ one of introducing radical
reforms that might bring social tension and higher unemployment,
and a second that would bring change more gradually. Hungary's
leaders have said the saecond course might mean lagging behind
competing nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CollapseProbe     07-13 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Collapse Probe,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineer: Why Texas Store Collapsed May Never Be Known</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials may never know why a Texas
department store collapsed, killing 14 people, but a preliminary
report will be available this week, an engineer investigating the
accident said Wednesday.
   ``I don't think we're going to be able to pinpoint a cause,''
Garry G. Nichols said. ``We're working on it now.''
   He said the investigation has been hampered by the
unavailability of important building records and sketchy witness
accounts.
   Nichols and Glenn J. Winslow, civil engineers with
Birmingham-based Southern Building Code Congress International
Inc., are the primary investigators of the collapse of the
three-story Amigo store in Brownsville. They spent three days there
after the July 7 accident.
   ``We've been told that the (city) building department has moved
two or three times ... and some of the records may have been
involved in a flood,'' Nichols said.
   He said the city is still searching its records, which were
stored in several locations, for the construction plans. Nichols
said one Brownsville building official said they may have been lost.
   Nichols said officials had not found the architect or engineer
of the building. The city contacted the contractor, but he had no
copy of the construction specifications.
   The store was built in 1969; the third floor was added about
1975, he said.
   Witnesses said lightning struck either an electrical transformer
or utility poles near the building, said Nichols. He said there is
speculation the poles might have fallen on the building, causing
the collapse.
   The engineers are also looking into the possibility that the
heavy rain falling that afternoon may have caused the cave-in. More
than 2 inches of rain fell in a 30-minute period just before the
collapse. Nichols said if the building's drainage pipes were
clogged, water could have backed up and its weight then could have
triggered the fall.
   Nichols and Winslow work for a non-profit agency that writes
building code laws for governments to adopt. Nearly 2,000 city,
county and state building departments are served by the
organization.
   A complete report on the Brownsville collapse will be issued in
several months.
</TEXT>
