<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ContraAidProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0809 07-13 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0809,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Votes To Drop Probe of Contra Aid Disbursements</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 6 grafs after 9th graf pvs bgng, `He said the
agency's,' to include Panetta complaints of use of family
assistance funds</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee voted unanimously Wednesday
to abandon an investigation of the administration of non-lethal
U.S. aid to Nicaragua's Contra rebels after being told there were
few if any problems with it now.
   The investigation had been requested by Rep. Leon Panetta,
D-Calif., who headed a 1986 inquiry that determined that more than
half of an earlier $27 million package of aid for the Contras had
ended up in private hands.
   But Panetta told the House Foreign Affairs Committee that the
Agency for International Development, which oversees the latest
$47.9 million Contra aid fund, is doing a good job overall in
administering the program.
   The previous economic aid to the Contras was administered by
other U.S. agencies.
   Panetta said AID voluntarily had provided all of the data he had
requested.
   ``It is clear from the documentation requested that AID has
implemented this entire program in a spirit of openness, allowing
for close public scrutiny and review,'' Panetta said before the
committee voted to drop the investigation.
   ``The agency should be commended for how it has handled the
administration of this program in the difficult political climate
surrounding the issue of humanitarian aid,'' Panetta said.
   He said the aid agency has established safeguards to make sure
assistance funds went to their intended recipients and that the
money was spent in accord with the law.
   He said the agency's operations also were monitored by the
General Accounting Office, along with AID's own inspector general
and the private accounting firm of Price Waterhouse.
   Panetta said he remains concerned, however, that Price
Waterhouse accountants were not able to document adequately a $1
million expenditure for so-called family assistance in which
monthly payments are made to senior Contra personnel living in
Costa Rica, Honduras and Miami.
   The payments range from $25 to $2,750 a month. with the payments
being made in Miami to 34 to 41 people, he said.
   He said none of the three monitoring agencies could document how
these payments were used.
   Price Waterhouse reported, Panetta said, that the recipients are
designated by Enrique Bermudez, commander of the Contra military
forces, who provides a list of beneficiaries and payment amounts,
including his own, with no formal criteria for designating or
removing beneficiaries.
   He also noted that Price Waterhouse found certain cases of
apparent abuse, including the sale of supplied food by Contra
members in Honduras to Hondurans and other Nicaraguan refugees.
   It is important that AID improve ways of verifying how family
assistance funds are used, Panetta said.
   The State Department recently had expressed concern that
Panetta's investigation appeared to challenge the integrity of the
administration of the Contra aid fund even after precautions had
been taken to assure that integrity.
   ``This inquiry has uncovered no significant accountability
problem with AID's administration of this assistance,'' Deputy
Secretary of State John C. Whitehead said in a letter to the
panel's chairman, Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla.
   Panetta said $11.9 million of the aid fund has been spent to
date, including $6.7 million for food, clothing and medical care,
$385,000 on communications equipment, $1.5 million for a children's
surgical fund and $1.8 million for transportation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
