<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CBSChanges 4thLd-Writethru a0793 07-13 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS Changes, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0793,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Announces Changes in Broadcast Segment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf `William S.' with 4 grafs to CORRECT that
statement was attributed to Paley but he did not appear at news
conference, UPDATE with quote from Tisch, reaction from analysts.
INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs `Despite the...' to UPDATE with
affiliate reax. Picks up 8th graf pvs `Jankowski moved...' A
version moved on financial wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY48</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS announced a management shakeup Wednesday
that has the president of CBS News becoming president of the
Broadcast Group and for the first time in CBS history brings in an
outsider to head the news division.
   Effective Aug. 1., ABC News Vice President David Burke takes
over CBS News, CBS News president Howard Stringer becomes president
of the CBS Broadcast Group, replacing Gene Jankowski, who becomes
Broadcast Group chairman.
   CBS' broadcast division has struggled during the past season,
with its entertainment schedule lagging in third place behind NBC
and ABC for the first time ever. The ``CBS Evening News'' has been
No. 1 among the three major networks' nightly news program in
recent weeks after trailing ABC during the second quarter of the
year.
   William S. Paley, chairman of the CBS board of directors, and
Laurence A. Tisch, the company's president and chief executive
officer, announced the changes in a statement.
   Tisch later opened a news conference on the changes by saying,
``Today, we start a new era.''
   Financial analysts suggested the changes were an inevitable
result of Tisch's efforts to place his stamp on the company, which
he has headed since the fall of 1986.
   ``Larry's putting his man in charge, and Gene is probably taking
the first step out the door,'' said Edward Atorino, who follows the
media business for the investment firm Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co.
   Stringer has been with CBS for 23 years, the last 22 months as
president of CBS News. Jankowski has served 11 years as president
of the CBS Broadcast Group.
   It was Stringer who steered the beleaguered news division
through the controversial and highly publicized layoffs and budget
cuts that prompted even CBS notables such as anchor Dan Rather to
criticize network management.
   Despite the cutbacks, the division under Stringer managed to
launch a new news show, ``48 Hours,'' and, with a little help from
the Writers Guild strike prompting the need for prime-time
programming not subject to its delays, kept three prime-time news
hours on the fall schedule, compared to one for ABC and none for
NBC.
   Phil Jones, general manager of KCTV in Kansas City, Mo., and
immediate past chairman of the CBS affiliates board, called
Stringer's appointment ``magnificent.''
   ``He is people-sensitive, programming-sensitive and has the
background in news that I think is the real foundation of CBS. He
will bring those qualities to the job and will be good person to do
business with,'' Jones said.
   Jankowski moved up through the CBS sales division to become head
of the Broadcast Group, overseeing the finances of the network.
During his tenure, CBS' prime-time schedule fell victim to NBC's
rise and last year embarrassed the network by placing a miserable
third. Kim LeMasters became a mid-season replacement for CBS
Entertainment President Bud Grant and will be tested when his first
full-season schedule finally gets on the air in 1988-89.
   Paley said Jankowski has been ``an outstanding president,'' and
said he was delighted Jankowski will continue ``as a key member of
CBS' senior management.''
   Tisch said Jankowski had told him that with the completion of
this year's program development cycle, it was ``an appropriate time
for an orderly transition in the management of the broadcast
group.''
   Stringer ``was the obvious candidate to assume leadership of the
broadcast group,'' Tisch said.
   Burke, who once served on the staff of U.S. Sen. Edward Kennedy,
joined ABC 11 years ago as a business and policy adviser to ABC
News President Roone Arledge. Stringer said Burke has established
``a remarkable record as a news executive through program
innovation and management strength.''
   ``I am confident that CBS News under his leadership will
maintain the highest professional standards while finding creative
new ways to provide news programming and information to the
American people,'' Stringer said.
   Arledge, who successfully turned ABC News into a contender in
his decade there, is not expected to step down anytime soon. He
responded to Burke's impending departure by saying, ``He richly
deserves this recognition, which is a compliment both to him and to
ABC News. ... We all wish him the absolute best.''
