<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-13 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says 88 Guerrillas Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kabul radio said Wednesday that
security forces had killed 88 guerrillas in Afghanistan's eastern
provinces, but gave no figures on government casualties.
   It said 45 ``extremist elements,'' the Communist government's
term for Moslem insurgents, were killed in Wardak province and 43
during two operations in Nangarhar province near the border with
Pakistan.
   The radio did not say when the battles occurred or give the
sites in the provinces.
   Guerrillas began fighting after a Communist coup in April 1978,
and Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979.
More than 5 million Afghans have fled the country and at least 3
million live in cities and refugee camps just inside Pakistan.
   Soviet troops are withdrawing under a U.N.-mediated agreement
signed April 14 by Afghanistan and Pakistan, with the Soviet Union
and United States as guarantors.
   The pullout began May 15 and is to be completed by Feb. 15,
1989. More than 30,000 of the estimated 115,000 Red Army soldiers
have left so far, according to U.N. figures.
</TEXT>
