<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO-AbuSharif     07-13 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Abu Sharif,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top PLO Spokesman Says He's Been Invited to the United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocaited Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO spokesman who called last month for
direct negotiations with Israel said Wednesday that two private
groups have invited him to the United States to discuss peace in
the Middle East.
   Bassam Abu Sharif, an adviser to Palestine Liberation
Organization chief Yasser Arafat, said he was ``prepared to visit
Washington to elaborate further on my paper.'' He said the State
Department had not yet granted him a visa.
   In an interview with The Associated Press in Baghdad, Abu Sharif
said the invitations were from the Brookings Institution and the
National Press Club, both in Washington. The Brookings Institution
is a liberal think tank dealing with economic and foreign policy
issues.
   Abu Sharif, a writer and former journalist, published an article
last month in the London-based newsletter Mideast Mirror calling
for negotiations between the PLO and Israel in connection with a
U.N.-sponsored international peace conference.
   Arab radicals viewed the proposal as an implicit recognition of
Israel.
   Both Israel and the United States have refused to deal directly
with the PLO, but the Americans have said they would review the
position if the PLO recognized Israel's right to exist. The PLO
insists on simultaneous, mutual recognition.
   U.S. and Israeli officials have responded favorably to Abu
Sharif's article but demand that Arafat endorse it. Although the
PLO chief has made no public comment, it is unlikely Abu Sharif
would have published the article without his consent.
   Abu Sharif said Wednesday the PLO executive committee, the
organization's 15-man ruling body, discussed his paper last week
and approved it on the basis it did not contradict the condition of
mutual, simultanous recognition.
   He said the 11-man Central Committee that runs Fatah, the PLO's
largest guerrilla faction, also had no objections to the position.
</TEXT>
