<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DestroyerSlaying 1st-LdWritethru a0789 07-13 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Destroyer Slaying, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0789,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Petty Officer Guilty of Killing Ship's Paymaster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf before final graf to UPDATE with detail of
prosecution evidence.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-martial jury found a
Navy petty officer guilty Wednesday of killing his ship's paymaster
and taking $94,000.
   A sentencing hearing was scheduled for Thursday to decide
whether Petty Officer 1st Class Ruben Colon, 34, should receive the
death penalty.
   No Navy man has been executed in this century.
   The five-member jury deliberated 10 hours before unanimously
finding Colon guilty of murder while perpetrating a robbery. The
panel also found him guilty of robbery and kidnapping.
   In closing arguments Tuesday, a prosecutor said Colon strangled
the paymaster, shot him in the head, buried him in a ``pile of
seabags'' and then emptied the safe.
   To allow consideration of the death penalty, the murder verdict
had to be unanimous and the jury had to find that a robbery was
committed or that the murder was premeditated. Colon was found
innocent of murder with premeditation.
   At the sentencing hearing, attorneys will have an opportunity to
present evidence and arguments.
   Colon, an electronic warfare technician from Vega Baja, Puerto
Rico, was convicted of killing Lt. j.g. Ratish Prasad, 24, of Park
Forest, Ill., while the destroyer John Hancock was docked at
Mayport Naval Station on March 15.
   Investigators searched three of Colon's safe-deposit boxes and
found $87,350 in cash and 2,575 blank U.S. Treasury checks, each
bearing the USS John Hancock imprint, a prosecutor said.
   Defense attorney Lt. Matthew Michels argued that other crew
members had been under suspicion for the crime, owned weapons and
failed polygraph examinations.
</TEXT>
