<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HowardBeach     07-13 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Howard Beach,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juries Deliberate In Second Racial Assault Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second Howard Beach racial assault trial
headed toward completion Wednesday with one jury deliberating an
attempted murder charge, and another jury considering riot charges
against four people.
   One jury completed its second day of deliberations without
deciding the fate of Thomas Gucciardo, 19, who is charged with
attempted murder, assault and riot stemming from the Dec. 20, 1986,
attack by a white gang on three blacks in the predominantly white
Queens neighborhood.
   The second jury recessed for the evening at 7:25 p.m., eight
hours after the trial judge, state Supreme Court Justice Thomas
Demakos, gave the panel instructions concerning the four
co-defendants, all facing riot charges.
   Gucciardo and the others _ William Bollander, Thomas Farino and
James Povinelli, all 18, and John Saggese, 20 _ were tried together
but the second jury heard no testimony about the more serious
charges against Gucciardo.
   The trial, which began June 13, was the second stemming from the
highly publicized racial assault. Three teen-agers were convicted
of manslaughter in the first trial for the death of Michael
Griffith, 23, who was struck by a car and killed as he fled his
attackers.
   A fourth youth was acquitted at that trial; two other teen-agers
pleaded guilty to riot charges just prior to the second trial.
Another defendant, Robert Riley, agreed to plead guilty and
testified against the others at both trials.
</TEXT>
