<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusSafety     07-13 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Safety,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New School Buses to Have Extra Window Exits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Board of Education voted
Wednesday to require emergency exit windows on new school buses,
the first design changes ordered since a fiery bus crash killed 27
people in May.
   The board also voted to require new buses to be powered by
diesel fuel, which is considered safer and less combustible than
gasoline. Officials said that change had been proposed as an
economy measure before the May 14 crash of the bus owned by the
Radcliff First Assembly of God church, which was gas-powered.
   In addition to the changes, the board ordered studies of other
safety devices, including roof exits, additional side doors, extra
fire extinguishers and fire-retardant seat covers.
   The decisions followed the recommendations of a standing
advisory committee that annually reviews the state's bus safety
standards.
   Sam Jackson, the state education department's representative on
the advisory committee, stressed that better training of drivers
and evacuation training for school children may do more than the
design measures.
   ``Push-out windows or any emergency exit are not worth a darn
unless you develop some plan of evacuation,'' Jackson said.
   But he added, ``We definitely feel push-out windows will not
hurt.''
   About two-thirds of Kentucky's school buses are gas-powered,
said Byron Watkins, a committee member and assistant superintendent
of Hopkins County schools.
   The state board also recommended that local districts:
   _Restrict seating to two children per bench seat on buses making
extracurricular trips and use separate vehicles to transport cargo,
such as band instruments and sports equipment. Children were
sitting three abreast on the Radcliff bus, a capacity for which the
bus was built.
   _Step up bus-driver training programs in defensive driving, bus
cleanliness, evacuation and use of emergency equipment.
   The Radcliff church's 1977 model bus exploded in flames when it
was struck head-on by a pickup truck driven in the wrong direction
on Interstate 71 near Carrollton.
   The victims, who included 24 children, were returning from an
outing at the Kings Island amusement park near Cincinnati. The
state medical examiner said all died of smoke inhalation, not from
crash injuries.
   Like school buses commonly in use in Kentucky, the church bus
had a single emergency exit at the rear. Safety officials have said
that was insufficient to evacuate a large numbers of passengers.
   Under the new rule, the largest school buses _ those built for
65 to 71 passengers _ must have two window exits on each side.
Buses built for 35 to 53 passengers must have one window exit on
each side.
   Buses equipped for the handicapped would need one window exit on
35-passenger models and two window exits on 65-passenger models.
   No additional exits would be required on any bus carrying 21 or
fewer passengers.
   The board also recommended, but did not require, that school
systems install exit windows on existing buses that are used for
trips outside local school districts.
   Kentucky has about 7,500 school buses, of which 1,047 were built
before 1978, when stricter federal safety standards went into
effect, said Jackson. Those federal standards require a steel cage
around the fuel tank _ a feature the Radcliff bus lacked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Congress-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0707 07-13 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Condemns Sandinistas, Threatens Renewed Military Aid to
Contras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with Senate vote, edits to
conform; PICKS UP 12th graf pvs bgng, `Cranston said'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, in an overwhelming 91-4 vote,
condemned Nicaragua's Sandinista government Wednesday for
``dramatic new steps in brutality'' and warned that further human
rights violations could trigger renewed U.S. military aid to the
Contra rebels.
   In what some senators called a ``carrot and stick policy,'' the
Senate also said it was ready to extend economic aid to Nicaragua
if the Sandinistas fully comply with commitments made a year ago
and ``proceed to permit the establishment of a democratic system.''
   Although the sense of the Senate resolution is not binding, the
wide bipartisan coalition which swung behind it was intended to
emphasize the anger and concern caused by recent Sandinista actions
to suppress dissent.
   These include the closing of the opposition newspaper La Prensa
and Nicaragua's Catholic radio station, the suppression of a
non-violent demonstration in Managua, the arrest of 40 opposition
political leaders and the expulsion of U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton and seven other U.S. diplomats.
   ``You can say its only a sense of the Senate resolution, but in
my view it means a great deal,'' said Senate Republican leader Bob
Dole of Kansas.
   Dole told the Senate: ``We are moving now because the Sandinista
goons have been in the streets of Managua again; because the
Sandinista jails are filling up with new prisoners; because what
little independent media there has ever been in Nicaragua is being
closed down again; and because the light of freedom in Nicaragua
has been nearly snuffed out again.''
   The resolution states: ``The Sandinistas should understand that
blatant violations (of last year's peace agreement) and the human
rights of the Nicaraguan people could cause Congress to consider
the provision of additional humanitarian and other appropriate
assistance, including military aid, if conditions should so
warrant.''
   Originally drafted by Dole but modified by Senate Majority
Leader Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia, the resolution also
supported President Reagan's action in expelling Nicaraguan
diplomats from the United States as ``an appropriate response to
the unjustified expulsion of U.S. diplomats from Managua.''
   ``Now, for the first time, we have a broad-based bipartisan
policy toward Nicaragua,'' said Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M. ``For
the first time, the United States Senate is blaming only the
Sandinista communists for what is going on there.
   ``We're saying, loud and clear, Daniel Ortega, you and your
regime are violating the peace plan, violating the human rights of
your people,'' he said.
   The four senators voting against the resolution were Sens. Brock
Adams, D-Wash.; Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.; Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii,
and William Proxmire, D-Wis. Those not voting were Sens. Joseph R.
Biden, D-Del.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Larry Pressler, R-S.D.; John
Stennis, D-Miss., and Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   Meanwhile, the Senate Intelligence Committee questioned
Ambassador Richard Melton privately and members said later they
found no evidence he was in engaged in espionage or any other acts
that would justify his expulsion or that of seven other U.S.
diplomats.
   And 37 Republican senators appealed to House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, to permit House members to vote on legislation which would
not only condemn the Sandinista regime but would continue economic
aid to the Contras and keep open the option of resuming military
aid ``if Sandinista repression continues.''
   ``We hope that this new and blatant proof of Sandinista tyranny,
violations of human rights and bad faith will lead you to support
our legislation or, at a minimum, permit the members of the House
of Representatives the opportunity to make their own judgment on
its merits,'' the senators said in their letter to Wright.
   While not responding directly, Wright told reporters that a
bipartisan group of House members was drafting an alternative
resolution which will ``call upon the Nicaraguan government to
reopen the organs of free expression and repeal the law that
permits the response they made.''
   Dole told his colleagues that the Central American peace process
has broken down and that the Sandinistas, freed of the pressure
represented by Contra military action, have no incentive to live up
to their commitments to embrace democratic reforms.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., a leader of efforts to cut off
Contra aid, told reporters he continues to believe the United
States should use diplomatic rather than military pressure to bring
democratic change in Nicaragua.
   Cranston said the Sandinistas' recent action makes him no more
sympathetic than before to the Contra cause.
   ``But it doesn't make me any more sympathetic to the Sandinistas
either,'' he said.
   Melton answered questions before a private session of the
Intelligence Committee, but objections by Sen. Christopher J. Dodd,
D-Conn., blocked the committee from continuing the session in
public.
   Committee Chairman David Boren, D-Okla., said he will try to
question Melton in public on Thursday.
</TEXT>
