<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Trident     07-13 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Trident,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Nuclear Arsenal ``At Risk'' Over Warhead Plant Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delayed construction of a warhead parts factory
for U.S. Trident nuclear missiles threatens to slow modernization
of Britain's nuclear arsenal, a parliamentary committee said
Wednesday.
   ``We believe that warhead production is a major risk area to the
Trident program,'' the House of Commons' influential Public
Accounts Committee said in a report.
   The committee, headed by a legislator in the governing
Conservative Party, Robert Sheldon, accused the Defense Ministry of
inadequate management and control of the building program, adding,
``We are dismayed and concerned.''
   The potent Trident missiles may not be in service on schedule
because of a delay in construction work on a facility to make
warhead components in Berkshire, west of London, the committee said.
   Completion of the facility has fallen four years behind
schedule. The buildings at the Atomic Weapons Establishment at
Aldermaston, 50 miles from London, will not be ready until 1992 and
deployment of the missiles was planned for the mid-1990s.
   Under a $15 billion program, 16 Trident missiles and four
Trident submarines are to replace the same numbers of Polaris
missiles and subs, which date from 1969.
   The long-range Trident missiles are to increase British nuclear
firepower eightfold.
   The committee said the delay meant vital work on Trident
components will have to be done on old premises used to build
warheads for Britain's aging fleet of submarine-launched Polaris
missiles.
   Defense Ministry officials testified to the committee that they
still expect the billion Trident system to come into service on
schedule. They argued there was a better chance of keeping on
schedule by using the old facilities, provided they did not break
down, than simply not doing the work.
   ``However, there is clearly some risk of breakdown and we are
concerned at the extent of reliance on the use of aging facilities
which need to be replaced,'' said the report.
   The $1.7 billion new building, known as A90, at Aldermaston was
too complex for the Atomic Weapons Facility to handle and private
consultants had to be called in, the report said.
   Plutonium and uranium components for the warheads are to be
assembled at Aldermaston, while the rest will be U.S.-made. The
submarines are being built in Britain.
   In January a London newspaper, The Independent, reported that
warhead shortages threatened the Trident program. The Defense
Ministry at first denied this, but later acknowleged ``slippages''
in the program.
   The Independent reported that mistakes in building the
Aldermaston facility meant having to tear out piping, wiring and
fittings from buidlings designed before it was known what equipment
they were to house.
   The newspaper said that extending the life of the Polaris
weapons if Trident is not ready will cost about $425 million for
each of the four submarines.
   The Polaris submarines carry fewer warheads and are more
vulnerable to Soviet attack than the new Trident system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
