<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AlienTrial     07-13 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alien Trial,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins For Minister, Journalist Charged With Alien Smuggling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was selected Wednesday in the
trial of a Lutheran minister and a journalist accused of smuggling
two pregnant Salvadoran women into the United States, and attorneys
began arguing over what evidence should be admitted.
   The defense asked U.S. District Judge John Conway to bar
statements allegedly made by a Salvadoran attorney, Luis Arturo
Ventura-Rivas, who was indicted Dec. 10 along with the Rev. Glen
Remer-Thamert and free-lance journalist Demetria Martinez.
   Ventura-Rivas remains in El Salvador and is not currently on
trial.
   Conway delayed ruling on the motion to exclude evidence, saying
he wanted to study the matter. He told attorneys to be ready with
opening statements Thursday morning.
   Remer-Thamert, 44, was indicted on nine counts of conspiracy,
transporting and harboring illegal aliens and mail fraud, the
latter charge in connection with the adoption of one of the
Salvadoran women's babies. Ms. Martinez, 28, was charged with four
counts of transporting and inducing illegal aliens.
   Conway said he was concerned about admitting into evidence a
letter allegedly written by Ventura-Rivas in November 1986 and
delivered by Remer-Thamert to one of the Salvadoran women in
Albuquerque. Conway noted the indictment charges the defendants
with a conspiracy that ended Aug. 28, 1986, but the letter was
written months later.
   He also said he had problems extending any alleged conspiracy
between Remer-Thamert and Ventura-Rivas to include Ms. Martinez.
   U.S. Attorney William Lutz argued that statements from
Ventura-Rivas should be allowed because they could be corroborated
with other evidence. But defense attorney Karen Snell of San
Francisco called that evidence hearsay.
   The only person to testify at the three-hour hearing was Mike
Murphy, a U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service investigator,
who described what the Salvadoran women told him about their trip
into the United States in August 1986.
   The women, Cecelia Elias-Alegria and Inez Campos-Anzora, were
not in court Wednesday, although they remain in the United States
and are expected to be called as prosecution witnesses.
</TEXT>
