<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Shanklin     07-13 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Shanklin,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Agent In Charge of Kennedy Shooting Probe, J.G. Shanklin, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired FBI agent J. Gordon Shanklin, who directed
the federal investigation of President John F. Kennedy's
assassination, has died of cancer. He was 78.
   Shanklin, who died Monday, was named agent in charge of the
Dallas division of the FBI in 1963, a few months before the
assassination.
   Shanklin was called ``No Comment Shanklin'' by reporters and
never spoke publicly about the FBI's investigation.
   Shanklin retired in June 1975 after 32 years with the FBI to
practice law in Dallas.
   Born and reared in Elkton, Ky., Shanklin earned bachelor's and
law degrees from Vanderbilt University.
   Shanklin practiced law in Nashville, Tenn., from 1934 to 1943,
when he joined the FBI. In addition to Dallas, he worked in FBI
offices in Huntington, W.Va.; New York; Washington, D.C.; Mobile,
Ala.; Pittsburgh; Honolulu; and El Paso.
</TEXT>
