<HEAD>Shultz Will Ask Chinese To Stop Middle East Arms Sales, Source
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Shultz was to ...' with 1 graf to UPDATE
with Shultz leaving for Beijing. PICKS up 6th graf pvs bgng, It
will be ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will try to
persuade China's leaders to stop selling missiles in the Middle
East because they are destabilizing the region, a senior State
Department source said Wednesday.
   The Chinese already have sold CSS-2 intermediate-range missiles
to Saudi Arabia and may be marketing another missile in the Middle
East still being tested in China, said the source, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``The ballistic missiles ... are being introduced into one of
the most volatile areas of the world,'' the source said. ``They
have introduced a new weapons system that had not been in the
Middle East before.''
   The source said Shultz would try to convince the Chinese
leadership the weapons flow is destabilizing the Middle East, a
process neither in China's interest nor that of the United States.
   Shultz left for Beijing on Thursday for a visit that includes
meetings with senior Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, Communist Party
General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, Premier Li Peng and Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen.
   It will be the sixth stop on a nine-nation Asian and Pacific
tour.
   Shultz arrived in Hong Kong on Wednesday for a one-day stopover
before proceeding to China, South Korea, Japan and the Marshall
Islands. He has already visited Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, and
the Philippines.
   Recent news reports have quoted Israeli officials as saying the
Chinese may be selling M-9 missiles to Syria. The State Department
source said the Chinese have denied the reports and have said the
CSS-2s sold to Saudi Arabia were non-nuclear and defensive in
nature.
   The United States believes the M-9, with an estimated range of
375 miles, is still being tested but that marketing may have begun,
the source said.
   ``China has not been a major player in the Middle East but its
emergence as a major arms suppliers in the area has changed that,''
the source said. ``So the question of how our interests interplay
in the Middle East has become more significant over the last year
and a half.''
   In Hong Kong, Shultz discussed the problem of the Vietnamese
refugee flow with the colony's governor, Sir David Wilson.
   The governor told Shultz Hong Kong was enforcing a month-old
policy of deterring the Vietnamese from leaving their homeland and
hoped to establish a repatriation program with Vietnam, a senior
U.S. administration source said.
   A political adviser to the governor is to leave for Hanoi next
week for talks with the Vietnamese on the refugee problem, which
escalated this year.
   About 20,000 refugees are in Hong Kong, including more than
3,000 who arrived since the new policy was announced.
   Hong Kong continues to grant temporary asylum but prohibits
people from seeking resettlement in third countries if they fled
their homeland for economic reasons rather to avoid political
persecution.
   The more than 90 percent of those who are regarded as economic
refugees are housed in camps and told they will eventually be sent
back to Vietnam.
   The State Department official said that in Beijing Shultz will
also discuss recent U.S.-Soviet developments, the future of
war-torn Cambodia and security at the Olympic Games in Seoul, South
Korea, which begin Sept. 17.
   The source said China has recently proposed a new peace plan for
Cambodia. China supports the Khmer Rouge and other guerrilla groups
fighting the Vietnamese, who invaded Cambodia in 1978.
   The United States and most countries are opposed to a return to
power by the Khmer Rouge, who massacred hundreds of thousands of
their countrymen in an agrarian revolution. Washington maintains
Bejing has recently become more flexible on this issue.
   The Chinese plan includes provisions for freezing military
forces of all sides and the nomination of leaders by the various
Cambodian factions that would be acceptable to all parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
