<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Visas     07-13 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Visas,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Stops Issuing Nicaraguans Tourist Visas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy temporarily stopped
issuing tourist visas to Nicaraguans, a spokeswoman announced
Wednesday, after the two countries ordered several of each other's
diplomats expelled.
   Also Wednesday, the leftist Sandinista government expropriated
Nicaragua's largest sugar and rum production company, according to
official Radio Sandino.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Jan Hartman said the embassy was forced
to stop issuing the tourist visas because it lacked personnel after
Nicaragua expelled eight diplomats. ``We just don't have enough
bodies,'' she said.
   Ms. Hartman did not say when the embassy would begin processing
the visas again.
   The government on Monday ordered U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton
and seven other diplomats to leave. The Sandinistas accused the
American diplomats of encouraging domestic dissent and unspecified
``criminal acts'' against the Nicaraguan people.
   Melton left Tuesday for Washington, and the others were due to
leave by Thursday.
   Washington retaliated by ordering out Nicaragua's ambassador and
seven other diplomats.
   Ms. Hartman said the embassy's consular section will continue
handling problems involving Americans.
   She said the embassy in recent months has handled 250 requests
for tourist visas daily.
   A leading businessman, meanwhile, attacked the government's move
to take over Ingenio San Antonio, Nicaragua's oldest and largest
sugar mill. Gilberto Cuadro, vice president of the opposition
Superior Council of Private Enterprise, called the expropriation
``the end of a mixed economy in Nicaragua.''
   President Daniel Ortega announced in June steps to move the
government away from Marxist wage and price control in order to
surmount the economic damages caused by seven years of war against
the U.S.-supported rebels known as Contras.
   Ortega said last month that the government did not plan to
abolish private enterprise ``because there would be political
pluralistic demonstrations against the revolution.''
   Radio Sandino said Wednesday the government expropriated the
mill because the wealthy Pellas family that owned it ``had not been
investing money in it since 1981.''
   The mill and accompanying enterprises, including the rum
distillery Flor de Cana, are near Chichigalpa, a city 79 miles west
of the capital.
   Since the Sandinistas seized power in July 1979, overthrowing
the rightist pro-American regime of President Anastasio Somoza,
they have taken over many privately owned companies.
   The radio said the government will appoint a special commission
to compensate the mill owners.
</TEXT>
