<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0865 07-13 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0865,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Hints At Convention Floor Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th graf pvs, bgng: Dukakis, told xxx
with new Jackson comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An indignant Jesse Jackson hinted broadly
Wednesday at a possible convention fight in Atlanta next week,
saying the floor was ``wide open'' when the No. 2 spot on the
Democratic ticket is decided.
   Jackson, rebuffed in his bid for the spot that likely Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis gave to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, returned to
Chicago to plan his convention strategy and to prepare for the bus
caravan that will take him and his supporters to Atlanta.
   Aides said he was ``flabbergasted'' at the way the announcement
of Bentsen was handled. Jackson heard from reporters Tuesday that
he had not been chosen, although Dukakis said at a news conference
Wednesday that he had tried unsuccessfully to reached Jackson
before the news got out.
   Two Democratic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Jackson was told privately Monday afternoon that he would not be
picked. One source said Dukakis emissary Paul Brountas told Jackson
``he would bring the ticket down'' if nominated for vice president.
   ``After yesterday, many people have a sense of indignation and a
sense of insult,'' Jackson said at a news conference.
   As to whether that feeling would result in a bitter fight in
Atlanta next Thursday when the vice presidential nomination is
taken up, Jackson took a wait-and-see approach and stopped short of
saying he would engineer a dispute.
   He confirmed that his supporters planned to put his name in
nomination for the presidential spot on the ticket, but would not
say whether they would do so for the vice presidential spot as well.
   ``At this point I'm not in the partnership,'' he said, adding:
``I'm not suggesting that I will compete for a place on the ticket
but the floor is wide open on Thursday night when the
recommendation is made.''
   Jackson said that ``so long as we stay within the rules and
follow the process'' the possibility of such a fight was there.
   Dukakis, told of Jackson's hint of a fight over the vice
presidential nomination, said: ``I'm confident we'll have a united
convention.''
   Later, addressing Operation PUSH, the civil rights group he
founded, Jackson criticized ``power brokers (who) have sat in small
rooms with closed doors and made great decisions.''
   ``We must be a part of this process. When they sit around these
tables, the key investors in our party are not in the group,'' he
said.
   At his news conference, Jackson said he spoke briefly with
Bentsen earlier Wednesday, describing the conversation as a
``courtesy call that I appreciated very much.''
   But he said that the choice of Bentsen was a blow to the
progressive Democrats who had helped bring the party ``back to
life.''
   ``The conservative wing is now in the equation. They have
someone recommended for the ticket, subject to ratification ... at
the convention,'' Jackson said at a news conference.
   He said his supporters have ``earned a place in the Democratic
equation'' but ``so far no talks have taken place along that line.''
   Jackson said he would leave Thursday on the ``Rainbow Express''
bus caravan that will stop in Indianapolis, Ind.; Louisville, Ky.;
Nashville, Tenn., and Chattanooga, Tenn.; on the way to Atlanta.
   At each stop, he will be registering people to vote and raising
money for a political action committee, ``Keep Hope Alive.'
   ``Our objective is simply this _ to achieve within our party a
partnership. To be a part of the equation. To share responsibility.
... We're the future of the party,'' said Jackson.
   Jackson said he was not given the nod by Dukakis yet he will be
asked to deliver votes.
   ``In reality, I'm being asked to, in spite of inadequate
communication and not being recommended for the ticket, to motivate
more people and deliver more votes and pour out more energy at
greater risk and danger than any governor or any senator.
   ``So with that responsibility, and with those obligations must
go the ability to satisfy the legitimate and reasonable requests of
those constituents. ... Those who do in fact invest in a Democratic
Party victory must get a fair return on their investment.''
</TEXT>
