<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PanamaCanal     07-13 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama Canal,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Panama Interfering With Smooth Operation of Canal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Panama Canal Commission
said Wednesday that Panama's boycott of a meeting here interferes
with the waterway's operation and threatens a smooth transition to
Panamanian ownership.
   Board Chairman William Gianelli said the Panamanian government
ordered its four members of the nine-member board not to attend the
meeting because of U.S. sanctions against Panamanian leader Gen.
Manuel Noriega. He added that Noriega, who has been indicted on
drug-related charges in Florida, also was upset when the canal
board canceled a meeting to be held in Panama in April.
   Panamanian officials say they will continue to boycott the
meetings until ``the United States normalizes relations with
Panama, whatever that means,'' Gianelli said.
   The Reagan administration, which appointed the Panama Canal
Commission's five U.S. board members, is seeking Noriega's ouster
and supporting a president whom the general removed in February.
   The board, meeting privately without its Panamanian members,
voted to suspend its regulations calling for at least two of its
four annual meetings to be held in Panama, spokesman Michael Rhode
said.
   Panama has said it will not recognize any action taken by the
canal board members here.
   Gianelli said Panama is interfering with the operation of the
canal, through which about 12,000 ships pass each year, by not
allowing administrative staff members to attend meetings.
   The commission is supposed to manage the canal until Dec. 31,
1999, when Panama is to assume full responsibility under a treaty
between the two countries.
   Gianelli said tension between the United States and Panama is
not yet affecting the operation of the canal, but could do so.
   ``We are still moving ships through the canal, but it is hurting
morale for the 8,500 employees of the commission,'' Gianelli said.
``The situation is not the healthiest thing.''
</TEXT>
