<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-SaltyRiver     07-13 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Salty River,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Corps Begins Shipping Fresh Water to Mississippi Delta Parish</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This story includes material from AM-Drought Insurance,
a0838, and can stand as an AM-Drought Rdp.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army Corps of Engineers Wednesday began
shipping fresh water from New Orleans to Plaquemines Parish at the
southern tip of the Mississippi Delta, where river water has become
too salty to drink.
   Salty Gulf of Mexico water has been creeping up the Mississippi
for weeks because the drought has reduced the river's southern flow
drastically.
   The Corps is drawing fresh water from the river at New Orleans
and shipping it on barges to Pointe a la Hache and other
Plaquemines communities. Corps spokesman Bruce Sossaman said the
first barges should reach Pointe a la Hache by early Thursday
morning.
   ``We anticipate delivering about 3{ million gallons of water a
day,'' said Don Clement, acting director of operations for the
Corps' New Orleans District.
   ``If the salt water wedge migrates up, we'll provide the same
type of a service to the other parishes as their salt content
increases,'' Clement told a gathering of state and local officials
here.
   The Corps also is constructing an underwater sill near Myrtle
Grove in Plaquemines Parish to impede the flow of salt water
upriver. The salt water is heavier than fresh water and creeps
along the river bottom.
   At the Plaquemines Parish intakes, salt concentrations have been
reported at more than 1,500 parts per million.
   Health officials say salt cannot be tasted in concentrations
below 400 or 500 parts per million and doesn't pose a health threat
until it reaches 1,000 parts per million or more.
   Heavy rain in western Tennessee lifted the shrunken Mississippi
seven-tenths of a foot higher than expected at Memphis, Tenn.,
according to James Pendergrass, a hydrologist with the Army Corps
of Engineers.
   Nevertheless, the Mississippi was still 21 feet below normal for
this time of year and the Coast Guard said the slight rise had no
effect on the river's commercial traffic.
   There were these other drought-related developments:
   _State regulators in Des Moines, Iowa, filed formal charges of
misrepresentation Wednesday against Federal Insurance Co. for
selling drought insurance policies to 1,500 Iowa farmers and then
failing to issue the policies.
   Insurance Commissioner William Hager said he would try to force
Federal, a subsidiary of the Chubb Group Insurance Cos. of Warren,
N.J., to issue the policies or give farmers a double refund on
premiums paid.
   Chubb officials said one of Federal's agents had violated his
authority in selling thousands more policies than the company had
approved, and that they would offer double refunds to farmers at a
cost of $15 million to $20 million.
   _Ohio Lt. Gov. Paul Leonard asked three state agencies to draft
proposals to combat the drought's impact and said the Legislature
might need to convene in a special session.
   ``There isn't sufficient legislation on the books to address the
drought,'' he said, adding that the state currently doesn't have
authority to intervene in local water allocation disputes.
   _Illinois Treasurer Jerry Cosentino unveiled a program of loans
for farmers at below-market interest rates.
   Cosentino said the state would provide $50 million to banks to
lend to farmers under the program and said he was prepared to add
another $150 million if necessary.
   _In Tampa, Fla., the Southwest Florida Water Management District
called for voluntary but immediate water-use cutbacks throughout a
16-county area on Florida's Gulf coast. The agency asked water
users to irrigate only before 9 a.m. and after 5 p.m., when
evaporation is reduced; to use irrigation equipment that conserves
water when possible, and to run only full loads in home dishwashers
and washing machines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
