<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Draft     07-13 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Draft ,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poland Enacts Law Allowing Alternative To Military Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament passed a law Wednesday giving
conscientious objectors the right to choose alternative civilian
work to avoid the military draft.
   ``We consider it a success,'' said Jacek Czaputowicz, head of
the outlawed peace group Freedom and Peace. The organization has
waged a three-year campaign for the right to alternative service.
   The government denied Freedom and Peace created any pressure for
passing the law.
   Lawmakers in the Sejm, or parliament, passed the measure as
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev was midway through a six-day visit
to Poland.
   Under the new law, young men may apply for alternative civilian
service for reasons of moral or religious belief. They would
otherwise have to serve two years in the Polish army, or, if
college graduates, one year.
   A draft board of military and civilian members will decide if
applicants are sincere in their beliefs. If conscientious objector
status is granted, the men will serve three years in civilian
service or two if they are university graduates.
   The alternative service will take place in state-owned
factories, according to the state-run news service PAP.
   Poland enacted the law ``in keeping with views expressed in the
United Nations and corresponding to international civil and
political rights covenants ratified by Poland,'' PAP said.
   The Sejm on June 17 also approved a change in the military oath,
removing a reference to serving beside the Soviet army. Freedom and
Peace also demanded that change.
   Czaputowicz said seven members of his group were detained in
Szczecin on Tuesday and Wednesday after they applied for a permit
to demonstrate during Wednesday's visit to that Baltic port city by
Gorbachev.
   The group had proposed a banner reading, ``OK, Gorby, thanks for
Afghanistan. When will you withdraw the troops from Poland?''
   The Soviets are in the process of withdrawing their more than
100,000 troops from Afghanistan. Western sources have recently
speculated that the Soviets might soon pull their estimated 65,000
troops from Hungary or more than 10,000 soldiers from Poland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
