<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HUD-Appropriation     07-13 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-HUD-Appropriation,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves $59.1 Billion Appropriation for HUD, NASA, Other
Agencies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate approved a $59.1 billion
appropriation bill Wednesday for the Department of Housing and
Urban Development, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and 15 other independent agencies.
   The bill, approved by a 86-11 vote, cuts off virtually all funds
for the Urban Development Block Grant program, created more than 10
years ago to aid redevelopment of distressed cities. The Reagan
administration has opposed the program for the past eight years.
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., proposed an amendment to move $30
million from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration to
UDAG but was defeated Tuesday on 64-22 vote.
   The legislation increases the appropriation for fiscal 1989,
beginning Oct. 1, by $2.4 billion for all 17 agencies over the
current year, which ends Sept. 30, and is some $409.7 million more
than requested by President Reagan.
   However, it is $633.4 million less than the appropriation
approved by the House earlier this year. A Senate-House conference
will iron out the differences before the measure is sent to the
White House.
   The legislation provides only about one-fifth of the amount
requested by the administration for a manned space station.
   Senior White House aides have said they would recommend that
Reagan veto the legislation since it provides only $200 million for
a proposed manned space station, $767.4 million less than the
administration requested.
   NASA Administrator James Fletcher issued a statement saying,
``We are disappointed at the Senate's action on funding for the
space station. If this is the ultimate outcome, it is a setback for
NASA and a blow to this country's future in space.''
   ``I hope the conference committee will reverse this action and
keep the space station on schedule,'' Fletcher said.
   The Senate appropriation is $702 million lower than the
House-approved amount for the space station. The Senate would use
the money either to phase out the program or to continue it until
the next administration determines its future.
   Other appropriations included in the measure are:
   _$12.9 billion for HUD, $1.3 billion more than requested by the
administration.
   _$5.4 billion for the Environmental Protection Agency, $611.8
million more than requested.
   _$10.1 billion NASA, $1.4 billion less than asked.
   _$1.9 billion for the National Science Foundation, $170 million
more than requested.
   _$28 billion for the Veterans Administration, $112.7 million
more than wanted by the administration.
</TEXT>
