<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0740 07-13 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0740 ,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Claim They Captured Iranian Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with reports of northern fighting,
Iraqi claims of Iran torturing prisoners. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi forces surged across the border
Wednesday and seized the western Iran city of Dehloran, and 20,000
Iranians were killed or wounded in the latest offensive, official
Iraqi radio reported.
   Official Iranian and Iraqi news agencies also reported fighting
in Iraq's northern Kurdistan province, where the Iranians still
held two major positions in the Penjwin and Hajj Omran border towns.
   Baghdad radio said the capture of Dehloran, 30 miles inside
Iran, was part of the third phase of the ``We Depend on God''
offensive.
   Iraqi forces have recaptured Iranian-held territory in southern
Iraq in recent battlefield victories.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted an unidentified senior
military commander as saying 20,000 Iranians have been killed or
wounded and 5,155 captured since the latest thrust was launched
Tuesday.
   There was no confirmation from Tehran of the Iraqi reports. But
Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Nicosia, acknowledged fighting in the southern sector of the
733-mile warfront.
   Baghdad radio interrupted regular programming to announce the
latest victory. On Tuesday, the Iranians were chased out of the
Zubaidat region, losing their last positions in southern Iraq.
   The broadcast said President Saddam Hussein personally
supervised Wednesday's battle, launched by the elite Presidential
Guard.
   Hussein and other officials have said land offensives mounted
since April were designed to liberate Iraqi territory and that
Iraqi forces would not seek to occupy Iranian land.
   After the liberation of the oil-rich Majnoon islands in a June
offensive, the Iraqis also pushed about 30 miles into Iranian
territory, chasing fleeing Iranians.
   They withdrew several days later, apparently after destroying
the Iranians' defenses across the border.
   State-run Iraqi New Agency said the Penjwin basin, but not the
town, was recaptured Wednesday and that the Iraqis were inching
toward the border.
   The Iranian agency said the attacks were repulsed and that
Iranian warplanes bombarded Iraqi troops in the region.
   Iran said Tuesday its troops withdrew from Halbja, a strategic
mountain town in the region, where Iranian-backed Kurdish rebels
live.
   Halabja, Penjwin and Hajj Omran were captured in an Iranian
thrust last March. At the time, Iran said that about 5,000 Kurdish
rebels, most of whom are backed by Iran, were killed and 7,000
wounded in Iraqi chemical bomb attacks on Halabja.
   The Iraqis began recapturing their lost territories in April.
They said they seized about 133 strategic heights in the northern
region.
   Simultaneously, they launched assaults in the south, recapturing
the southern Faw peninsula in April and the Shalamcheh and Majnoon
islands in May and June.
   An Iranian retreat from Zubaidat in a four-hour battle Tuesday
capped these victories in the nearly eight-year war.
   Meanwhile, in a letter released Wednesday at the United Nations,
Iraq accused Iran of barring visits by the Red Cross to at least
30,000 Iraqi prisoners of war and of torturing and killing
prisoners.
   In a July 4 letter to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar, Iraq's U.N. Ambassador, Ismat Kittani, quoted from a
report by the International Committee of the Red Cross to his
government.
   Kittani also said that ``the Iranian regime has subjected the
prisoners to every atrocity from which a civilized human being
would shrink.
   ``These include killing prisoners who are bound by ropes,
cutting off their limbs and burying them alive.''
   In a follow-up note sent Friday, Kittani said that when Iraqi
forces recaptured the Mawat region in northeastern Iraq near the
Iranian border, they ``found the remains of considerable numbers of
Iraqi prisoners.''
   ``It is quite clear that the Iranian regime killed them,
mutilated their corpses and burned them, after tying up some of
them with ropes,'' Kittani said in his note.
</TEXT>
