<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Seabrook     07-13 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seabrook,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility Kicks In $2 Million To Keep Nuclear Project Going</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the owners of the stalled Seabrook
nuclear power plant said Wednesday it will pay an extra $2 million
in maintenance to keep the project afloat until Sept. 1 and gain
more time to secure financing for another year.
   ``We decided that to allow Seabrook to continue in an orderly
fashion, we had better do something,'' said Robert E. Busch, senior
vice president of finance for Northeast Utilities of Connecticut.
``The idea (is to) buy some breathing room to work something out
for the longer term.''
   Seabrook would have run out of cash in two weeks without the
added funds.
   ``We wouldn't have done this interim step if we didn't think a
long-term arrangement was possible. I think it will be a complex,
difficult job, but doable,'' Busch said in a telephone interview
from NU offices in Berlin, Conn.
   Busch declined to elaborate on negotiations to get funding to
keep Seabrook alive for at least another year _ by which time plant
officials hope to win a commercial operating license.
   If a deal can't be reached, ``then I think the Seabrook project
has some pretty severe problems,'' Busch said.
   The $5.5 billion, 1,150-megawatt Seabrook reactor, owned by 12
New England utilities and holding companies, was completed two
years ago but remains idle for lack of federally approved
evacuation plans.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has refused to submit
evacuation plans for six Massachusetts communities within
Seabrook's 10-mile emergency planning zone, saying such plans would
never work.
   Every month's delay in licensing the plant adds about $50
million to its price tag in maintenance, financing and other costs,
officials have said.
   Seabrook's latest cash crunch began when directors of
Massachusetts Municipal Wholesale Electric Co. voted in June to
withhold its maintenance payment for July and try to sell its 11.6
percent stake in Seabrook. They contended that rising costs made
Seabrook financially unattractive even if it were allowed to begin
operation. MMWEC already has invested $875 million in Seabrook on
behalf of 28 utilities in Massachusetts and eight in other states.
   Seabrook's other major owners have said they cannot assume
MMWEC's payments or buy its share of the reactor. Lead Seabrook
owner Public Service Company of New Hampshire is under bankruptcy
protection and other key participants also face financial woes.
   MMWEC directors voted Wednesday to withhold its August payment
of about $2 million.
   NU, New England's largest electric utility, owns 4.1 percent of
Seabrook through the Connecticut Light & Power Co.
   In return for covering MMWEC's $2 million maintenance payment,
NU President Bernard Fox said Public Service and three other
Seabrook owners agreed to buy 250 megawatts of surplus power from
NU during the next year.
   Busch said it was a ``remote'' possibility that NU would buy
MMWEC's Seabrook share.
</TEXT>
