<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, July 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rising California Home Prices a Nightmare for First-Time Buyers</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dream of home ownership, which once
seemed almost a right to most Californians, is slipping ever
farther from first-time buyers as prices explode far beyond the
limits of the average pocketbook.
   The state's desirable climate and strong economy have long
pushed housing demand and prices ahead of the national average. But
nowadays, would-be home buyers are finding it difficult to come up
with even a down payment.
   Statistics show why: The median cost of a California home
reached $160,073 in May, nearly double the national median of
$88,600 and 13.4 percent higher than the median California home
price a year ago.
   Just 28 percent of the state's households could afford that
average-priced home in May, according to figures provided by the
California Association of Realtors. Nationally, 48 percent of
households can afford the median level home.
   ``We really want to be in a house this year, and we're going to
go into debt to our ears to do it,'' said Tim Dressendorfer, a
locksmith who once thought he and his wife could find a reasonable
starter home for $150,000 in the Long Beach area.
   After six months, they are still searching, and are now
considering taking out a variable-interest loan rather than a
fixed-rate mortgage so they can borrow more money.
   The latest state Realtors' figures show Orange County with the
highest median home price tag in the state, $202,760. The average
30-year mortgage with a 20-percent down payment on that house would
require monthly payments of $1,565, the trade group says.
   Even in affluent Orange County, only 22 percent of households
earn the $62,611 a year needed to qualify for such a mortgage.
   ``It's just so hard to save as much money as you need so your
payments aren't ridiculous,'' said Michelle St. John, 26, who rents
a home in Riverside with her husband, Judd.
   Many people sacrifice _ typically with a longer commute,
commonly two to four hours round trip in the Los Angeles area, to a
home in distant suburbs where prices are lower.
   The old option of asking Mom and Dad for help has been
supplemented these days by brokers who match investors with
potential home buyers who need a down payment. The young couple
live in the house and share the home title with their equity
partner, who shares any resale profits.
   Just how fast are prices rising? In recent months, buyers of
homes in desirable sections and suburbs of Los Angeles have found
themselves in bidding wars for their dream houses, paying far above
listed price.
   Carl McMahan, a 34-year-old downtown Los Angeles lawyer, put a
$349,000 bid on a home near Pasadena's Rose Bowl only to be outbid
at $369,000 _ $40,000 above the asking price. The home was on the
market only five hours.
   McMahan, who grew up in Fresno, joked: ``If I went to Fresno and
bought a home for $350,000 they would name a street after me.''
   Competition for homes is so fierce that customers frequently
camp out in front of sales offices at new developments, sleeping in
motorhomes and cars, sometimes for weeks, to be among the first in
line when sales open.
   When Pardee Construction Co. recently opened Phase 3 of its San
Remo tract in San Diego, 400 people were on the waiting list for 23
homes priced at $198,000 to $247,000.
   The state's slow-growth movement only adds to the dwindling
supply of homes, as the state's swelling population pushes along
demand.
   Many real estate brokers and economists warn that hard times for
first-time home buyers eventually will breed trouble throughout the
state's economy, as a generation matures without the security of
home ownership.
   ``The only weakness in the market is the entry level, and the
entry level is absolutely crucial to the marketplace and to the
long-term health of the state of California,'' said Joel Singer,
chief economist for the California Association of Realtors.
   ``I can't tell you how concerned we are about this,'' he said.
``It's a very tough battle.''
   ``You talk to any psychologist and he'll tell you people want
food, clothing and shelter,'' said Ira Gribin of Encino, incoming
president of the National Association of Realtors.
   Like many in the industry, Gribin believes the government should
subsidize housing.
   Help is being considered. Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., is
working with Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., on a national housing
policy that would, among other provisions, allow money saved for a
home down payment to be tax deductible.
   In the California Legislature, Sen. Marian Bergeson has
introduced a bill that would award lucrative state grants to cities
whose plans encourage the building of affordable homes.
   A study of 61 metropolitan areas by the National Association of
Realtors found four California locations among the 10 most
expensive areas for home buying in the first three months of 1988.
   Behind Honolulu and New York came the northern Orange County
area of Santa Ana and Anaheim, ranking third with a median home
price of $183,380 for the first quarter, followed by San Francisco
with $178,800. Los Angeles was eighth at $159,900, San Diego ninth
with $134,400.
   The Riverside-San Bernardino area, considered affordable by
Ca parents, were Lincoln
County residents, but gave no further identification.
   Hospital officials declined to comment on whether the case might
be related to an attempted abduction Sunday of another baby born at
the hospital. But police said they suspected a connection between
the cases.
   In that case, a woman told state police that after she delivered
her baby she received a visit from a woman who told her she had
recently lost a newborn baby. The mother told state police the
woman showed up later at her home in Mingo County with a gift for
the baby.
   Once inside, police said, the woman was allowed to hold the
baby, then brandished a knife and threatened to take the infant.
State police said the intruder fled when another person walked into
the room.
</TEXT>
