<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv17   07-13 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 17,0756</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>What Farmers Need Is Some Plain, Old ``Normal'' Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's an old story about the western Kansas
farmer who claimed he had ``some of that 70-mile-an-hour wheat''
and it looked pretty good, despite a hard winter, spring drought
and grasshoppers.
   Of course, the farmer meant that if you drove by the field at a
fast clip the wheat didn't look all that bad.
   In much of the nation today, drought-damaged fields don't look
good at any speed. Even in places that recently had heavy rain,
stunted corn won't produce grain or even decent forage.
   The Agriculture Department will issue another crop report on
Aug. 11 based on information from on-site field surveys. It will
include per-acre yield estimates and total production figures for
the major crops, including wheat, corn, soybeans, cotton, hay and
sorghum.
   Last week, in a special July edition, the USDA ``projected''
1988 production figures for a number of the major crops in the wake
of the drought.
   The projections were made to reflect conditions as of July 12,
the same day the report was issued, and were said by officials to
be ``highly tentative.''
   Over the last seven years, the average difference, or error
rate, between July crop projections and final production has been:
wheat, 1.9 percent; rice, 5.1 percent; corn, 12.4 percent; sorghum,
15.4 percent; oats, 10.5 percent; soybeans, 6.6 percent; and
cotton, 10.8 percent.
   ``For corn, the July projection has been below final production
in four years and above in three,'' the report said. ``The average
difference is 743 million bushels, ranging from an underestimate of
1.1 billion bushels in 1981 to an overestimate of 2 billion bushels
for 1983, the last major drought year.''
   The July 12 projections indicated the corn crop at 5.2 billion
bushels, down 29 percent from pre-drought expectations, and 26
percent less than harvested in 1987. Soybeans, projected at 1.65
billion bushels, were down 12 percent from before the drought and
13 percent below 1987 output.
   A number of state and private experts said the USDA numbers were
too high, that crop losses are greater than the projections
indicated.
   Assistant Secretary Ewen M. Wilson, the department's top
economist, told a meeting of the U.S. Agriculture Communicators'
Congress that the report represented ``the best information
existing today'' on the crop situation.
   Wilson also explained that the projections were ``based on the
assumption of normal weather from here on out'' during the the
remainder of the 1988 crop growing season.
   The projected corn output of 5.2 billion bushels this fall, down
from 7.06 billion harvested last year, would be one of the biggest
year-to-year declines on record. In 1983, drought and a huge
federal acreage-idling program designed to trim grain surpluses,
resulted in corn production of 4.17 billion bushels, down from a
record then of 8.24 billion in 1982.
   Wilson said red meat and poultry production this year is
expected to be a record 59.9 billion pounds, up nearly 3 percent
from 1987.
   ``High feed prices and lack of forage have forced some producers
to sell breeding stock, adding to meat supplies,'' he said. ``The
dairy sector also has been affected by the drought.''
   Although Wilson cited the relatively large stockpiles of wheat
and corn as buffers against shortages in 1988-89, prices are
climbing and will add to the cost of producing meat, poultry and
dairy products.
   The projections showed that corn prices could rise to an average
of $2.45 to $2.85 per bushel in the 1988-89 marketing year that
will begin Sept. 1, compared with $1.65 to $2 expected before the
drought. Corn prices in 1987-88 are forecast at an average of $1.90
to $2 per bushel.
   Wilson said pastures and livestock ranges as of July 1 were
rated 46 percent of ideal, the worst for mid-year since records
began in 1921.
   ``We expect that farmers will harvest 63 million acres of hay
this year, compared with 61 million in 1987,'' he said. ``This
acreage figure includes hay cut from the area approved for haying
and grazing on land idled by annual commodity programs and land in
the long-term Conservation Reserve Program.''
   However, the projections did not include an estimate of 1988 hay
production. That will be included for the first time in the Aug. 11
report.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 17 and thereafter</NOTE>
