<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Polaroid Bjt   07-13 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid, Bjt,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid Announces Employee Cutbacks, New Film Distribution Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Instant photography pioneer Polaroid
Corp. plans to begin worldwide distribution of conventional color
film as part of a reorganization that analysts say stems from
takeover rumors and shareholder pressure.
   The plan announced Tuesday also includes the reduction by up to
8 percent of Polaroid's domestic work force, an employee stock
ownership plan intended to acquire about 14 percent of the
company's outstanding common shares and a $300 million stock
buyback.
   ``What they are doing is very close to the type of action an
acquirer would take,'' said Eugene Glazer, an analyst at Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York. ``They are cutting back on
workers, focusing more on core business and cutting back on
(research and development) and riskier projects.''
   Officials at Polaroid would not provide details about the
production or distribution of the new line of 35mm, 126 and 110
film, which have been available in Spain and Portugal for about two
years.
   Polaroid spokesman Sam Yanes said the company has not released
sales figures for the film, which will compete against industry
leaders Eastman Kodak Co., Agfa-Gevaert and Fuji Photo Film Co. Ltd.
   Glazer said the conventional film project eliminates many of the
uncertainties linked to new products by using Polaroid's
established distribution network.
   Polaroid stock closed up $1.50 to $31.25 a share Tuesday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   The restructuring moves, estimated to save the company about $70
million annually, are in apparent response to pressure from
shareholders to increase profitability and refocus on the $7
billion annual conventional film business in the face of declining
instant photography sales.
   ``We have the worldwide name recognition, quality franchise,
global distribution system and outstanding marketing capabilities
that have enabled us to maintain our leadership position,'' I.
MacAllister Booth, Polaroid's president and chief executive, said
in a news release.
   ``...We have designed this comprehensive plan of action to
capitalize on those strengths while maximizing our internal
efficiencies, which we believe will dramatically improve our
profitability in 1989 and beyond,'' Booth stated.
   The cuts of 500 to 800 employees are planned to be completed by
January through early retirement or severance programs. A company
statement said employees could receive up to one year's salary
through the severance plan.
   The Polaroid work force has dropped from about 20,000 to 13,000
since 1978, said Yanes. About 10,000 of the present employees are
based in Massachusetts.
   Pay for the remaining workers will be reduced 5 percent to 10
percent under a employee stock ownership plan designed to purchase
about 10 million shares the company issued last year. All employees
will be required to participate in the program, with 10 percent of
top-level executives' salary being converted into stock while the
lowest-paid workers will receive stock without a cut in take-home
pay, said Yanes.
   No timetable or minimum price was announced for the $300 million
stock repurchase plan.
   Polaroid and Kodak are scheduled to appear in U.S. District
Court in Boston on Jan. 9 to begin the damage award trial in
Polaroid's $5.7 billion patent infringement suit against Kodak.
   Polaroid claims that Rochester, N.Y.-based Kodak violated
Polaroid patents on instant photography and film from 1976 to 1986.
Kodak has called the claim unreasonably inflated.
</TEXT>
