<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ColecoChronology     07-13 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleco Chronology,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Events Leading Up to Toymaker's Chapter 11 Filing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Coleco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the events leading up to
Tuesday's filing by Coleco Industries Inc. for protection under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law:
   July 16, 1987 _ Coleco announces a profit of $752,000 for the
second quarter following three consecutive losing quarters.
   Oct. 15 _ Announces earnings of $1.55 million for the third
quarter.
   Nov. 24 _ Lays off 10 percent of headquarters staff.
   Dec. 13 _ Lays off 25 workers at its headquarters.
   March 14, 1988 _ Announces it lost $98.8 million in the fourth
quarter and $105.4 million for all of 1987 and says it will miss an
April 1 interest payment on its debentures.
   March 23 _ Announces $335 million debt restructuring plan that
must be approved by debtholders.
   May 3 _ Announces it is cutting its already-reduced work force
by more than 40 percent.
   May 5 _ Chairman Arnold Greenberg resigns, is replaced by
executive vice president Morton Handel.
   May 18 _ Coleco announces $47.4 million first quarter loss, says
it will seek a buyer for several product lines.
   May 20 _ Loses license to market Trivial Pursuit, one of its
most popular products.
   June 30 _ Abandons debt restructuring plan after repeated
extensions and rejection by debtholders.
   July 12 _ Announces it has filed for protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy code.
</TEXT>
