<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PaylessCashways     07-13 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Payless Cashways,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Edelman Group Reduces Stake in Payless Cashways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by New York
financier Asher B. Edelman has reduced its stake in Payless
Cashways Inc., leading analysts to speculate that the group may
abandon efforts to acquire the building materials retailer.
   The group sold about 500,000 Payless shares Friday, reducing its
holding from 8.1 percent to 6.3 percent, according to documents
filed Tuesday with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The
group, which now owns about 2.1 million shares, remains the
company's largest shareholder.
   The group, directed by Edelman and Sutherland Lumber-Southwest
Inc. of Kansas City, did not disclose why more shares had been
sold. Perry Sutherland, a member of the group, declined to comment
on what the investors planned to do with their remaining shares.
   Analysts said the stock sale seemed to clear the way for a group
of Payless senior managers to buy the company for $27 a share, or
$909 million. Their bid, announced June 30, requires shareholder
approval.
   Payless became the subject of takeover rumors more than three
months ago when its stock soared in heavy trading. In May, the
Edelman-Sutherland group disclosed it had a large stake in Payless
and said that it might try to acquire the company. The group later
increased its position to 9.9 percent.
   Since then, the group periodically has sold Payless shares.
Moreover, the group has not made an offer for Payless, and recently
the investors stopped commenting publicly on what they planned to
do.
   Sutherland Lumber is a competitor of Payless and is also based
in Kansas City.
   Payless stock, traded on the New York Stock Exchange, fell
Tuesday to $26.75, down 37{ cents a share.
   Analysts said that because the Edelman-Sutherland group had been
selling Payless shares since late May, it appeared unlikely that
that group or anyone else would make a competing offer.
   ``I'd say the chances of another offer is about the same as the
(management) deal not going through,'' said Richard Pyle, an
analyst who follows Payless at Piper, Jaffray & Hopwood Inc. in
Minneapolis.
   Payless has 200 stores in 26 states and has about 15,000
employees. It has 10 stores in the Kansas City area, where it
employs 1,400 people.
</TEXT>
