<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Astros     07-13 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Astros,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vans Cause A Big Stink For Automaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has discovered that 1987
Chevrolet Astro and GMC Safari vans with 4.3-liter engines and
overdrive transmissions might spew exhaust that smells like rotten
eggs.
   GM has issued a service bulletin to dealers with instructions on
how to fix the problem. Among the recommendations is replacement of
the on-board computer that monitors the fuel mix in the engine.
   The computer is only used in vans with the overdrive
transmission.
   An improper fuel mix results in the buildup of a sulfur and
hydrogen, causing the rotten egg smel.
   GM spokesman Dee Allen of the Chevrolet-Pontiac-GM of Canada
Group said heavy use of the vans can cause the problem.
   The problem does not affect all 4.3-liter GM engines, such as
those installed in pickup trucks, Allen said.
   There were fewer than 72,000 1987-model Chevy Astro vans and GMC
Safari vans sold, the newspaper said. The problem was fixed in 1988
vans, the technician said.
</TEXT>
