<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 0905EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMLayoffs     07-13 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Layoffs,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indefinite Layoffs Planned At GM's Doraville Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DORAVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. will lay off about
800 hourly workers at its Doraville production plant for an
indefinite period beginning Friday, company officials say.
   The plant will be closing for a month to make a model change.
When the suburban Atlanta facility reopens Aug. 16, only about
4,100 of the plant's 4,900 hourly workers will return to work, said
George J. Simms, the plant's personnel director.
   The plant will be staffed then for production of 50 cars an
hour, according to Simms. Since November, it has been staffed with
enough workers to make 75 an hour, although that production has
been frozen at 50 per hour, or 800 a day, since May 31.
   The Doraville plant is being equipped to make the 1989
Oldsmobile Cutlass.
   Almost all of the plant's production workers will be laid off
temporarily during the model change, Simms said. Those who do not
return next month will be eligible for jobs in training and other
non-production areas.
   Neither Simms nor Jerry J. Hall, president of the United Auto
Workers Local 10, could say how long the indefinite layoffs might
last.
   Hall said he hoped many of the laid-off workers would be
recalled by August 1989, when the plant begins building a four-door
version of the Cutlass. Currently, the plant makes a two-door model.
   Hall said he did not believe that GM froze production at
Doraville because of poor Cutlass sales. Cutlass sales reportedly
are on the increase after a slow start.
   Doraville is GM's sole facility for the Cutlass.
</TEXT>
