<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-13 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0317</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today in a
drifting summer session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 2.84 to 2,095.48 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in the early tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 497 up, 381 down and
503 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 30.29 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Close to half of that activity came on dividend-related trading
in a single issue, Pacific Enterprises, which was up [ at 47.
   Otherwise, analysts said many market participants were holding
back awaiting Friday's report from the Commerce Department on the
nation's international trade balance for May.
   Some observers worry that the recent run of favorable trade news
might have about run its course, or that continued strength in
exports might provide a fresh signal of potential credit-tightening
by the Federal Reserve.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, told a congressional
committee today that the Fed took several steps to restrain the
economy in recent months with the aim of keeping inflation in check.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Exxon rose [ to 44|; General
Electric gained [ to 42]; American Telephone & Telegraph dropped [
to 26[, and International Business Machines was down [ at 125[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.15 to 151.77. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .07 at 307.24.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 18.67 to
2,092.64.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones about 7 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 442 issues up, 1,039 down and 481 unchanged. Big Board
volume totaled 161.65 million shares, up from 123.30 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
