<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0279</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned upward today, recouping
some of Tuesday's losses as interest rates declined.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 18.67 on Tuesday,
rose 8.71 to 2,101.35 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in the overall count
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 638 up, 475 down and
549 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 74.88 million shares at
midmorning.
   About a third of that activity came on dividend-related trading
in a single issue, Pacific Enterprises, which was up [ at 47.
   Otherwise, analysts said the market drew some encouragement from
remarks by Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
in congressional testimony.
   Greenspan said the Fed took several steps to restrain the
economy in recent months with the aim of keeping inflation in check.
   By implication, brokers said, Greenspan seemed to be suggesting
that no further credit-tightening might be needed in the near
future to achieve that end. Bond-market interest rates fell after
accounts of his comments crossed financial news wires.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose [ to 125]; Exxon was steady at 44{, and American
Telephone & Telegraph dropped [ to 26[.
   Intel gained \ to 36 in the over-the-counter market. On Tuesday
the company reported a sharper-than-expected increase in its
earnings for the second quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.43 to 152.05. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .08 at 307.23.
</TEXT>
