<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-13 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Surge Their Limits On Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices soared their
daily limits at the opening today on the Chicago Board of Trade in
reaction to a government report showing severe drought damage to
those crops.
   In a special report issued Tuesday afternoon, the Agriculture
Department estimated this year's corn production would fall more
than 26 percent below last year to a 5-year low, based on current
crop conditions. The USDA said soybean production probably would
decline by at least 14 percent from last year's 1.9 billion bushels.
   Many analysts had called the estimates conservative and were
expecting a less dramatic reaction from traders.
   ``I guess their enthusiasm picked up after they had a chance to
sleep on it,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst in Chicago with the
trading firm G.H. Miller & Co.
   Forecasts for a dry weekend in the Corn Belt followed by a
return to 100-degree temperatures gave prices an additional boost,
he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 6 cents to 8} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.90 a bushel; corn was 3{ cents
to the limit 10 cents higher with the limitless July contract up 16
cents at $3.22 a bushel; oats were up the 10-cent limit across the
board except for the limitless July contract, which was up 15 cents
at $2.94 a bushel; soybeans were locked up the 30-cent limit with
limitless July contract up 38{ cents at $9.18 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .65 cent lower to .23 cent higher with August
at 65.17 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to .82 cent
lower with August at 74.97 cents a pound; hogs were .62 cent lower
to .68 cent higher with July at 45.05 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .15 cent to 1.90 cents higher with July at 35
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Tuesday while pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
