<HEAD>Wackenhut is Leader in Airline Security</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Airlines-Security Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wackenhut Corp. is the leader in airline
security work among U.S. security companies. Here are the companies
that provide passenger screening and other security services under
contract to the nation's major airlines:
   _WACKENHUT CORP., Coral Gables, Fla.
   Services: Provides a variety of security services, including
nuclear power plant protection and security at U.S. embassies
overseas, as well as airline work. Clients include nearly all the
major U.S. airlines.
   Total employees (including airline services): 28,000 full-time,
4,000 part-time.
   1987 net income: $5.66 million on revenue of $382 million.
   _GLOBE SECURITY SYSTEMS INC., Philadelphia.
   Services: Provides security services to airlines, nuclear power
plants and government installations. It currently has five airline
clients and operates in about 40 airports.
   Total employees: 6,500, including about 500 in airline services.
   1987 revenue: $125 million.
   _J.J. SECURITY INC., Green Bay, Wis.
   Services: Provides airplane crash and fire rescue assistance as
well as passenger screening and other routine services. It has
around 100 airline clients and operates in 70 airports, mainly in
the Midwest, Southwest and California.
   Total employees: 2,000, including about 1,300 in airline
services.
   Financial data not disclosed.
   _OGDEN ALLIED SERVICES CORP., New York.
   Services: Provides general cargo handling and building cleaning
as well as airline security work, in-flight food service and
security services for other industries.
   Total employees: 45,000 (not all involved in security).
   1987 net income: $36 million on revenue of $1.15 billion.
(Financial data for security services are not broken out.)
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday July 18</NOTE>
