<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market put together a modest gain
today, recouping some of Tuesday's losses as interest rates
declined.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 18.67 on Tuesday,
rose 5.87 to 2,098.51 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in the overall count
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 680 up, 534 down and
556 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 126.90 million shares at
noontime.
   A big chunk of that activity came on dividend-related trading in
a single issue, Pacific Enterprises, which was up [ at 47.
   Otherwise, analysts said the market drew some encouragement from
remarks by Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
in congressional testimony.
   Greenspan said the Fed took several steps to restrain the
economy in recent months with the aim of keeping inflation in check.
   By implication, brokers said, Greenspan seemed to be suggesting
that no further credit-tightening might be needed in the near
future to achieve that end. A rise in interest rates is ``not
inevitable,'' he said.
   Bond-market interest rates fell after accounts of his comments
crossed financial news wires.
   Among actively traded blue chips, General Electric rose [ to
42}; Exxon was up [ at 44|; International Business Machines lost [
to 125[, and American Telephone & Telegraph dropped [ to 26[.
   Intel gained { to 36\ in the over-the-counter market. On Tuesday
the company reported a sharper-than-expected increase in its
earnings for the second quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.32 to 151.94. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .15 at 307.16.
