<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Warner-Chris-Craft     07-13 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Warner-Chris-Craft,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warner Says It Will Contest Chris-Craft Suit to Delay Lorimar
Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. says it will
vigorously defend itself against a lawsuit filed by Chris-Craft
Industries Inc., its largest shareholder, to delay Warner's $1.18
billion acquisition of Lorimar Telepictures Corp.
   Chris-Craft, a broadcasting and manufacturing company, filed the
suit Tuesday in New York State Court.
   In a statement issued Wednesday, Warner denied Chris-Craft's
claim that the merger with Lorimar, which owns six television
stations, would violate a 1984 agreement prohibiting Warner from
owning any TV station so long as it owns 25 percent or more of
Chris-Craft's BHC Inc. broadcasting subsidiary.
   Warner has a 42.5 percent stake in BHC, which it acquired from
Chris-Craft in 1984 in exchange for a 23 percent interest in
Warner's voting stock.
   Chris-Craft's suit seeks to delay the completion of the merger
until Lorimar has sold its TV stations to an outside party or
Warner has transferred enough of its BHC stock so that it owns less
than 25 percent of the unit.
   Warner has proposed putting the six Lorimar stations in a voting
trust, but Chris-Craft maintained that would still violate the 1984
agreement and cause injury to Chris-Craft.
   Warner said it intends to move forward to complete the merger,
which puts a value of about $14 on each of Lorimar's 47 million
outstanding common shares, for a total of around $630 million. In
addition, Warner plans to assume Lorimar's debt of about $550
million.
   Chris-Craft's four representatives on Warner's board of
directors abstained from voting when the merger was approved by
Warner and Lorimar in May. Chris-Craft management is said to
believe the Lorimar stations are of inferior quality and shouldn't
be purchased by Warner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
