<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Mead     07-13 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Mead,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Up 41 Percent in 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mead Corp. said Wednesday that its earnings
jumped by 41 percent in the second quarter on a 7.4 percent rise in
sales.
   The paper products and electronic publishing company said the
gains were the result of strong demand in all of its product lines.
   For the quarter ended July 3, profit totaled $73 million, or
$1.12 a share, on net sales of $1.16 billion. That compared with
earnings of $51.9 million, or 82 cents a share, on sales of $1.08
billion in the same 1987 period.
   For the first six months, it said earnings rose 61 percent to
$138.8 million, or $2.13 a share, from $86.1 million, or $1.37 a
share, last year.
   Six-month sales rose 10.3 percent to $2.25 billion from $2.04
billion.
   Mead said a non-recurring gain of 17 cents a share was included
in this year's first-quarter results. Even without that gain,
however, the company said earnings per share were 43 percent above
those in the same period of 1987.
   Burnell R. Roberts, Mead's chairman and chief executive officer,
said strong order backlogs through the first half of the year
enabled Mead's mills and plants to operate at a high level.
   The company's publishing paper division led the second-quarter
earnings improvement, Roberts said, but orders continued to climb
for other divisions.
   Mead said the purchase of Brunswick Pulp & Paper Co. by Georgia
Pacific Corp., announced last month, will results in a one-time
gain of about $1.50 a share. That gain will be reflected in
third-quarter earnings, Mead said.
</TEXT>
