<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0323</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed lower today after an
early advance played itself out.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up about 10 points at
its morning peak, was down 6.94 at 2,085.70 by 2 p.m. on Wall
Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 6 in the overall count
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 593 up, 691 down and
592 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 157.85 million shares with two
hours to go.
   About a third of that activity came on dividend-related trading
in a few high-yielding stocks.
   Otherwise, analysts said many market participants were holding
back awaiting Friday's report from the Commerce Department on the
nation's international trade balance for May.
   Some observers worry that the recent run of favorable trade news
might have about run its course, or that continued strength in
exports might provide a fresh signal of potential credit-tightening
by the Federal Reserve.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, told a congressional
committee today that the Fed took several steps to restrain the
economy in recent months with the aim of keeping inflation in check.
   However, brokers said he also seemed to be suggesting that no
further credit-tightening might be needed in the near future to
achieve that end. A rise in interest rates is ``not inevitable,''
he said.
   Among actively traded blue chips, General Electric dropped \ to
42]; International Business Machines lost 1\ to 124, and American
Telephone & Telegraph dropped \ to 26.
   Intel gained \ to 36 in the over-the-counter market. On Tuesday
the company reported a sharper-than-expected increase in its
earnings for the second quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.30 to 151.32. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .52 at 306.79.
</TEXT>
