<2ND_LINE>BC-Stock Journal,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OTC Stock Journal Put Up For Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National OTC Stock Journal and its sister
company, OTC America Inc., are for sale following financial
difficulties, executives say.
   Terry Freeman, president of OTC America and publisher of the
weekly newspaper about the over-the-counter market, has disclosed
his companies' financial troubles in several articles and letters
written since mid-June.
   Both OTC Stock Journal, published in Denver, and OTC America are
public companies with shares traded on the pink sheets, a loosely
organized market of 20,000 issues. Both have suffered since the
October stock market crash.
   Freeman's OTC Stock Journal, published since 1981, has
chronicled the fortunes of Denver's penny stock brokers and the
companies they underwrite since the heyday of penny stocks in
Denver.
   Its major competitor is the Penny Stock News based in Columbia,
Md.
   If a sale cannot be arranged, Freeman said he would try to
continue publishing the stock journal.
   Freeman, 41, worked for CBS Inc. in San Francisco. He also
worked briefly for Penny Stock News before buying an interest in
the publication in 1981. OTC Stock Journal became a public company
through a merger with Hair Analysis Inc. in 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
