<1ST_LINE>u f PM-PlantClosing 3rdLd-Writethru   07-13 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Closing, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs, subs 2nd graf, The vote, with 2 new grafs to
say 10 members did not vote. Removes pvs grafs 8-12, Both sides, as
outdated.</NOTE>
<HEAD>House Appoves 60-Day Plant Closing, Layoff Notices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed legislation today requiring
companies to give workers and local officials 60 days advance
notice of plant closings and large layoffs.
   The vote was 286-136. That was four more than the two-thirds
majority of those voting that would be required to override an
expected veto by President Reagan. Ten members of the House did not
vote.
   If all members voted, 288 votes would be needed to override a
veto.
   Fifty-four Republicans voted against the administration on the
issue.
   Regan vetoed a massive trade bill in May, saying the
plant-closing provision was his main reason for doing so.
   The AFL-CIO threatened to withdraw its pivotal support from the
trade measure, which was to be acted on later today in the House,
if the layoff provisions were not enacted first.
   Democrats earlier had voted to give Republican opponents only
one opportunity to amend the bill. But Republican leaders decided
against it at the last minute.
   ``There are a lot of people in this country who have not been a
part of this burgeoning economic miracle that some talk about,''
said Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich. ``Nearly half of today's displaced
workers had no notice whatosover.''
   House Republicans complained they were being given only one
chance to alter a bill that is not needed in the first place in
view of the 5{-year-long economic recovery, the longest in the
nation's history.
   ``Why are we doing this?'' House Minority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., asked rhetorically. ``Job levels are at an all-time high,
unemployment is at a 14-year low.''
   Business groups made a last-ditch effort to head off what would
be organized labor's biggest political victory this decade.
   Both sides have been waging a massive grassroots letter,
telegram and phone campaign the past week.
   The House has voted on the issue only once before. The provision
was supported then by a 253-vote majority _ far short of the 290
votes that labor considers comfortable for sustaining a veto _ when
Republicans tried to strike it from a trade bill last spring.
   Reagan cited the mandated notices as his primary reason for
vetoing a massive overhauling of the nation's trade laws in May,
saying they were anticompetitive and would stifle new job creation.
   Vice President George Bush, who has wrapped up the Republican
nomination, supported Reagan's veto, saying he favors telling
workers in advance they are about to be laid off but companies
shouldn't be forced to do so.
   When subsequent polls showed more than 80 percent voter support
for requiring the notices, Democrats seized on the issue to attack
Reagan and Bush on domestic economic issues.
   ``If Edwin Meese can give himself 30 days' notice, the least we
can do is give American workers 60 days' notice before we lay them
off,'' Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis said
Tuesday.
   Meese announced his resignation as Reagan's attorney general
last week, giving no specific date when he will step down other
than to say it will be in either late July or early August.
   ``Politics has the priority,'' complained Senate Republican
Leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``It is not the working man or working
woman we're talking about. It is who might win in November. That
has become the issue, not the merits of this bill.''
   White House lobbyists pointed out after the Senate vote that
Reagan has not definitely said he would veto the plant closing
measure. Under the law, he has 10 working days to sign the bill,
exercise a veto or allow it to become law without his signature.
   But both sides still anticipate a veto, regardless the margin of
today's vote.
   Business groups fear a victory for the AFL-CIO on the plant
closing and layoff notices will open a Pandora's box of other labor
legislation such as mandated health benefits, maternity leaves and
measures making it easier for unions to organize workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
