<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed sharply higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade with most contracts up
their allowable limit in reaction to a government report showing
severe drought damage to crops.
   In addition to lowering its 1988 corn production estimate by 29
percent, the Agriculture Department estimated soybean plantings
this year ...
... expectations, analysts said.
   Those factors, plus forecasts for a return to extremely hot, dry
weather in the Midwest this weekend, sent corn and soybean prices
up their daily limits at the opening. Oats also locked limit-up and
wheat finished sharply higher.
   Scattered showers were predicted in the Corn Belt from Wednesday
night through Friday morning but traders fixated on the weekend
forecasts, analysts said.
   ``My weather people seem to feel the amounts in any rains
anticipated tonight, tomorrow and even Friday morning will be a
quarter- to a half-inch, and that's not significant enough moisture
to break any drought, particularly with the hot weather staring us
in the face,'' said Jerry Gidel, grains analyst with the
Chicago-based trading company G.H. Miller & Co.
   At the close, wheat was 7 cents to 13 cents higher with July at
$3.89{ a bushel; corn was the limit 10 cents higher across the
board except for the limitless July contract, which was up 28 cents
at $3.34 a bushel; oats were locked up the 10-cent limit with
limitless July up 25{ cents at $3.04{ a bushel; soybeans were
locked up the 30-cent limit with limitless July up 67{ cents at
$9.47 a bushel.
</TEXT>
