<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Rover 1stLd-Writethru   07-13 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Rover, 1st Ld-Writethru,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Aerospace Reconsidering Bid for Rover</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf to CLARIFY status of British Aerospace; picks
up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, British Aerospace also ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Aerospace PLC said Wednesday it was
reconsidering its takeover bid for Rover Group PLC after the
European Economic Community ordered a large cut in the British
government's planned cash injection into the state-owned automaker.
   British Aerospace had reached an agreement with the British
government to acquire its 99.8 percent stake in Rover for 150
million pounds, or about $254 million at current exchange rates. At
the same time, the government had said it would inject 800 million
pounds, or around $1.35 billion, into Rover to reduce the
automaker's debt.
   But the EEC's executive Commission, which has the power to block
deals that it considers harmful to competition in the 12-nation
trading bloc, said earlier Wednesday it approved a smaller British
aid package of 469 million pounds.
   Because some regional aid also would be allowed, the government
subsidy effectively would be reduced to 547 million pounds, British
Trade Secretary Lord Young said.
   British Aerospace, an aircraft manufacturer that was privatized
by the Conservative government, said it requested more time to
consider its proposed takeover in light of the Commission's ordered
reduction in British aid.
   British Aerospace also said that trading in its shares, which
was halted earlier Wednesday pending the EEC announcement, would
remain suspended.
   Negotiations between the government and British Aerospace were
continuing, he said.
   Peter Sutherland, the EEC's competition commissioner, said in
Brussels, Belgium, that the Commission ``came to the conclusion
that not all of the elements making up the 800 million-pound
write-off could be considered as (Rover) debt.''
   He said that allowing the British government to write off all of
Rover's debt would have placed the automaker in an ``artificially
favorable situation vis-a-vis competitors.''
   Meanwhile, Rover said it swung into profit in the first half of
its fiscal year, helped by healthy operating profit at its Austin
Rover car division and a strong recovery by its Land Rover unit
after a pay dispute earlier this year. The Land Rover is an
all-terrain vehicle.
   Rover reported after-tax profit of 5 million pounds, or about $8
million, in the six months ended July 2, compared with an after-tax
loss of 42 million pounds, or $71 million, in the same period a
year earlier.
   Revenue rose to 1.55 billion pounds, or $2.62 billion, from 1.53
billion pounds, or $2.59 billion, a year earlier.
</TEXT>
