<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Utilities-Spending     07-13 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Utilities-Spending,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investor-Owned Utilities Raise Capital Appropriations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public utility companies raised their planned
spending in the final quarter of 1987, signaling possible growth in
the industry to meet future consumer demand, the Conference Board
said Wednesday.
   Spending authorizations for plant and equipment reached $6.1
billion in the final quarter of 1987, an increase of more than 11
percent from the year-earlier period and an 18.7 percent rise from
the previous quarter, the report said.
   ``This is the most positive sign we've had in quite some time
that the utility industry is beginning to recognize the need for
more capacity to meet future demand and to plan for it,'' said
Kenneth Goldstein, an economist with the Conference Board, a
business-financed research organization.
   Goldstein said results of the quarterly survey represented ``a
significant turnaround in utility spending, which has been held
down by sluggish demand and regulatory and competitive pressures.''
   An increase in utility spending probably will not affect
consumers for several years, when utilities begin expanding their
current plants, he said.
</TEXT>
