<DOCNO> AP880713-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet     07-13 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street,0495</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late round of buying attributed to computer
program trading gave the stock market a lift in the waning moments
of an erratic session Wednesday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down about 10 points at
its afternoon lows, closed with an 11.73-point gain at 2,104.37.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 6 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
782 up, 668 down and 525 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 218.93 million
shares, against 161.65 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 242.78 million shares.
   A big chunk of the day's activity came in dividend-related
trading of a few high-yielding stocks.
   Otherwise, analysts said many market participants were holding
back awaiting Friday's report from the Commerce Department on the
nation's international trade balance for May.
   Some observers worry that the recent run of favorable trade news
might have about run its course, or that continued strength in
exports might provide a fresh incentive for credit-tightening by
the Federal Reserve.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, told a congressional
committee Wednesday that the Fed took several steps to restrain the
economy in recent months with the aim of keeping inflation in check.
   However, brokers said he also seemed to be suggesting that no
further credit-tightening might be needed in the near future to
achieve that end. A rise in interest rates is ``not inevitable,''
Greenspan said.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up | at
43\; Philip Morris, up 1\ at 89~; Exxon, up | at 45[, and
McDonald's, up { at 46}.
   Federal National Mortgage jumped 3\ to 47\. The company posted
second-quarter earnings of $1.52 a share, up from 74 cents in the
comparable period last year.
   Pier 1 Imports tumbled 3\ to 10{. The company said it ended
talks with prospective buyers, having been advised by its
investment bankers to remain independent.
   York International, which said it received a $61-a-share
acquisition bid from Snydergeneral Corp., gained 3\ to 59[.
   Intel rose { to 36\ in the over-the-counter market. On Tuesday
the company reported a sharper-than-expected increase in its
earnings for the second quarter.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $10.95 billion, or
0.41 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.65 to 152.27.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 1.45 to 311.12, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.47 at 269.32.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market edged
up .04 to 393.56. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 307.66, up .35.
