<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Zondervan-Harper&Row     07-13 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zondervan-Harper & Row,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harper & Row Signs Merger Agreement with Zondervan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publishing giant Harper & Row
announced Wednesday it has agreed to buy financially troubled
Zondervan Corp., the market leader in Bible sales.
   Robert Biewen, group vice president for educational and
professional publishing at Harper & Row in New York, said the
company will start a cash tender offer for all of Zondervan's more
than 4.2 million shares at $13.50 per share.
   Total cost of the merger agreement could reach about $57
million, Biewen said.
   Brent D. Clark, Zondervan corporate counsel, said it is now up
to Zondervan shareholders to approve the deal.
   ``The company believes it's a fair offer and the final decision
is left up to the shareholders in the tender-offer process,'' Clark
said.
   Grand Rapids-based Zondervan owns an 80-store chain of
bookstores and operates a book and Bible division and music
publishing concern. It owns exclusive rights for the new
International version Bible, the market leader in Bible sales.
   Zondervan's board of directors unanimously approved the deal.
The directors have been trying to sell the publisher since October
1986, when a group of hostile shareholders threatened a takeover.
The company reported a net profit in 1987 of $859,000, down 60
percent from its 1986 net profit of $2.1 million.
   ``We are pleased to have reached an agreement with such a
distinguished publishing firm, which has the financial strength to
help Zondervan achieve its full potential,'' said James G. Buick,
Zondervan's president and chief executive officer.
   Harper & Row officials said the acquisition will boost the
company's standing in the religious publishing business.
   ``Harper & Row has a long and distinguished tradition in
religious publishing, and with the acquisition of Zondervan, we are
pleased to be expanding our efforts in the largest segment of our
market,'' said George Craig, Harper & Row president and chief
executive officer.
   Biewen said Zondervan's offices would remain in Grand Rapids and
it would retain an independent editorial voice if the merger goes
through. He added that it would coordinate marketing with Harper &
Row's San Francisco-based religious publishing subsidiary.
</TEXT>
