<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern-Unions     07-13 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Unions,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Says It's Made New Offers to Machinists, Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said Wednesday it has made new
conciliatory offers to its Machinists and pilots union, although
the financially pressed carrier is still trying to slash overall
labor costs.
   Thomas Matthews, Eastern's vice president for human resources,
said this week ``we put our best compromise on the table to get an
agreement.'' He noted that last week, Eastern and its unions made
agreements on handling safety issues and worker complaints.
   ``Those meetings let us put the safety question behind us,''
Matthews was quoted as saying in Wednesday's editions of the Wall
Street Journal. ``Now we are trying to put our other differences
behind us.''
   The proposals made this month would save Eastern an estimated
$229 million annually, the airline said. They would move it near a
goal of around 30 percent in labor cost cuts set by President Phil
Bakes in January 1987.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said management's proposal to
the pilots includes protection of salaries, days off and job
security. She said it also contains a ``fence agreement''
guaranteeing that Eastern would remain separate from Continental
Airlines by flying at least 217 aircraft and keeping the Air Line
Pilots Association as the recognized representative of Eastern
pilots.
   Eastern and nonunion Continental are both subsidiaries of
Houston-based Texas Air Corp., the nation's largest airline
company. Union critics have accused Texas Air management of
intending to strip Eastern's assets.
   Eastern has offered guarantees of no layoffs for any pilot hired
before July 1, 1984, and to maintain the pilots' current wages and
15 days off monthly, Ms. Ceremsak said.
   Changes in the pilots' complex work rules would save the company
$69 million a year, she said.
   For the 12,000 Machinists at Eastern, Ms. Ceremsak said, Eastern
pledged job security for anyone hired before May 16, 1984.
   Eastern's overall offer to the Machinists, with whom it's been
in federal mediation for seven months, would cut their costs to
Eastern by $160 million annually, according to the airline. The
current Machinists' offer would add $50 million to annual costs,
Ms. Ceremsak said.
   The Machinists refused to join the Eastern pilots and flight
attendants in accepting 20 percent wage cuts in February 1986 that
preceded the sale of Eastern to Texas Air.
   Ms. Ceremsak said Eastern would largely protect the wages of the
mechanics, ``to recognize their marketplace value.'' Under the
company proposal, top-scale mechanics' wages would decline from
$18.83 to $18 an hour, she said.
   The new Eastern offer would reduce baggage handlers' wages, now
at $15.60 an hour for top scale, to $10 hourly for the three-year
contract. Originally, she said, Eastern proposed cutting the
baggage handlers' pay to $10 an hour the first year of the
contract, $9 the second year and $8 the third.
   Other cuts for Machinists would involve their benefits packages,
she said, bringing them in line with Eastern's other unions.
   Machinists local President Charles E. Bryan said details of the
negotiations are supposed to be secret. He agreed that progress was
being made, but declined further comment.
   Bryan said Eastern continues to push for release from federal
mediation, which would activate a 30-day strike deadline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
