<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Banks     07-13 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Chicago Has Strong 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Chicago Corp., the nation's 10th largest
banking company, reported vastly improved second-quarter earnings
Wednesday, due partly to its sale of $900 million of securities
backed by credit-card debt.
   First Chicago reported net income of $122.9 million, or $2.02
per share, for the three months ending June 30, compared with a net
loss of $599.9 million, or $10.96 per share, for the same period a
year ago.
   The loss in the second quarter of 1987 was due to an $800
million addition to reserves to cover potential losses on loans to
troubled countries, the company said.
   Net interest income for the second quarter was $305.9 million
compared with $309.4 million a year ago. Non-interest income for
the quarter totaled $234.7 million compared with $120.7 million a
year ago.
   First Chicago's sale of $900 million in securities backed by
credit card receivables had the effect of lowering the company's
net interest income while raising its non-interest income, said
spokesman Anthony B. Zehnder.
   Return on common assets for the second quarter was 1.09 percent
and return on common equity was 30.18 percent.
   For the first six months of 1988, First Chicago had net income
of $264.4 million, or $4.40 per share, compared with a net loss of
$536.1 million, or $9.90 a share, a year ago.
   Net interest income for the first half was $621.2 million,
compared with $587.2 million a year ago. Non-interest income
totaled nearly $630.6 million, compared with $543.8 million.
   First Chicago said it had reduced outstanding loans to troubled
countries by $350 million during the second quarter and by $505
million since the end of 1987.
</TEXT>
