<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   07-13 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0858</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Prices Soar On Crop Report, Weather Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices blasted out of their recent
slump Wednesday in response to the government's report of severe
drought damage to crops and forecasts for more hot, dry weather in
the Farm Belt.
   On other markets, silver futures soared, pulling the precious
metals higher; livestock and meat futures were mixed; cotton
plummeted; energy futures sank; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Analysts said Tuesday's special crop report from the Agriculture
Department was largely responsible for the leap in prices for
future deliveries of grain and soybeans.
   Besides slashing its 1988 corn production estimate by 29 percent
to a 5-year low of 5.2 billion bushels, the USDA estimated soybean
plantings this year at 58.52 million acres, a figure below the
market's expectations, analysts said.
   The agency also lowered its soybean and wheat production
estimates by 12 and 13 percent respectively, and predicted overall
grain production would be nearly 25 percent below last year's level.
   Many traders had called the damage estimates conservative and
some were predicting, even minutes before the markets opened, that
soybean prices would rise only moderately on the data.
   But within minutes of the opening bell, traders had bid most
corn contracts up the maximum of 10 cents a bushel and most soybean
contracts were up their 30-cents-a-bushel limit. The sharp advances
halted trading in all but the July contracts, on which limits have
been removed pending their July 20 expiration.
   Jerry Gidel, an analyst in Chicago with the trading firm G.H.
Miller & Co., called the crop-production numbers ``impressive'' and
said most traders apparently came to the same conclusion after
digesting the data.
   ``I guess their enthusiasm picked up after they had a chance to
sleep on it,'' he said.
   In addition to the crop report, forecasts for a return to
extremely hot, dry weather in the Midwest kept the buy orders
coming. Gidel said unfilled buy orders for December deliveries of
corn totaled more than 30 million bushels at the close of the
session, and unfilled buy orders for November soybeans totaled more
than 6 million bushels.
   Scattered showers were predicted in the Midwest from Wednesday
night through Friday morning but traders fixated on forecasts for
the weekend and beyond, analysts said.
   A National Weather Service 6-to-10-day forecast issued after the
close predicted above-normal temperatures and below-normal rainfall
for most growing areas during the middle and latter parts of next
week.
   The agency's 30-day outlook called for continued hot and dry
conditions in the Midwest and Great Plains through mid-August.
   Wheat settled 10} cents to 17 cents higher with July at $3.92 a
bushel; corn was 10 cents to 27{ cents higher with July at $3.33{ a
bushel; oats were 10 cents to 25{ cents higher with July at $3.04{
a bushel; soybeans were 30 cents to 69 cents higher with July at
$9.48{ a bushel.
   Reports of a silver miners' strike in Peru sent silver futures
prices soaring on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   But John O'Connell, metals analyst in New York with Refco Inc.,
said abundant supplies of silver in the exchange's approved
warehouses should temper any fears of shortages.
   ``I think there's enough silver in Comex warehouses to take care
of everybody for a long time,'' he said.
   Silver settled 19.1 cents to 20.6 cents higher with July at
$7.165 a troy ounce; gold was $3.10 to $3.90 higher with August at
$441.80 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures resumed the drought-driven trading
pattern of recent months, featuring sharply lower prices on
contracts for summer and fall delivery.
   Live cattle were unchanged to the limit 1.50 cents lower with
August at 64.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .60 cent to the
limit 1.50 cents lower with August at 74.22 cents a pound; hogs
were 1.30 cents lower to .93 cent higher with July at 44.75 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .52 cent to 1.57 cents higher with
July at 33.62 cents a pound.
   Cotton futures had a sharp negative reaction to the USDA crop
report, which boosted the prediction for the July 31, 1989, surplus
from 6.8 million bales to 7.4 million bales. On the New York Cotton
Exchange, cotton settled 1.49 cents to 1.82 cents lower with
October at 57.58 cents a pound.
   Crude oil prices skidded to a 21-month low on the New York
Mercantile Exchange amid pessimism about OPEC overproduction.
Gasoline futures plummeted on profit-taking, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 23 cents to 25 cents
lower with August at $14.44 a barrel; heating oil was .32 cent to
.67 cent lower with August at 40.14 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .75 cent to 3 cents lower with August at 50.48 cents a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's
500 index settled 2.05 points higher at 271.40.
</TEXT>
