<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PlantClosing 2ndLd-Writethru f0200 07-13 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Closing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0200,0901</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veto Showdown Looms On Plant-closing Bill Passed By House</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with House passing trade bill, INSERTS 1 graf after
6th graf pvs bgng, `I don't;' and DELETES now outdated 17th graf
pvs bgng, `The House'; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An election-year juggernaut to force employers
to give workers 60 days' notice before closing plants or ordering
large layoffs cleared the House on a 286-136 vote Wednesday,
setting up a likely veto showdown with President Reagan.
   Fifty-four Republicans abandoned the administration, giving the
White House nine fewer votes than the 145 _ or one third _
necessary to sustain a veto, assuming all 432 members vote.
   The legislation passed the Senate by a veto-proof 72-23 vote
last week. The House tally, if repeated exactly, also would be
sufficient to override a veto, but 10 members _ seven Democrats
including Speaker Jim Wright of Texas and three Republicans _ did
not vote. A veto override would require 288 votes if all members
voted.
   ``I suspect the president will veto it,'' said House Minority
Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill. ``The legislation is here to create an
issue, not because people are demanding it.''
   But former GOP opponents of the bill immediately began sending
signals to Reagan and Vice President George Bush, the party's sure
presidential nominee, not to press an issue that Democrats can use
in the November elections.
   ``I don't think he'll be able to sustain a veto,'' said Rep.
Marge Roukema, R-N.J. ``There are a lot more than 54 Republicans
who don't want him to veto it. We fought every fight; Bush is going
to have to handle the issue now.''
   Later Wednesday, the House passed on a 376-45 vote a massive
overhauling of the nation's trade laws that Reagan vetoed in May,
primarily because the layoff notices then were a part of it. Senate
leaders have said they do not anticipate acting on the trade bill
until early next month.
   With polls showing that more that 80 percent of voters support
mandated layoff notices, unions successfully persuaded Democratic
congressional leaders to attempt enacting the measure before
considering a revived trade bill that Reagan vetoed in May because
it included the notices.
   ``Today's House vote, coupled with last week's overwhelming
Senate margin, clearly gives the White House a strong message that
this bill should be signed,'' said AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland,
who called it an issue of fairness for workers.
   Business groups, however, said they are still counting on Reagan
for a veto.
   ``If he vetoed the trade bill because of it, I don't know why he
would turn around now,'' said Renee Reymond, the National
Association of Manufacturers' chief lobbyist on the issue.
   White House officials have pointed out that Reagan has not said
directly that he would veto layoff notices as a stand-alone bill,
although his senior advisers have said they would urge him to do so.
   Reagan cited the plant-closing language as his primary reason
for vetoing the overhauling of the nation's trade laws in May,
arguing that the notices would stifle competition by hamstringing
businesses in moments requiring quick action.
   ``These bills are linked because they have an effect on each
other,'' said Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich. ``I've got 5,000 workers
in Michigan whose trade readjustment assistance is running out this
week. There are a lot of people in this country who have not been a
part of this burgeoning economic miracle that some talk about.''
   Under the law, the president has 10 days _ excluding Sundays _
to sign the bill, veto it or allow it to become law without his
signature once it is delivered to the White House, expected
sometime next week.
   Bush supported Reagan's veto in May, saying he favors telling
workers in advance they are about to be laid off but that companies
shouldn't be forced by the government to do so.
   Democrats have seized on the issue to attack Reagan and Bush on
domestic economic issues.
   ``If Edwin Meese can give himself 30 days' notice, the least we
can do is give American workers 60 days' notice before we lay them
off,'' Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis said
Tuesday.
   Meese announced last week he would resign as attorney general,
but said he wouldn't actually depart until late this month or early
August.
   Rep. Silvio Conte, a liberal Massachusetts Republican and
co-sponsor of the measure, cited a General Accounting Office study
showing that the average layoff notice given workers in this
country is seven days.
   ``It takes two months to get a worker readjustment program going
at a plant,'' Conte said. ``Most of the heartache of losing a job
could be avoided if companies just give workers enough notice to
readjust their lives.''
   Layoff notices have been required in Canada, Japan and most
European countries for years. And a 1986 study by the congressional
Office of Technology Assistance found little opposition to them in
those foreign settings by subsidiaries of American-owned companies.
   But business groups feared a victory for the AFL-CIO on the
plant closing and layoff notices will open a Pandora's box of other
labor legislation such as mandated health benefits, maternity
leaves and measures making it easier for unions to organize workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1904EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade 2ndLd-Writethru   07-13 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0783</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 3 grafs new to update with partisan breakdown, leaders
predict Reagan will sign; pickup 3rd graf pvs: Earlier in; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed 376-45 on Wednesday a
revamped version of its massive trade bill, now largely tailored to
conditions set by President Reagan when he vetoed the original in
May.
   ``The best protection for our economic future is this trade
bill,'' Ways and Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowksi, D-Ill., declared
in a two-hour debate.
   Only 41 Republicans and four Democrats held out against the
1,000-page bill. Leaders of both parties said Reagan will sign the
bill if the Senate passes it in its current form.
   Earlier in the afternoon, the House passed 286-136 a separate
bill to force employers to give 60 days advance notice to workers
of plant closings and major layoffs. That was a feature of the
initial trade bill and was cited by Reagan as the basis for his
veto.
   Even the severest critics of the trade legislation conceded it
was headed for law. Rep. William Frenzel, R-Minn., declared he was
``not a fan'' of the measure but urged the House to go ahead and
pass it ``rather than fooling around with trade'' when it should be
focusing on the budget deficit.
   Before acting on the bill itself, the House rejected 237-183 an
attempt to delete the measure's provisions for duty-free imports of
ethanol produced at Caribbean refineries from European and
Brazilian base products.
   Ethanol is fuel produced from a variety of farm products,
notably corn. The provision came under attack from House Minority
Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill, whose district includes huge corn
refineries.
   Rep. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said the measure punishes ``these
drought-stricken farmers as much as the searing sun.'' Critics
scoffed at the Michel-Durbin proposal as a delaying tactic. Rep.
Robert Matsui, D-Calif., said the provision would help consumers by
assuring a reliable supply of ethanol at reasonable prices.
   ``Unfortunately what you are hoping for is some excess profits
out of it,'' Matsui said.
   The plant-closings plan was but one part of the trade bill
passed in May, but President Reagan singled it out for criticism in
his veto. He said it would rob managers of the flexibility to
operate their companies at peak economic health. Sponsors say
warning family breadwinners of impending layoffs is the decent and
compassionate thing to do.
   Declaring their intent to meet Reagan's objections, Democratic
leaders split off the plant-losings provision and reconstituted it
as a separate bill. They also dropped new curbs on exports of
Alaska oil.
   The measures remain closely tied together, however, and came to
the House floor under a rule that required the chamber to take up
plant closings first and then go immediately to trade. It reflected
a move by congressional leaders to ease the concerns of union
officials over separating the issues.
   The trade bill was expected to come to the floor in the Senate
at an unspecified time after next week's Democratic National
Convention.
   Some Democrats say Gov. Michael Dukakis' choice of Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, D-Texas, as his running mate on the national Democratic
ticket provides all the more reason to push ahead with the trade
bill.
   Bentsen is chief Senate sponsor of the measure and placing the
bill on Reagan's desk at the opening of the presidential campaign
might be expected to lend a note of drama to the issue.
   Renewed congressional action on what House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, described as ``the trade and jobs bill'' follows a June
unemployment rate of 5.3 percent, a 14-year low, and an April
merchandise trade deficit of $9.9 billion, the lowest since
December 1984.
   The administration has been hoping since September 1984 to pound
a massive dent in the trade deficit by lowering the dollar, thus
raising the cost of imports while making it easier to sell U.S.
products overseas. There is no way to forecast what May trade
figures due Friday will show, but the red ink for February was
$14.4 billion and for March was $11.9 billion.
   Provisions of the bill would grant the administration authority
to reach agreements in the current Uruguay Round of international
trade talks and guarantee them speeded up consideration by Congress
with no amendments.
   Procedures under which the United States imposes import curbs to
protect U.S. industries and retaliate against trade violations
would be streamlined under the measure. Other features range from
repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil company earnings to as
much as $2 billion in agricultural subsidies.
</TEXT>
