<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-CBS     07-13 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-CBS,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Posts 40 Percent Profit Rise in 2nd Qtr</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CBS Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. said Wednesday its profit for the
second quarter climbed 40 percent from a year ago, citing
improvement by its broadcast group despite a sluggish advertising
market, a rise in interest income and the effects of cost-cutting.
   But the company said the outlook for the rest of the year
remained clouded due to the continuing strike by the Writers Guild
of America, which could reduce the amount of new programming
available for the fall television season.
   CBS said it earned $128.7 million, or $5.01 a share, in the
three months ended June 30, compared with an after-tax profit of
$92.1 million, or $3.77 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 4
percent to $740 million from $714 million.
   For the first six months of the year, CBS earned $1.04 billion,
or $40.43 a share, up about sevenfold from $140.8 million, or $5.70
a share, a year earlier. Revenues were unchanged at $1.44 billion.
   The latest six-month results included a one-time gain of $866.6
million from the sale of the CBS magazine and record groups.
   Laurence A. Tisch, president and chief executive, said income
from continuing operations and net income were the highest in the
company's history.
   ``The CBS Broadcast Group scored higher sales in spite of a
sluggish advertising market, and improved its operating margin,
underscoring the effectiveness of ongoing efforts to reduce costs
and improve operating efficiences,'' he said.
   He said sales and profits rose at the CBS Television network,
the CBS television stations and the CBS radio division. The
television network benefitted from sports programming, which
included the championship events of college and professional
basketball.
   Net corporate interest income climbed to $43.9 million in the
quarter from $6.7 million a year earlier, reflecting investment of
proceeds from the company's recent asset sales.
</TEXT>
