<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has
told Congress that the central bank stands ready to push interest
rates higher to stem inflation.
   Greenspan said Wednesday that the risks of a new wage-price
spiral are ``sufficiently great'' that the Fed should tighten
credit rather than stimulate the economy.
   In his mid-year report on monetary policy, Greenspan said the
Fed already has made a series of small credit-tightening steps from
late March through late June, allowing short term interest rates to
rise.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. has announced a management shakeup that
has the president of CBS News becoming president of the broadcast
group and will for the first time bring in an outsider to head the
CBS news division.
   Effective Aug. 1, news division head Howard Stringer replaces
Gene F. Jankowski, who has been president of the broadcast group
for 11 years, the network announced Wednesday.
   Succeeding Stringer as president of CBS News will be David
Burke, who has been with ABC News for 11 years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A measure to force employers to give workers
60 days notice before closing plants or ordering large layoffs has
cleared the House on a 286-136 vote, setting up a likely veto
showdown with President Reagan.
   Fifty-four Republicans abandoned the administration, giving the
White House 9 fewer votes than the 145 needed to sustain a veto,
assuming all 432 members vote.
   The legislation passed the Senate by a veto-proof 72-23 vote
last week. The House tally on Wednesday, if repeated exactly, also
would be sufficient to override a veto, but 10 members _ seven
Democrats including Speaker Jim Wright of Texas and three
Republicans _ did not vote.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's is opening restaurants in
hospitals, in what one doctor suggests is an invitation to a Big
Mac heart attack. But a hospital spokesman argues the food ``hasn't
killed anyone yet.''
   The fast food chain has opened eight such restaurants
nationwide. One more is under construction at Dayton Children's
Hospital in Ohio, and four are under contract, said Steven Roth,
McDonald's manager of hospital development.
   Dr. Michael Goldblatt, McDonald's staff nutritionist, said
Wednesday that the restaurants supplement hospitals' regular food
services and are aimed at staff and visitors, not patients.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines says it has made new conciliatory
offers to its Machinists and pilots union, although the financially
pressed carrier is still trying to slash overall labor costs.
   The proposals made this month would save Eastern an estimated
$229 million annually, the airline said Wednesday.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said management's proposal to
the pilots includes protection of salaries, days off and job
security. She said it also contains a ``fence agreement''
guaranteeing that Eastern would remain separate from Continental
Airlines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic car sales rose at No. 3 Chrysler Corp.
but fell at General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. during the
first 10 days of July, reflecting fewer incentive offerings.
   Domestic light truck sales climbed by 8.6 percent on a daily
average, slightly outweighing an overall 1.6 percent slide in daily
sales of U.S. made cars, the automakers reported Wednesday.
   Combined car and light truck sales totaled 228,870 for the seven
sales days in the July 1-10 period, and the combined daily sales
rate was up 2 percent from the comparable 1987 period, which
contained eight days.
</TEXT>
