<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CopyrightLawsuit     07-13 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copyright Lawsuit,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard Countersues Apple Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co., responding to Apple
Computer Inc.'s copyright infringement suit, filed a countersuit in
a federal court Wednesday alleging unfair business practices by
Apple and violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
   Hewlett-Packard, based in Palo Alto, Calif., denied all of
Apple's allegations and asked the U.S. District Court in San Jose
to invalidate Apple's copyrights in the case and to dismiss its
suit against Hewlett-Packard.
   ``(Hewlett-Packard) is confident the court will agree Apple's
suit has no merit,'' said Douglas C. Chance, executive vice
president of the company's Business Systems Sector.
   Apple, based in Cupertino, Calif., sued Hewlett-Packard and
Microsoft Corp. of Redmond, Wash., in March, charging them with
copyright infringement in two so-called ``operating environment''
programs: Microsoft's Windows and Hewlett-Packard's NewWave.
   Operating environment programs provide a visual ``desktop'' on
the screen, on which a computer user can view various symbols
representing documents, applications programs and places to store
information.
   Apple's suit shook software developers and computer makers
throughout the industry because of its potential scope. Besides
taking aim at Hewlett-Packard and Microsoft, Apple also indirectly
challenged its biggest rival, International Business Machines
Corp., which has been incorporating display graphics similar to
Apple's.
   Apple was seen as essentially asking the court to preserve a
technological edge it has enjoyed over its competitors, just as the
rivals were starting to close the gap.
   In April, Microsoft submitted a response to the court in San
Jose, charging that Apple violated contracts, acted in bad faith
and damaged Microsoft's relations with other companies.
   Microsoft denied that its Windows product infringed on Apple
copyrights by using images that too closely resembled the ``look
and feel'' of Apple's popular Macintosh computer.
   Hewlett-Packard claimed in its countersuit that Apple does not
hold valid copyrights for the visual displays and images because
Apple did not originate them.
   ``By claiming sole authorship of those displays and images,
Apple misled the U.S. Copyright Office in order to stifle
competition and hamper (Hewlett-Packard), Microsoft and others from
entering a market _ graphical user-interface operating environments
for personal computers _ that Apple dominates,'' Hewlett-Packard
said in a statement.
   Hewlett-Packard also said ``Apple misled the court and the
public by altering Hewlett-Packard screen images to create the
false impression that they are similar to the Apple Macintosh.
   ``(Hewlett-Packard) believes Apple's real concern is not that
some features of NewWave resemble those of the Macintosh, but that
NewWave delivers what Apple itself has described as its vision of
the future.''
   On Monday, the court granted Hewlett-Packard's motion to
disqualify the Palo Alto-based law firm of Fenwick, Davis and West
from representing Apple. Hewlett-Packard claimed that the firm had
previously worked for it and should not be allowed to participate
in a suit between the companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LTVPensions     07-13 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LTV Pensions,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agency Takes over LTV Pension Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp. announced Wednesday that Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corp. will resume control of three of the Dallas-based
company's pension plans and their assets.
   The plans have been the subject of dispute between the steel and
energy company, which is reorganizing under federal bankruptcy
protection from creditors, and the PBGC, a government agency that
insures pension benefits.
   The PBGC took over LTV's steel company pension plans, which were
$2 billion in debt, in January 1987 after the company terminated
them, making the agnency LTV's biggest creditor.
   But the agency attempted to restore LTV's responsibility for the
plans the following September, after a new LTV labor contract with
the United Steelworkers of America restored some benefits
previously cut.
   A federal judge on June 22 in Manhattan refused to uphold PBGC's
decision to force LTV to reassume the pension obligations, stating
that the agency had not presented a good enough case for the move.
   LTV has contended since filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection two years ago that it can not successfully reorganize if
it is held responsible for the $2 billion shortfall of the pension
plans.
   Company officials said the resumption of PBGC responsibility
should not affect LTV Steel retirees or their benefits. Officials
said they will work with the PBGC to assure payments continue
during the transition period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GM-Airbags     07-13 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM-Airbags,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stempel: GM To Offer Air Bags Standard By 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILFORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. will install
driver-side air bags as standard equipment on 500,000 cars a year
by 1990 because ``they aren't selling like hotcakes'' as costly
options, GM's president said Wednesday.
   Robert Stempel said GM will not begin phasing in passenger-side
air bags until 1990, unlike some of its competitors, and will not
include them as standard equipment until 1992 because the
technology still is being developed.
   Stempel also said GM would include rear lap-and-shoulder belts
as standard equipment on all 1989 models. He said automakers did
not include rear shoulder belts previously because they had
believed passengers were safer in the back seat than in the front
seat and needed less restraint.
   The federal government requires automakers to have passive
restraints _ automatic shoulder belts or driver-side air bags
combined with manual shoulder-lap belts _ by 1990. The regulation
requires passive restraints on an increasing percentage of each
maker's vehicles each year until 1990, but leaves makers the
discretion to offer them as standard equipment or as options.
   Chrysler Corp. has said it would include air bags as standard
equipment on all its U.S.-produced models by 1990 and will use
automatic belts on its smaller, imported models.
   Ford Motor Co. and GM will use a more even mix of air bags and
automatic belts than Chrysler. Ford has had some success offering
air bags as options but also will make them standard on many
vehicles.
   Stempel spoke at the 20th anniversary of the GM Research and
Development Laboratory at GM's 4,000-acre Milford proving ground,
where vehicle research includes in-depth safety studies that have
produced such new devices as the self-aligning steering wheel.
   The new safety steering wheel, which is being introduced on the
1989 Chevrolet Cavalier, is a hollow hub on six metal tabs that
collapse on impact to flatten the wheel against the driver's torso,
evenly distributing impact force across the entire wheel to reduce
potential face and chest injuries.
   The wheel, developed by four GM engineers, is effective but not
costly and will be phased in on other cars not equipped with air
bags, primarily economy cars. Stempel said he believed buyers of
cheaper cars were less likely to accept the added cost of an air
bag.
   He said GM will make air bags standard only on its middle- and
upper-price range vehicles, because those buyers are more willing
to shoulder the air bag cost. But if they are given a choice, they
also tend to ignore the air bags, he said.
   ``Oldsmobiles with air bags are not selling like hotcakes. By
themselves, they don't seem to be a saleable feature,'' Stempel
said. ``Most people don't buy a car thinking they are going to be
in an accident.
   ``We'll have to move toward standard installation of air bags to
get them in there in any number.''
   For 1989, GM will offer driver-side air bags on the Oldsmobile
Delta 88 and 98 and the Cadillac DeVille, Fleetwood and Fleetwood
60 Special, Stempel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880713-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Brokerages     07-13 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Brokerages,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Boston Posts Second Quarter Profit Following Year-Earlier
Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Boston Inc. posted a second-quarter profit
of $43.7 million on Wednesday, compared with a $13.2 million loss
in the same period a year earlier.
   Earnings for the investment banking firm, which amounted to
$1.20 per share, stemmed partly from strong merger and acquisition
activity, according to Peter T. Buchanan, First Boston's president
and chief executive officer.
   The firm reported revenue of $365.5 million, up 80 percent from
$202.6 million a year earlier, for the three months ended June 30.
   The year-earlier loss stemmed largely from losses in bond
trading, particularly in volatile options on 30-year Treasury
bonds. First Boston and other firms lost millions of dollars when
bond prices plummeted in April 1987 over speculation that the
then-weakening dollar would reignite high inflation.
   During the latest quarter, revenue from principal transactions _
those conducted for its own account _ jumped to $88.5 million from
a loss of $108.4 million a year earlier, the firm reported.
   Commission revenue fell to $31.8 million from $41.6 million,
while investment banking revenue rose to $261.4 million from $245.4
million.
   For the six months ended June 30, First Boston posted a profit
of $85.7 million, or $2.37 per share, up from $63 million, or $1.79
per share, for the same period last year.
   Revenue rose to $704.7 million in the first half from $685.9
million in the year-earlier period.
</TEXT>
