<2ND_LINE>BC-York International,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bidding Battle for Air Conditioning Company Heats Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas-based air conditioning equipment maker
has offered about $795 million to acquire York International Corp.,
which already has agreed to a $750 million buyout led by Citicorp,
York announced Wednesday.
   SnyderGeneral Corp., which is based in Dallas, offered $61 a
share to acquire York, which also manufactures heating and air
conditioning equipment.
   Late last month, York agreed to be acquired by York Holdings
Corp., a new group capitalized by Citicorp Capital Investors Ltd.
and other investors, for $57.50 a share in cash and debentures, or
a total of about $750 million. The investor group began its tender
offer on July 1.
   York International stock rose $3.25 to $59.12{ a share Wednesday
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Officials from Citicorp, York International and SnyderGeneral
would not comment on the competing offer.
   More than a dozen suits have been filed by shareholders who say
the Citicorp-led offer of $57.50 per share offer is too small. The
suits, which name York International, members of its board, York
Holdings and others as defendants, are aimed at stopping the sale,
according to Securities and Exchange Commission documents.
   SnyderGeneral is a privately-held company that employs about
4,800 people at nine facilities, including two in Europe.
   York International employs 1,600 people. It was a division of
Borg-Warner Corp. until it was spun off to stockholders in 1986.
</TEXT>
